{"title_page": "Robert Maclagan", "text_new": "{{about|the Scottish military engineer|his nephew, the Scottish physician and folklorist|Robert Craig Maclagan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}\n[[File:Robert_Maclagan.jpg|thumb]]\nGeneral '''Sir Robert Maclagan''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG|FRSE|FRGS}} (14 December 1820 \u2013 1894) was a [[British Army]] officer and military engineer. He served most of his career in India.\n\n==Life==\n\nHe was born on 14 December 1820 the son of Jane Whiteside and her husband, the eminent Edinburgh physician [[David Maclagan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/General-Sir-Robert-Maclagan-KCMG/6000000002889135091|title=General Sir Robert Maclagan, KCMG|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref> His childhood home was 22 George Street in the centre of [[New Town, Edinburgh|Edinburgh\u2019s New Town]].<ref>Edinburgh and Leith Post Office Directory 1820-21</ref>\n\nHe was educated at the [[Royal High School, Edinburgh|High School]] in Edinburgh and the [[University of Edinburgh]] but did not graduate. He then went to [[Addiscombe Military Seminary]] near [[London]]. He joined the Honourable [[East India Company]] as a 2nd Lieutenant in 1839. He then went to the School of Military Engineering in Chatham, to specialise as an engineer. He arrived in [[Delhi]] in India in 1842. He was in charge of the engineering works for the defence of [[Lahore]] in March 1846. Following severe illness he was given more sedate duties, including running the Civil Engineering College at [[Rurki]] aged 27. In the Mutiny of 1857 he successfully defended Rurki against the rebel forces. In his military career he rose to the rank of General, first in the Bengal Engineers then in the [[Royal Engineers]].<ref>https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/S037016460004904X</ref>\n\nIn 1853 he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]] his proposer being [[Robert Christison|Sir Robert Christison]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0 902 198 84 X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1861 he ran the Public Works Department for all of the [[Punjab]]. [[Queen Victoria]] created him a Knight of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) for his efforts.\n\nHe retired in 1879. He spent most of his final years between Edinburgh and London.\n\nHe died in 1894.\n\n==Family==\nHis brothers included [[Andrew Douglas Maclagan]] and Rev [[William Maclagan]], Archbishop of York.\n\nHis children included Robert Smeiton Maclagan CIE, Sir Edward Douglas Maclagan KCIE.\n\nHe was uncle to [[Robert Craig Maclagan]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maclagan, Robert}}\n[[Category:1820 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:Scottish engineers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Scottish military engineer|his nephew, the Scottish physician and folklorist|Robert Craig Maclagan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}\n[[File:Robert_Maclagan.jpg|thumb]]\nGeneral '''Sir Robert Maclagan''' [[FRSE]] [[FRGS]] [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]] LLD (14 December 1820 \u2013 1894) was a [[British Army]] officer and military engineer. He served most of his career in India.\n\n==Life==\n\nHe was born on 14 December 1820 the son of Jane Whiteside and her husband, the eminent Edinburgh physician [[David Maclagan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/General-Sir-Robert-Maclagan-KCMG/6000000002889135091|title=General Sir Robert Maclagan, KCMG|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref> His childhood home was 22 George Street in the centre of [[New Town, Edinburgh|Edinburgh\u2019s New Town]].<ref>Edinburgh and Leith Post Office Directory 1820-21</ref>\n\nHe was educated at the [[Royal High School, Edinburgh|High School]] in Edinburgh and the [[University of Edinburgh]] but did not graduate. He then went to [[Addiscombe Military Seminary]] near [[London]]. He joined the Honourable [[East India Company]] as a 2nd Lieutenant in 1839. He then went to the School of Military Engineering in Chatham, to specialise as an engineer. He arrived in [[Delhi]] in India in 1842. He was in charge of the engineering works for the defence of [[Lahore]] in March 1846. Following severe illness he was given more sedate duties, including running the Civil Engineering College at [[Rurki]] aged 27. In the Mutiny of 1857 he successfully defended Rurki against the rebel forces. In his military career he rose to the rank of General, first in the Bengal Engineers then in the [[Royal Engineers]].<ref>https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/S037016460004904X</ref>\n\nIn 1853 he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]] his proposer being [[Robert Christison|Sir Robert Christison]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0 902 198 84 X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1861 he ran the Public Works Department for all of the [[Punjab]]. [[Queen Victoria]] created him a Knight of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) for his efforts.\n\nHe retired in 1879. He spent most of his final years between Edinburgh and London.\n\nHe died in 1894.\n\n==Family==\nHis brothers included [[Andrew Douglas Maclagan]] and Rev [[William Maclagan]], Archbishop of York.\n\nHis children included Robert Smeiton Maclagan CIE, Sir Edward Douglas Maclagan KCIE.\n\nHe was uncle to [[Robert Craig Maclagan]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maclagan, Robert}}\n[[Category:1820 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:Scottish engineers]]\n", "name_user": "Necrothesp", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Maclagan"}
{"title_page": "Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market", "text_new": "{{about|the 2019 Directive|the 2001 Directive|Information Society Directive}}\n{{short description|2019 EU copyright reform directive}}\n{{use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox EU legislation\n| number              = 2019/790\n| type                = directive\n| EEA                 = yes\n| title               = Directive (EU) 2019/790 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 17 April 2019 on copyright and related rights in the Digital Single Market and amending Directives 96/9/EC and 2001/29/EC\n| Parties             = \n| madeby              = \n| madeunder           = Articles 53(1), 62 and 114\n| OJrefurl            = \n| OJref               = [https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=OJ:L:2019:130:TOC L 130, 17 May 2019]\n| EEATreaty           = \n| EEADec              = \n| made                = {{dts|17 April 2019}}\n| commenced           = {{dts|6 June 2019}}\n| implementation      = within 2 years after coming into force\n| EPVote={{Composition bar|348|622|hex=#00FF00}}\n| application         = \n| CommProp            = \n| ESCOpin             = \n| CROpin              = \n| ParlOpin            = \n| Reports             = \n| replaces            = \n| amends              = [[Database Directive]] (Directive 96/9)<br>[[Information Society Directive]] (Directive 2001/29/EC)\n| amendedby           = \n| replacedby          = \n| status              = in force (implementation pending)\n}}\nThe '''Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market''', formally the '''Directive (EU) 2019/790 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 17 April 2019 on copyright and related rights in the Digital Single Market and amending Directives 96/9/EC and 2001/29/EC''' is a [[European Union]] (EU) [[Directive (European Union)|directive]] which has been adopted and came into force on 7 June 2019. It is intended to ensure \"a well-functioning marketplace for copyright\".<ref name=\"EC2016\">{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A52016PC0593|title=Proposal for a Directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on copyright in the Digital Single Market|author=[[European Commission]]|date=14 September 2016|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623032844/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A52016PC0593|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It extends existing [[copyright law of the European Union|European Union copyright law]] and is a component of the EU's [[Digital Single Market]] project.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/eu-copyright-legislation |title=The EU copyright legislation |author=European Commission |access-date=4 July 2018 |date=28 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705032942/https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/eu-copyright-legislation |archive-date=5 July 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The [[European Council]] (EC) describes their key goals with the Directive as protecting press publications; reducing the \"value gap\" between the profits made by Internet platforms and by content creators; encouraging collaboration between these two groups, and creating [[copyright exceptions]] for [[text and data mining|text- and data-mining]].<ref name=\"EUJune252\">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|title=Copyright rules for the digital environment: Council agrees its position \u2013 Consilium|publisher=Europa (web portal)|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613171238/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|archive-date=13 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe directive was introduced by the [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] on 20 June 2018, and a revised proposal was approved by the parliament on 12 September 2018. The final version, which resulted from negotiations during [[formal trilogue meeting]]s, was presented to the parliament on 13 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU reaches provisional deal on online copyright reform |url=http://afp.omni.se/eu-reaches-provisional-deal-on-online-copyright-reform/a/Eo11J3 |website=afp.omni.se |accessdate=14 February 2019 |language=sv |date=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214233336/http://afp.omni.se/eu-reaches-provisional-deal-on-online-copyright-reform/a/Eo11J3 |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The measure was approved by on 26 March 2019<ref name=\"wired-13pass\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/eu-article-13-passed-meme-war|title=The EU has passed Article 13, but Europe's meme war is far from over|last=Volpicelli|first=Gian|access-date=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912151840/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/eu-article-13-passed-meme-war|archive-date=12 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"verge finalvote mar19\">{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/26/18280726/europe-copyright-directive | title=  Europe\u2019s controversial overhaul of online copyright receives final approval | first =James | last =Vincent | date = 26 March 2019 | accessdate = 26 March 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-47708144|title=EU backs controversial copyright law|last=Kleinman|first=Zoe|date=2019-03-26|work=BBC|access-date=2019-03-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the directive was approved by the [[Council of the European Union]] on 15 April 2019.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/15/article-13-eu-council-backs-copyright-law-that-could-hit-youtube-fb.html|title=Article 13: EU Council backs copyright law that could hit YouTube, FB|last=Browne|first=Ryan|date=2019-04-15|website=CNBC|access-date=2019-04-15}}</ref> Member states have two years to pass appropriate legislation to meet the Directive's requirements.<ref name=\"internationalinsider.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://internationalinsider.org/2019/10/15/digital-single-market-copyright-directive-eu-to-start-dialogue-with-stakeholder/|title=Digital Single Market Copyright Directive: EU to start dialogue with stakeholder|date=2019-10-15|website=International Insider|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\nCopyright guarantees that writers, composers, musicians, filmmakers and other creators are acknowledged, compensated and protected for their work.<ref name=\"internationalinsider.org\"/>\n\nThe directive has generally been supported by newspapers, publishers, and media groups but opposed by major tech companies and some Internet users, as well as human rights advocates. Two of the Directive's articles have drawn significant discussion. Draft Article 11 (Article 15 of the directive), known as the \"link tax\", gives newspapers more direct control and re-use of their product, which may impact some Internet services like [[news aggregator]]s. Draft Article 13 (Article 17 of the directive) tasks service providers that host [[user-generated content]] to employ \"effective and proportionate\" measures to prevent users from violating copyright. Tech companies expressed concern that this would necessitate the need for upload filters at their current scales. A broad concern with the Directive is on the use of [[fair dealing]] through the directive, and that it could quell freedom of speech.\n\n== History ==\n===Background===\nThe European Union's (EU) first attempt to unify copyrights in light of digital technologies was adopted in 2001 as the [[Information Society Directive|Information Society Directive 2001/29/EC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-01-528_en.htm|title=Commission welcomes adoption of the Directive on copyright in the information society by the Council|author=[[European Commission]]|date=4 July 2018|access-date=4 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705062644/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-01-528_en.htm|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The Directive's major objectives were to harmonise EU legislation with international law (as set by the 1996 [[World Intellectual Property Organization]] treaties), to strengthen intellectual property protection, to reduce conflicts in copyright laws between member states, and to assure adequate remuneration to content producers.<ref name=\"CESP 2015\">{{cite report | url = https://www.ceps.eu/system/files/SR120_0.pdf | title = The Implementation, Application and Effects of the EU Directive on Copyright in the Information Society | author1 = Andrea Renda | author2 = Felice Simonelli | author3 = Giuseppe Mazziotti | author4 = Alberto Bolognini | author5 = Giacomo Luchetta | publisher = [[Centre for European Policy Studies]] | date = November 2015 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180913223259/https://www.ceps.eu/system/files/SR120_0.pdf | archivedate = 13 September 2018 | url-status = live}}</ref> While some parts of the 2001 Directive were effective, other parts of the directive were not satisfactory for the current digital market long after its implementation. In 2012, the [[European Commission]] (EC) announced that they would be reviewing the 2001 Directive and having stakeholder discussions in light of several issues raised with failed copyright proposals from those in the [[European Commissioner for Internal Market and Services]] position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/battle-on-eu-copyright-law-re-opened-by-commission/|title=Battle on EU copyright law re-opened by Commission|date=5 December 2012|work=POLITICO|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005238/https://www.politico.eu/article/battle-on-eu-copyright-law-re-opened-by-commission/|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The EC took public comments from December 2013 through March 2014, and published its first report on the state of the EU copyright law in July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/internal_market/consultations/2013/copyright-rules/docs/contributions/consultation-report_en.pdf|title=Report on the responses to the Public Consultation on the Review of the EU Copyright Rules|last=Directorate General Internal Market and Services Directorate D \u2013 Intellectual property D1|date=July 2014|url-status=live|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005034/http://ec.europa.eu/internal_market/consultations/2013/copyright-rules/docs/contributions/consultation-report_en.pdf|archive-date=23 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] was elected to the [[President of the European Commission|presidency of the European Commission]] and took office in November 2014.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-27679170 | title = Profile: EU's Jean-Claude Juncker | date = 15 July 2014 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = BBC | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181101003046/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-27679170 | archive-date = 1 November 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In his campaign position, Juncker saw the potential to \"improve\" the EU's financial status by harmonising the various digital marketplaces among member nations to create job opportunities and drive a knowledge-based society. Juncker appointed Estonian politician, [[Andrus Ansip]], as Vice-President for the Digital Single Market within the EC that year, tasked with working with [[G\u00fcnther Oettinger]], [[European Commissioner for Digital Economy and Society]], and other sections within the EC to come up with the necessary legislative steps that would be required to implement a Digital Single Market.<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-523_en.htm | title = Questions and Answers: The Juncker Commission | date = 10 September 2014 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = [[European Commission]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180827115040/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-523_en.htm | archive-date = 27 August 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Initial plans for the legislative steps and their potential impact were announced by the EC in May 2015. Ansip stated that by the implementation of a Digital Single Market, they could increase the European [[gross domestic product]] by as much as {{\u20ac|415{{nbsp}}billion|link=yes}} per year.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/may/06/eu-unveils-plans-digital-single-market-online-firms | title = EU unveils plans to set up digital single market for online firms | first = Ian | last = Traynor | date = 6 May 2015 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | work = [[The Guardian]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180704093514/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/may/06/eu-unveils-plans-digital-single-market-online-firms | archive-date = 4 July 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?qid=1447773803386&uri=CELEX:52015DC0192|title=Communication from the Commission to the European Parliament, the Council, the European Economic and Social Committee and the Committee of the Regions \u2013 A Digital Single Market Strategy for Europe|date=6 May 2015|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|series=COM/2015/0192|url-status=live|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623004904/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?qid=1447773803386&uri=CELEX:52015DC0192|archive-date=23 June 2018}}</ref> The [[European Parliament]], following up on a report on the state of European Copyright from a [[member of the European Parliament]] (MEP), [[Julia Reda]], that identified several inadequacies of the 2001 Information Society Directive, affirmed support for the EC's goal of a Digital Single Market as well as supporting an initiative with the EP for similar copyright reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&reference=P8-TA-2015-0273&language=EN&ring=A8-2015-0209|title=European Parliament resolution of 9 July 2015 on the implementation of Directive 2001/29/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 22 May 2001 on the harmonisation of certain aspects of copyright and related rights in the information society (2014/2256(INI))|date=9 July 2015|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142725/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&reference=P8-TA-2015-0273&language=EN&ring=A8-2015-0209|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The EC subsequently began working on establishing the legal framework by the end of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=COM:2015:626:FIN|title=Communication from the Commission to the European Parliament, the Council, the European Economic and Social Committee and the Committee of the Regions \u2013 Towards a modern, more European copyright framework|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|series=COM/2015/0626|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623032857/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=COM:2015:626:FIN}}</ref>\n\n===Legislative process===\n[[File:Vote on the new Copyright regulation (46754387104).jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Approval of the measure by the European Parliament in [[Strasbourg]], 26 March 2019]]\n\nThe directive fell within the [[ordinary legislative procedure]], and thus was to be approved by both the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union. While the European Parliament had to pass the Directive with a simple majority, in the Council a [[qualified majority]] was needed: at least 55% of the countries, representing over 65% of the population.\n\nThe first draft of the proposed Directive from the EC was issued on 14 September 2016,<ref>{{cite report | url = https://ec.europa.eu/transparency/regdoc/rep/1/2016/EN/1-2016-593-EN-F1-1.PDF | title = Proposal for a Directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on Copyright in the Digital Single Market | date = 14 September 2016 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = [[European Commission]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180822171925/http://ec.europa.eu/transparency/regdoc/rep/1/2016/EN/1-2016-593-EN-F1-1.PDF | archivedate = 22 August 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Following revisions, the [[Council of the European Union]]'s [[Committee of Permanent Representatives]] (COREPER) approved of the EC's legislative directives on 25 May 2018 and prepared to bring the matter to vote in the EP,<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35373/st09134-en18.pdf|title=Proposal for a directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market|date=25 May 2018|page=26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609084910/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35373/st09134-en18.pdf|archive-date=9 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> to reach a final text, without the support of Germany, Finland, the Netherlands, Slovenia, Belgium, or Hungary.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=22 June 2018|title=EU Council agrees Copyright Directive position|url=https://www.create.ac.uk/eu-council-agrees-copyright-directive-position/|newspaper=CREATe|date=29 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623004703/https://www.create.ac.uk/eu-council-agrees-copyright-directive-position/|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] finalised their amendments to the directive on 20 June 2018 and put them toward the parliament for negotiation.<ref name=\"EUJune25\">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|title=Copyright rules for the digital environment: Council agrees its position|date=25 May 2018|publisher=[[European Council]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613171238/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|archive-date=13 June 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]] voted on 5 July 2018 not to proceed to the negotiation stage, but instead to reopen the directive for debate in September 2018.<ref name=\"theguardianeuvote\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|title=YouTube and Facebook escape billions in copyright payouts after EU vote|last=Sweney|first=Mark|last2=Rankin|first2=Jennifer|date=5 July 2018|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|access-date=5 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724094528/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"rejectjuly-5-2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=MEPs reject EU copyright reforms in victory for internet giants|last=Khan|first=Mehreen|date=5 July 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234046/https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref> There were 318 votes to re-open the debate, 278 to proceed, and 31 abstentions.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44712475|title=EU's controversial copyright plan rejected|date=5 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705230728/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44712475|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/eu-parlament-zu-urheberrecht-umstrittene-reform-ueberraschend-ausgebremst-a-1216741.html |title=EU-Parlament bremst Urheberrechtsreform aus |access-date=6 July 2018 |date=5 July 2018 |last=B\u00f6hm |first=Markus |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706071756/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/eu-parlament-zu-urheberrecht-umstrittene-reform-ueberraschend-ausgebremst-a-1216741.html |archive-date=6 July 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 September 2018, an updated position of the parliament was approved with the final vote being 438{{Nbsp}}in favour and 226{{Nbsp}}against,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/12/17849868/eu-internet-copyright-reform-article-11-13-approved|title=EU approves controversial Copyright Directive, including internet 'link tax' and 'upload filter'|date=12 September 2018|last=Vincent|first=James|website=The Verge|accessdate=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912113116/https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/12/17849868/eu-internet-copyright-reform-article-11-13-approved|archive-date=12 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> meaning that [[Formal trilogue meeting|trilogue negotiations]] can start between the [[European Commission]], the [[Council of the European Union]] and the [[European Parliament]], with an expected conclusion in early 2019. Should the three groups agree to the final language, then the directive will be sent to governments of the twenty-eight{{Nbsp}}member states to be passed as laws within those countries, with each country formalising certain processes as necessary to meet their existing laws.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/09/european-parliament-approves-copyright-bill-slammed-by-digital-rights-groups/ | title = What's in the sweeping copyright bill just passed by the European Parliament | first = Timothy | last = Lee | date = 12 September 2018 | accessdate = 12 September 2018 | work = [[Ars Technica]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180912163937/https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/09/european-parliament-approves-copyright-bill-slammed-by-digital-rights-groups/ | archive-date = 12 September 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nInitial trilogue meetings overseen by Romania were scheduled to start on 21 January 2019, however, on 19 January 2019, Romania cancelled these meetings following the rejection of Romania's proposed compromise text by eleven countries: Germany, Belgium, the Netherlands, Finland, Slovenia, Italy, [[Poland]], Sweden, Croatia, Luxembourg and Portugal. With the exclusion of Portugal and Croatia, the other nine countries rejected the compromised text for Articles 11 and/or 13 stating that the measures did not do enough to do to protect their citizens' copyright protections. Romania had the opportunity to revise their text to gain a majority vote, delaying the vote.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.engadget.com/2019/01/19/eu-copyright-directive-rejected-at-council/ | title = EU copyright laws face uncertain fate after 11 countries reject proposal | first = Jon | last = Fingas | date = 19 January 2019 | accessdate = 19 January 2019 | work = [[Engadget]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190120074753/https://www.engadget.com/2019/01/19/eu-copyright-directive-rejected-at-council/ | archive-date = 20 January 2019 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe trilogue negotiations were completed on 13 February 2019, the final text still retaining the controversial Articles 11 and 13.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20190226IPR28811/copyright-meps-back-provisional-agreement | title = Copyright: MEPs back provisional agreement | website = europarl.europa.eu | date = 26 February 2019 | access-date = 26 February 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190227060644/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20190226IPR28811/copyright-meps-back-provisional-agreement | archive-date = 27 February 2019 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> At this point, the text was reviewed by the [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]], and then presented to the full European Parliament for a vote. The vote in Parliament was held on 26 March 2019, with the Directive passing by a vote of 348 MPs to 274<ref>[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//NONSGML+PV+20190326+RES-VOT+DOC+PDF+V0//EN&language=EN voting results] on page 8</ref> against.<ref name=\"wired-13pass\" /><ref name=\"verge finalvote mar19\"/><ref name=\":15\"/> After corrections of mistaken votes, the result was a vote of 338 MPs to 284.<ref name=\"VotesCorrections\">[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//NONSGML+PV+20190326+RES-RCV+DOC+PDF+V0//EN&language=EN voting results with corrections (end of page 53)] on page 52-53</ref> The main support for the directive came from the centre-right ([[European People's Party group|EPP]]). In terms of countries, most votes in favour came from France (62), Italy (39), Germany (38), Spain (34) and the UK (31), while the most votes against it came from Germany (49), Poland (33), UK (30), Italy (27) and the Netherlands (17).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.votewatch.eu/en/term8-copyright-in-the-digital-single-market-draft-legislative-resolution-provisional-agreement-amendment-.html#/##vote-tabs-list-1 |title=Copyright in the Digital Single Market |accessdate=30 Mar 2019 |publisher=Votewatch Europe}}</ref> While there had been an additional vote on an amendment to have a separate vote on the inclusion of the two controversial Articles (draft Articles 11 and 13, Directive Articles 15 and 17), the amendment narrowly failed to pass, with at least 13 MEPs stating they mistakenly voted the wrong way on this vote; if these had been voted as the MEP had intended, the amendment would have passed and required the additional vote.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/27/18283837/europe-copyright-directive-accidental-vote-meps-amendment | title = Ten European lawmakers say they voted against pivotal copyright amendment by accident | first = James | last = Vincent | date = 27 March 2019 | accessdate = 27 March 2019 | website = [[The Verge]] }}</ref>\n\n; Voting results in the European Parliament without corrections on 26 March 2019 by political groups<ref name=\"VotesCorrections\" />\n(<span style=\"background:green;color:#FFF\">In favour</span>/<span style=\"background:red;color:#FFF\">against</span> DSM copyright directive)\n{{Graph:Chart|width=900|height=200|xAxisTitle=Political group|yAxisTitle=number of EP members|type=stackedrect|x=EPP (153:28), S&D (99:54), ECR (23:42), ALDE (36:25), Greens-EFA (4:39), GUE-NGL (5:36), EFDD (6:28), ENF (15:14), Non-attached (7:8) |y1=153,99,23,36,4,5,6,15,7|y2=28,54,42,25,39,36,28,14,8|y3=36,34,10,7,9,11,7,8,7|y1Title=Votes in favour|y2Title=Votes against|y3Title=Abstention or not present|colors=green,red,gray|legend=Colours}}\n\n[[File:Copyright DSM Council Vote.svg|thumb|400px|Voting in the Council on 15 April. Besides voting against, [[Finland]], [[Italy]], [[Luxembourg]], the [[Netherlands]] and [[Poland]] have released a joint statement opposing the final draft of the directive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.permanentrepresentations.nl/documents/policy-notes/2019/02/20/joint-statement-regarding-the-copyright-directive|title=Joint statement on the Directive of the European Parliament and Council on copyright in the Digital Single Market - Policy document - The Netherlands at International Organisations|last=Zaken|first=Ministerie van Buitenlandse|date=2019-02-20|website=www.permanentrepresentations.nl|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref>|alt=]]\nThe Directive was approved by the [[Council of the European Union]] on 15 April 2019.<ref name=\":17\" /> 19 member states (representing 71% of the EU population in the countries that cast a vote) voted in favour of the Directive with six opposing and three abstaining.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nThe Directive will enter into force on 7 June 2019.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/25/18639963/poland-european-union-copyright-directive-filed-complaint-court-of-justice|title=Poland has filed a complaint against the European Union\u2019s copyright directive|last=Liptak|first=Andrew|date=2019-05-25|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> Member states will then have until 7 June 2021 to introduce laws within their own countries to support the Directive.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/mar/26/meps-approve-sweeping-changes-to-copyright-law-european-copyright-directive|title=MEPs approve sweeping changes to copyright law|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=2019-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":19\"/>\n\n== Content ==\nArticle numbers refer to the draft version of this copyright directive up through around 20 March 2019; the approved directive reorders several of the articles, such as draft Article 13 becoming the Directive's Article 17.<ref name=\"final directive\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf | title = DIRECTIVE (EU) 2019/... OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL on copyright and related rights in the Digital Single Market and amending Directives 96/9/EC and 2001/29/EC | date = 26 March 2019 | accessdate = 15 April 2019 | publisher = [[European Parliament]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Article 3 ===\n\nArticle 3 introduces a [[Limitations and exceptions to copyright|copyright exception]] for [[text and data mining]] (TDM) for the purposes of scientific research.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=9 June 2018|title=Copyright Reform: Help Us Ensure an Effective TDM Exception! \u2013 LIBER|url=https://libereurope.eu/blog/2017/09/25/copyright-reform-help-us-ensure-an-effective-tdm-exception/|newspaper=LIBER|date=25 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228164450/http://libereurope.eu/blog/2017/09/25/copyright-reform-help-us-ensure-an-effective-tdm-exception/|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The COREPER version has both a mandatory and an optional extension.<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\"/>\n\nDepending on whether it acknowledges the [[public domain]] status of facts and information, the TDM exception could increase or decrease restrictions compared to the status quo.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=12 June 2018|title=24 organisations urge Rapporteur Axel Voss MEP to strike a more ambitious deal on TDM \u2013 European Alliance for Research Excellence|url=http://eare.eu/24-organisations-urge-rapporteur-voss-reach-ambitious-deal-tdm/|newspaper=European Alliance for Research Excellence|date=8 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140050/http://eare.eu/24-organisations-urge-rapporteur-voss-reach-ambitious-deal-tdm/|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Article 5 ===\n\nArticle 5 introduces a mandatory exception for the use of copyrighted works as part of \"digital and cross-border teaching activities\". This article clarifies that educational establishments can make non-commercial use of copyrighted works for illustrative purposes.<ref name=\"final directive\"/>\n\nThere have been worries from the educational sector that the exception proposed in article 5 is too limiting. For example, the sector proposes to broaden the scope of \"educational establishments\" to include cultural heritage institutions. The most debated part of the article is 5(2), under which the exception would not be available if there are \"adequate licenses\" available in the market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://education.okfn.org/educators-ask-for-a-better-copyright/|title=Educators ask for a better copyright|date=16 January 2018|work=Open Education Working Group|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705150720/https://education.okfn.org/educators-ask-for-a-better-copyright/|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe COREPER version{{clarify|date=April 2019}} has changes to reflect the arguments of the education sector, but still includes the debated article 5(2).<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.csee-etuce.org/en/news/archive/2657-etuce-urges-the-european-parliament-to-vote-in-favour-of-an-open-broad-and-flexible-eu-copyright-education-exception| title = ETUCE urges the European Parliament to vote in favour of an open, broad and flexible EU copyright education exception | date  =4 July 2018 | accessdate = 15 April 2019 | publisher = European Trade Union Committee for Education }}</ref>\n\n=== Article 14 ===\nArticle 14 states that reproductions of works of visual art that are in the [[public domain]] cannot be subject to copyright or related rights, unless the reproduction is an original creative work.<ref name=\"finaltext\">{{cite web |title=Final text of the Directive as submitted to the Parliament on 26 March 2019|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf |accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Article 11|Article 15}}Draft Article 11 (Article 15 of the directive) ===\nDraft Article 11 (Article 15 of the directive) extends the 2001 Information Society Directive to grant publishers direct copyright over \"online use of their press publications by information society service providers\".<ref name=\"EUJune25\" /> Under current EU law, publishers instead rely on authors assigning copyright to them and must prove rights ownership for each individual work.<ref name=\"EPstudy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/thinktank/en/document.html?reference=IPOL_STU(2017)596810|title=Strengthening the Position of Press Publishers and Authors and Performers in the Copyright Directive \u2013 Think Tank|publisher=European Parliament|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143258/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/thinktank/en/document.html?reference=IPOL_STU(2017)596810|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The version of the directive voted on by the [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] contained explicit exemptions for the act of [[hyperlinking]] and \"legitimate private and non-commercial use of press publications by individual users\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://juliareda.eu/2018/06/article-11-13-vote/|title=What\u2019s at stake in the July 5 #SaveYourInternet vote: The text, explained|last=Reda|first=Julia|work=Julia Reda|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705194938/https://juliareda.eu/2018/06/article-11-13-vote/|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe proposal attaches several new conditions to the right, including expiry after one year and exemptions for either copying an \"insubstantial\" part of a work or for copying it in the course of academic or scientific research.<ref name=\"EUJune25\" /> It is derived from the [[ancillary copyright for press publishers]] which was introduced in Germany in 2013.<ref name=\"EPstudy\" /> Press publishing, \"whose purpose is to inform the general public and which are periodically or regularly updated\", is distinguished from [[academic publishing|academic]] and [[Scientific literature|scientific]] publishing (Recital 33).<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\"/>\n\nArticle 11 was moved to Article 15 in the final draft from the trilogue negotiations issued 26 March 2019 and approved by the Parliament and Council.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://fortune.com/2019/03/26/eu-copyright-directive-article-13-passed/ | title = EU Holds Online Platforms Liable for Users' Copyright Infringement | first = David | last = Meyer | date = 26 March 2019 | accessdate = 15 April 2019 | work = [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] }}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Article 13|Article 17}}Draft Article 13 (Directive Article 17)===\nDraft Article 13 of the draft replaces the \"[[Electronic Commerce Directive 2000|mere conduit]]\" exemption from copyright infringement from for-profit \"[[User-generated content|online content sharing service]] providers\" with a new, conditional exemption to liability. These conditions are an implementation of \"effective and proportionate measures\", as claimed by service providers, to \"prevent the availability of specific [unlicensed] works identified by rightsholders\", acting \"expeditiously\" to remove them, and demonstrating that \"best efforts\" have been made to prevent their future availability. The article also extends any licenses granted to content hosts to their users, as long as those users are not acting \"on a commercial basis\".<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" />\n\nThe article directs member states to consider the size of the provider, the amount of content uploaded, and the effectiveness of the measures imposed \"in light of technological developments\". It also mandates an appeals process,<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" /> and requires content hosts to share \"information on the use of content\" with the content's owner, the lack of which has been a point of contention in the past.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/03/technology/internet/03youtube.html|title=Royalty Dispute Stops Music Videos in Germany|last=O\u2019Brien|first=Kevin J.|work=New York Times|access-date=10 August 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811005734/https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/03/technology/internet/03youtube.html|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDraft Article 13's provisions target commercial web hosts which \"store and give the public access to a large number of works or other subject-matter uploaded by its users which [they] organise and promote for profit-making purposes\". The proposal makes explicit that this does not include private [[cloud storage]] services, non-profit encyclopedias (such as [[Wikipedia]]), nor non-profit educational or scientific repositories.<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" />\n\nDraft Article 13b requires websites which \"automatically reproduce or refer to significant amounts of copyright-protected visual works\" to \"conclude fair and balanced licensing agreements with any requesting {{Sic|rightholders}}\".<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nDraft Article 13 was named Article 17 in the final trilogue draft issued in February 2019 and approved by the European Parliament and Council.<ref name=\"verge finalvote mar19\"/>\n\n=== Draft Articles 14 through 16 (Directive articles 18 through 20)  ===\nAs a whole, draft articles 14-16 (Directive Articles 18-20) in the working version of the Directive, improve the bargaining position of authors and performers, even though it set out systems that were weaker than some existing ones in member states.<ref name=EPstudy/> Draft article 15 (Directive article 19) aims to allow authors to increase their remuneration in some cases where it is disproportionately low.<ref name=EPstudy/>\n\nAssociations of authors had proposed a \"rights reversion mechanism\" which would allow cancelling a [[copyright transfer agreement]] proven to be disadvantageous.<ref name=\"basca01\" >{{cite web|title=Music creators call for EU-wide rights reversion mechanism|url=https://basca.org.uk/2017/10/19/music-creators-call-eu-wide-rights-reversion-mechanism/|website=BASCA|accessdate=5 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142607/https://basca.org.uk/2017/10/19/music-creators-call-eu-wide-rights-reversion-mechanism/|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20170811-ALCS-and-SoA-Briefing-note-on-DSM-directive-and-Juri-amendments.pdf|title=Our Views on the European Commission's Draft Legislation to Modernise the European Copyright Framework and Proposed Amendments|date=August 2017|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141523/http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20170811-ALCS-and-SoA-Briefing-note-on-DSM-directive-and-Juri-amendments.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Other articles ===\nOther passages of the proposal attempt to clarify the legal status of [[orphan works]] and certain common activities by libraries.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=22 June 2018|title=European Parliament votes to improve access to digitised cultural heritage|url=https://pro.europeana.eu/post/european-parliament-votes-to-improve-access-to-digitsed-cultural-heritage|website=Europeana|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622100105/https://pro.europeana.eu/post/european-parliament-votes-to-improve-access-to-digitsed-cultural-heritage|archive-date=22 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the Trilogue negotiations, Article 12a proposed granting sports event organisers copyright over recordings of their events.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&language=EN&reference=P8-TA-2018-0337|title=Amendments adopted by the European Parliament on 12 September 2018 on the proposal for a directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on copyright in the Digital Single Market|date=12 September 2018|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111211840/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&language=EN&reference=P8-TA-2018-0337|archive-date=11 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/3kenb8/the-eu-can-still-be-saved-from-its-internet-wrecking-copyright-plan | title = The EU Can Still Be Saved From Its Internet-Wrecking Copyright Plan | first = Karl | last =Bode |date= 12 September 2018 | accessdate = 15 April 2019 | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Motherboard]] }}</ref>  The March 2019 version only says, on the last page, that the commission in the future will assess the challenges of illegal online transmissions of sports broadcasts.<ref name=\"final directive\"/>\n\n== Positions ==\n\n=== Politicians ===\nAs of 21 March 2019, 100 MEPs have signed in support of the directive, while 126 have agreed to vote against it.<ref>{{cite web |title=MEPs pro Manifesto for an open and fair internet |url=https://www.manifesto4copyright.eu/MEPs |website=www.manifesto4copyright.eu |accessdate=21 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321104251/https://www.manifesto4copyright.eu/MEPs |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pledge 2019: Against Article 13 |url=https://pledge2019.eu/en |website=pledge2019.eu |accessdate=21 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320154614/https://pledge2019.eu/en |archive-date=20 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> On 20 March 2019 74 MEPs asked for Article 13 to be deleted from the directive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amendment 269 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-269-270_EN.pdf |accessdate=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321110827/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-269-270_EN.pdf |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In the end, 348 voted for and 274 voted against.<ref>{{cite web |title=Copyright in the Digital Single Market: European Parliament Vote |url=https://juliareda.eu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/copyrightvote.pdf |accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, support in the European Parliament was led by the [[European People's Party group]] and the [[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats]], the parliament's two largest groups. Major national parties in support include Germany's ruling [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]] and their coalition partners the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]], the United Kingdom's ruling [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and opposition [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], and Poland's main opposition party, [[Civic Platform]].<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.votewatch.eu/en/term8-copyright-in-the-digital-single-market-draft-legislative-resolution-vote-commission-proposal-ordinar.html|title=Results of the 12th of September vote on Copyright in the Digital Single Market|website=VoteWatch|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124230/https://www.votewatch.eu/en/term8-copyright-in-the-digital-single-market-draft-legislative-resolution-vote-commission-proposal-ordinar.html|archive-date=9 December 2018|url-status=live|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/the-industry-is-totally-united-on-this-issue-uk-music-leads-copyright-delegation-to-brussels/072965|title='The industry is totally united on this issue': UK Music leads copyright delegation to Brussels|access-date=23 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724032222/http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/the-industry-is-totally-united-on-this-issue-uk-music-leads-copyright-delegation-to-brussels/072965|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe directive's [[rapporteur]], [[Axel Voss]], is German MEP and a member of the EPP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eppgroup.eu/news/Axel-Voss-appointed-new-Rapporteur-for-Copyright-Directive|title=Axel Voss appointed new Rapporteur for Copyright Directive|date=15 June 2017|work=eppgroup.eu|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705233740/http://www.eppgroup.eu/news/Axel-Voss-appointed-new-Rapporteur-for-Copyright-Directive|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Voss rejects critics' arguments against the directive, and in particular describes talk of censorship as \"unjustified, excessive, objectively wrong and dishonest\". He points out that content filtering technology has been in use on [[YouTube]] for a decade without having ever sparked an \"anti-censorship campaign\",<ref name=\":7\" /> and accuses \"big [internet] platforms\" of mounting a \"fake news campaign\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://multimedia.europarl.europa.eu/en/copyright-directive-statement-by-axel-voss-eppde-rapporteur-_I158298-V_v|title=Copyright directive: statement by Axel VOSS (EPP,DE), rapporteur|date=2 July 2018|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705232910/https://multimedia.europarl.europa.eu/en/copyright-directive-statement-by-axel-voss-eppde-rapporteur-_I158298-V_v|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Axel Voss's understanding of copyright was referred to as \"absolutely lacking\" in 2019 by Till Kreutzer, a copyright expert, after Voss stated that people are allowed to upload newspaper articles in full.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU-Urheberrechtsreform: Das \"absolute Unverst\u00e4ndnis\" des Axel Voss - Golem.de |url=https://www.golem.de/news/eu-urheberrechtsreform-das-absolute-unverstaendnis-des-axel-voss-1902-139511.html |website=www.golem.de |accessdate=24 February 2019 |language=de-DE |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223193120/https://www.golem.de/news/eu-urheberrechtsreform-das-absolute-unverstaendnis-des-axel-voss-1902-139511.html |archive-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]], a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|member of Parliament of the United Kingdom]] and the deputy leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], said, \"we have got to secure for the workers [...] the full fruits of their industry. Google are trying to prevent that from happening\".<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOpposition in the European Parliament is led by populist parties including Poland's ruling [[Law and Justice]] party, Italy's ruling [[Five Star Movement]]/[[Lega Nord]] coalition, and the [[UK Independence Party]]. Other opponents include a large number of smaller parties at either end of the political spectrum.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/10/italy-steps-defend-eu-internet-users-against-copyright-filters-who-will-be-next|title=Italy Steps Up To Defend EU Internet Users Against Copyright Filters \u2013 Who Will Be Next?|last=O'Brein|first=Danny|date=23 October 2018|work=[[Electronic Frontier Foundation]]|accessdate=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023194617/https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/10/italy-steps-defend-eu-internet-users-against-copyright-filters-who-will-be-next|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Notable among these is the [[Pirate Party Germany]], whose sole MEP [[Julia Reda]] has been an outspoken opponent of the proposal.<ref name=\"PM2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/meps-rally-against-planned-eu-copyright-reform|title=MEPs rally against planned EU copyright reform|website=theparliamentmagazine.eu|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701164917/https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/meps-rally-against-planned-eu-copyright-reform|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She describes the efforts behind the law as large media companies trying to force \"platforms and search engines to use their snippets and to pay for them\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://copyrightblog.kluweriplaw.com/2018/06/18/julia-reda-discusses-current-proposal-directive-copyright-digital-single-market/|title=Julia Reda discusses the current Proposal for a Directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market \u2013 Kluwer Copyright Blog|date=18 June 2018|website=Kluwer Copyright Blog|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701164956/http://copyrightblog.kluweriplaw.com/2018/06/18/julia-reda-discusses-current-proposal-directive-copyright-digital-single-market/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> UKIP leader and MEP [[Gerard Batten]] said that the proposal may \"destroy the capacity for free speech on the internet and social media\".<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukip.org/national-ukip-news-item.php?id=18|title=UKIP opposes the EU's Copyright Directive in the Single Digital Market|date=3 July 2018|website=[[UK Independence Party]]|access-date=29 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129142031/https://www.ukip.org/national-ukip-news-item.php?id=18|archive-date=29 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Batten further noted that an international agreement, and not an EU directive, was needed to protect \"the legitimate rights of creators, authors and innovators\", whilst not stifling \"free speech and information dissemination\".<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nIt has been rumoured that during the [[European Council]]'s private vote to approve its negotiating position in March 2018 the ambassadors of Germany, Finland, the Netherlands, Slovenia, Belgium and Hungary either abstained from voting or voted against the proposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LauKaya/status/1000022947401224192|title=The #copyright directive was approved today...|last=Kayali|first=Laura|date=25 May 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219035846/https://twitter.com/LauKaya/status/1000022947401224192|archive-date=19 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref> However, MEPs of each of those countries' governing parties went on to largely or wholly support the directive in parliament.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nGerman politician [[Kevin K\u00fchnert]], federal chairperson of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]]'s [[Young Socialists in the SPD|youth organisation]], has voiced opposition to Article 13, claiming that it violates the coalition agreement between the SPD and the [[CDU/CSU]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/uploadfilter-kevin-kuehnert-fordert-abstimmung-auf-spd-parteikonvent-a-1254592.html |title=Kevin K\u00fchnert fordert Abstimmung auf SPD-Parteikonvent |work=[[Spiegel Online]] |language=de |date=22 February 2019 |access-date=22 February 2019 |last1=Hickmann |first1=Christoph |last2=Medick |first2=Veit |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222165055/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/uploadfilter-kevin-kuehnert-fordert-abstimmung-auf-spd-parteikonvent-a-1254592.html |archive-date=22 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Petra Sitte, vice-chair of the democratic socialist party [[The Left (Germany)|The Left]], also stated that the effective endorsement of upload filters violates the coalition agreement, calling this copyright directive a \"compromise between the interests of different large corporations\" (\"''Kompromiss zwischen den Interessen verschiedener Gro\u00dfkonzerne''\") and \"a grave threat to freedom of expression\" (\"''eine ernsthafte Gefahr f\u00fcr die Meinungsfreiheit''\").<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.linksfraktion.de/themen/nachrichten/detail/uploadfilter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-ewiges-deja-vu/ |title=Uploadfilter und Leistungsschutzrecht: Ewiges D\u00e9j\u00e0-Vu |last=Sitte |first=Petra |date=15 February 2019 |access-date=22 February 2019 |website=Die Linke. im Bundestag |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223074345/https://www.linksfraktion.de/themen/nachrichten/detail/uploadfilter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-ewiges-deja-vu/ |archive-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe day before the Parliament vote, the ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]'' reported that Germany may have caved in to support the Directive at the last minute in exchange for France's approval of the controversial [[Nord Stream|Nord Stream 2]] project, a [[natural gas]] pipeline from Russia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.faz.net/faz-edition/wirtschaft/2019-03-26/f30a5870c08cc1e1b4524c1be19d1faf/ |title=Altmaier opfert Start-ups im Urheberrecht |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |language=de |date=2019-03-25 |access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> MEP [[Tiemo W\u00f6lken]], a member of the SDP and opponent of the Directive, claimed that this had been rumoured before the report was published.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=woelken |number=1110278446515699712 |date=2019-03-25 |title=Was bisher in #Br\u00fcssel & #Berlin nur gemunkelt wurde, l\u00e4sst sich offensichtlich nun so belegen, dass es ver\u00f6ffentlicht wird. Es gab einen Deal auf h\u00f6chster Ebene zwischen Deutschland & Frankreich. #Uploadfilter gegen #Gas. Ein Grund mehr morgen mit #Nein zu stimmen! #Artikel13 |last=W\u00f6lken |first=Tiemo |authorlink=Tiemo W\u00f6lken}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-governmental organisations ===\n[[File:Blackout of wikipedia.de by Wikimedia Deutschland - March 2019.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Blackout of [[German Wikipedia]] - 21 March 2019]]\n[[File:Italian Wikipedia blocked.png|thumb|upright=1.4|The banner block on [[Italian Wikipedia]]. Other blocked Wikipedias had similar messages.]]\n[[File:English Wikipedia EU copyright banner.png|thumb|upright=1.4|The banner on the English Wikipedia seen from a German IP address]]\nIn 2017, [[Human Rights Watch]] and [[Reporters Without Borders]] were among the signatories of an open letter opposing Article 13.<ref>{{cite news |last=Locklear |first=Mallory |title=Digital rights groups speak out against EU plan to scan online content |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/17/digital-rights-groups-against-eu-scan-online-content/ |work=[[Engadget]] |date=17 October 2017 |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220063020/https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/17/digital-rights-groups-against-eu-scan-online-content/ |archive-date=20 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> 145{{Nbsp}}organisations from the areas of human and digital rights, media freedom, publishing, libraries, educational institutions, software developers, and [[Internet service provider]]s signed a letter opposing the proposed legislation on 26 April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leistungsschutzrecht.info/sites/default/files/assets/dokumente/aktuelles/openletter-axelvoss-deletearticle11-english.pdf|title=Letter by 145 civil society organisations|url-status=live|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141128/http://leistungsschutzrecht.info/sites/default/files/assets/dokumente/aktuelles/openletter-axelvoss-deletearticle11-english.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> Some of those opposed include the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], [[Creative Commons]], [[European Digital Rights]],<ref name=\"Index2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indexoncensorship.org/2018/04/digital-single-market-nightmare/|title=Directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market 'destined to become a nightmare'|date=26 April 2018|website=Index on Censorship|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140215/https://www.indexoncensorship.org/2018/04/digital-single-market-nightmare/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Max Planck Society]],<ref name=\"CNET2018June22\" /> [[GitHub]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boingboing.net/2018/09/11/developers-developers-develope-3.html|title=What developers need to do to save the internet from the EU's looming copyright disaster|last=Doctorow|first=Cory|authorlink=Cory Doctorow|date=11 September 2018|website=[[Boing Boing]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911113555/https://boingboing.net/2018/09/11/developers-developers-develope-3.html|archive-date=11 September 2018|url-status=live|access-date=11 September 2018}}</ref> various [[Wikimedia]] chapters,<ref name=\"Index2018\" /> and the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] (the parent organisation of [[Wikipedia]]).<ref name=\"WikimediaFoundation\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2018/06/29/eu-copyright-proposal-will-hurt-web-wikipedia/|title=How the EU copyright proposal will hurt the web and Wikipedia|last=Hershenov|first=Eileen|date=29 June 2018|website=wikimedia.org|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|access-date=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701194303/https://blog.wikimedia.org/2018/06/29/eu-copyright-proposal-will-hurt-web-wikipedia/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Italian Wikipedia]],<ref name=\"ItalyWikipedia\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44696302|title=Italy Wikipedia shuts down in protest at EU copyright law|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=3 July 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=29 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729060650/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44696302|archive-date=29 July 2018|url-status=live|publisher=BBC|department=World News (Europe)}}</ref><ref name=\"PagesShutDown\">{{Cite news|url=https://siliconangle.com/blog/2018/07/04/italian-spanish-polish-wikipedia-pages-shut-down-ahead-controversial-copyright-law/|title=Italian, Spanish and Polish Wikipedia pages shut down ahead of controversial copyright law|last=Farrell|first=James|date=4 July 2018|work=[[Silicon Angle]]|access-date=29 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729062249/https://siliconangle.com/blog/2018/07/04/italian-spanish-polish-wikipedia-pages-shut-down-ahead-controversial-copyright-law/|archive-date=29 July 2018|url-status=live|publisher=Silicon Angle Media|department=Blog}}</ref><ref name=\"PolishWikipedia\">{{Cite news|url=https://polandinenglish.info/37945453/polish-wikipedia-shuts-down-in-protest-at-eu-copyright-law|title=Polish Wikipedia shuts down in protest at EU copyright law|author=pg/st<!--No other author information availble.-->|date=4 July 2018|work=Poland in English|access-date=29 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729061112/https://polandinenglish.info/37945453/polish-wikipedia-shuts-down-in-protest-at-eu-copyright-law|archive-date=29 July 2018|url-status=live|publisher=[[Telewizja Polska]]}}</ref> later followed by others including the [[Spanish Wikipedia|Spanish]],<ref name=\"PagesShutDown\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/tecnologia/redes/abci-wikipedia-espanol-cierra-forma-temporal-protesta-propuesta-copyright-201807041109_noticia.html|title=Wikipedia en espa\u00f1ol cierra de forma temporal en protesta por la propuesta de copyright de la UE|work=abc|access-date=4 July 2018|language=es-ES|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704153031/https://www.abc.es/tecnologia/redes/abci-wikipedia-espanol-cierra-forma-temporal-protesta-propuesta-copyright-201807041109_noticia.html|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Estonian Wikipedia|Estonian]], [[Latvian Wikipedia|Latvian]], [[Polish Wikipedia|Polish]],<ref name=\"PagesShutDown\" /><ref name=\"PolishWikipedia\" /> [[French Wikipedia|French]], and [[Portuguese Wikipedia|Portuguese]] editions,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tehnika.postimees.ee/4513784/eesti-vikipeedia-pani-protesti-margiks-oma-lehekulje-kinni|title=Eesti Vikipeedia pani protesti m\u00e4rgiks oma lehek\u00fclje kinni|work=Tehnika|access-date=4 July 2018|language=et|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704084323/https://tehnika.postimees.ee/4513784/eesti-vikipeedia-pani-protesti-margiks-oma-lehekulje-kinni|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \"blacked-out\" its pages for readers on 3\u20135 July 2018, while the English Wikipedia added a banner asking readers in Europe to contact their representatives in the European Parliament.<ref name=\"ItalyWikipedia\" /> The Wikimedia Foundation reiterated its concerns in February 2019.<ref name=\"WikimediaFoundation19\">{{cite web |url=https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/02/07/problems-remain-with-the-eus-copyright-reform/ |title=Problems remain with the EU's copyright reform |last1=Dimitrov |first1=Dimitar |last2=Davenport |first2=Allison |website=[[Wikimedia Foundation]] |date=7 February 2019 |accessdate=21 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222041936/https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/02/07/problems-remain-with-the-eus-copyright-reform/ |archive-date=22 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"WikimediaFoundation19b\">{{cite web |url=https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/02/28/we-do-not-support-the-eu-copyright-directive-in-its-current-form-heres-why-you-shouldnt-either/ |title=We do not support the EU Copyright Directive in its current form. Here's why you shouldn't either |website=[[Wikimedia Foundation]] |last=Davenport |first=Allison |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=2 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306044327/https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/02/28/we-do-not-support-the-eu-copyright-directive-in-its-current-form-heres-why-you-shouldnt-either/ |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Four editions of Wikipedia\u2014German, Danish, Czech and Slovak\u2014were blacked-out for 24 hours on 21 March 2019 to further protest the directive.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why Wikipedia will go offline for 24 hours in Germany |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/03/14/wikipedia-go-offline-hours-germany-protest-against-eu-bill-that-could-harm-freedom-speech/ |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=14 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319215240/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/03/14/wikipedia-go-offline-hours-germany-protest-against-eu-bill-that-could-harm-freedom-speech/ |archive-date=19 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Prepare for the shutdown of Slovak Wikipedia |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/22079741/slovak-wikipedia-to-shut-down-eu-copyright-directive.html |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=spectator.sme.sk |date=20 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321073123/https://spectator.sme.sk/c/22079741/slovak-wikipedia-to-shut-down-eu-copyright-directive.html |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=Fort2019Mar21>{{cite news |title=Why Four Versions of Wikipedia Have Deliberately Gone Dark |url=http://fortune.com/2019/03/21/wikipedia-dark-eu-copyright-protest/ |accessdate=22 March 2019 |work=Fortune |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322122633/http://fortune.com/2019/03/21/wikipedia-dark-eu-copyright-protest/ |archive-date=22 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Wikipedia co-founder [[Jimmy Wales]] raised concerns regarding the costs and effectiveness of upload filters and possible negative effects upon [[free speech]] online.<ref name=\"BBC2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44482381|title=Protests over Brussels copyright reform|date=15 June 2018|work=[[BBC News Online|BBC News]]|accessdate=19 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316142603/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44482381|archive-date=16 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://copybuzz.com/copyright/50-human-rights-media-freedom-ngos-ask-eu-delete-censorship-filter-stop-madness/|title=Over 50 Human Rights & Media Freedom NGOs ask EU to Delete Censorship Filter & to Stop \u00a9 Madness \u2013 Copybuzz|website=copybuzz.com|language=en-US|access-date=8 July 2018|date=16 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709010042/http://copybuzz.com/copyright/50-human-rights-media-freedom-ngos-ask-eu-delete-censorship-filter-stop-madness/|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Technology companies ===\n[[Google]] (which operates the [[Google News]] aggregation site which would be affected) has opposed the directive since its first inception in 2016, when they argued that the proposals would \"turn the internet into a place where everything uploaded to the web must be cleared by lawyers\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.google/outreach-initiatives/public-policy/european-copyright-theres-better-way/|title=European copyright: there's a better way|date=14 September 2016|work=Google|access-date=10 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709132940/https://blog.google/outreach-initiatives/public-policy/european-copyright-theres-better-way/|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Kent Walker, Senior Vice President for Global Affairs and Chief Legal Officer at Google, \"Companies that act reasonably in helping rights holders identify and control the use of their content shouldn\u2019t be held liable for anything a user uploads, any more than a telephone company should be liable for the content of conversations.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blog.google/around-the-globe/google-europe/now-time-fix-eu-copyright-directive/|title=Now is the time to fix the EU copyright directive|last=|first=|date=Feb 7, 2019|website=Google Official Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2018 the company encouraged news publishers in its [[Digital News Initiative]] to lobby MEPs on the proposals, members of the initiative are eligible for grants to support digital journalism from a \u20ac150m fund.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a8031d7a-78a0-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=Google criticised for push against EU copyright reform|date=26 June 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705004439/https://www.ft.com/content/a8031d7a-78a0-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref> YouTube's [[chief executive officer]], [[Susan Wojcicki]], urged content creators on the platform to take action to oppose the legislation, as it \"poses a threat to both [their] livelihood and [their] ability to share [their] voice with the world\", and stressing that their [[Content ID (algorithm)|Content ID]] system was intended to help assure fair management and payments for copyright holders already without government intervention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/22/youtube-susan-wojcicki-creators-protest-eu-article-13-copyright-law.html|title=YouTube CEO urges YouTube creators to protest European copyright law|last=D'onfo|first=Julianne|date=22 October 2018|work=[[CNBC]]|accessdate=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022215957/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/22/youtube-susan-wojcicki-creators-protest-eu-article-13-copyright-law.html|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Wojcicki later wrote that any company implementing the necessary protocols to meet the directive would have a significant financial burden, and for a company the scale of YouTube, \"the potential liabilities could be so large that no company could take on such a financial risk\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/12/18087250/youtube-ceo-copyright-directive-article-13-european-union|title=YouTube CEO calls EU's proposed copyright regulation financially impossible|last=Alexander|first=Julie|date=12 November 2018|work=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=12 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112170240/https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/12/18087250/youtube-ceo-copyright-directive-article-13-european-union|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Facebook]] is also opposed, arguing that the proposal \"could have serious, unintended consequences for an open and creative internet\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/european-parliament-votes-against-publishers-right-copyright-law-changes-as-facebook-warns-of-unintended-consequences/|title=European Parliament votes against 'publisher's right' copyright law changes as Facebook warns of 'unintended consequences'|date=5 July 2018|magazine=Press Gazette|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711025503/https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/european-parliament-votes-against-publishers-right-copyright-law-changes-as-facebook-warns-of-unintended-consequences/|archive-date=11 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Computer and Communications Industry Association]], a trade association that represents Google and other large technology companies, is a principal funder of the [[Copyright for Creativity]] organisation, a coalition that led the \"Save Your Internet\" campaign opposing the directive.<ref name=\"Corp2019\">{{cite web |title=Copyright Directive: how competing big business lobbies drowned out critical voices |url=https://corporateeurope.org/power-lobbies/2018/12/copyright-directive-how-competing-big-business-lobbies-drowned-out-critical |website=Corporate Europe Observatory |accessdate=16 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216153252/https://corporateeurope.org/power-lobbies/2018/12/copyright-directive-how-competing-big-business-lobbies-drowned-out-critical |archive-date=16 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Reddit]] in November 2018 referred their European users to a website called \"Don't Wreck the Net\".<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=https://redditblog.com/2018/11/28/the-eu-copyright-directive-what-redditors-in-europe-need-to-know/|title=The EU Copyright Directive: What Redditors in Europe need to know|website=Reddit|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207083308/https://redditblog.com/2018/11/28/the-eu-copyright-directive-what-redditors-in-europe-need-to-know/|archive-date=7 December 2018|url-status=live|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Academics ===\nMore than 200 academics have criticised the directive, emphasising concerns about the effectiveness of Article 11's impact on the readership of online publication and of Article 13's obligations on service providers that will \"benefit big players\".<ref name=\"Create20180629\">{{cite web|url=https://www.create.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Academic_Statement_Copyright_Directive_29_06_2018.pdf|title=Copyright Reform: Open Letter from European Research Centres|date=29 June 2018|work=CREATe|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629155041/https://www.create.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Academic_Statement_Copyright_Directive_29_06_2018.pdf|archive-date=29 June 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ivir.nl/academics-against-press-publishers-right/|title=Letter by 169 academics|url-status=live|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180705001936/https://www.ivir.nl/academics-against-press-publishers-right/|archive-date=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://peepbeep.files.wordpress.com/2016/10/30-september-2016-openlettercommission-w-s1.pdf|title=Open letter by 40 scholars to the European Commission|date=30 October 2016|url-status=live|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141206/https://peepbeep.files.wordpress.com/2016/10/30-september-2016-openlettercommission-w-s1.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> [[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition|SPARC Europe]] called for the removal of Article 11, arguing that it would \"make the last two decades of news less accessible to researchers and the public, leading to a distortion of the public's knowledge and memory of past events\", and if extended to academic publishing, would \"in effect ask readers to pay publishers for access to works for which authors, institutions or research funders had already paid publishers to make freely accessible to all under '[[open access]]' terms\".<ref name=\"Create20180629\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sparceurope.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/CopyrightReformBrief.pdf|title=\"Copyright in the Digital Single Market\" briefing|publisher=SPARC Europe|url-status=live|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622220830/https://sparceurope.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/CopyrightReformBrief.pdf|archive-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> Twenty-five research centres common on concerns that the financial benefits from the proposed directive will occur to large rightsholders rather than creators, with creators simple being used as \"frontmen/women\".<ref name=\"Create20180629\" />\n\nThe proposal is generally supported by academic publishers including the [[International Association of Scientific, Technical, and Medical Publishers]].<ref name=\"Nature2018\">{{cite journal|last1=Schiermeier|first1=Quirin|date=5 April 2018|title=EU copyright reforms draw fire from scientists|journal=Nature|volume=556|issue=7699|pages=14\u201315|doi=10.1038/d41586-018-03837-7|pmid=29620761}}</ref> This group has nevertheless criticised the proposal for excluding scientific publishers from the provisions of Article 11, describing the exclusion as \"unwarranted and potentially discriminatory\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stm-assoc.org/2016_09_14_News_Release_STM_response_to_Directive_on_Copyright_in_the_Single_Digital_Market.pdf|title=STM response to Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market|date=14 September 2016|publisher=[[International Association of Scientific, Technical, and Medical Publishers|STM]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410174902/https://www.stm-assoc.org/2016_09_14_News_Release_STM_response_to_Directive_on_Copyright_in_the_Single_Digital_Market.pdf|archive-date=10 April 2018|url-status=live|access-date=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Eurodoc|European Council for Doctoral Candidates and Junior Researchers]] opposes the proposal on the grounds that Article 13's exemption for non-commercial groups does not cover all scientific repositories, and cites the [[Horizon 2020]] project as an example of commercial work in the sector. They also generally agree with the claims of other opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurodoc.net/eurodoc-open-letter-copyright-directive.pdf|title=Eurodoc Open Letter to European Parliament on Copyright Directive|date=2 July 2018|website=[[Eurodoc]]|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702233401/http://eurodoc.net/eurodoc-open-letter-copyright-directive.pdf|archive-date=2 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition]], an [[open access]] advocacy group, opposes the proposal in principle.<ref name=\"Nature2018\" />\n\n=== Publishers ===\nA campaign organised by the [[European Grouping of Societies of Authors and Composers]] collected over 32,000{{Nbsp}}signatures in 2018 from creators including [[David Guetta]], [[Ennio Morricone]], [[Jean-Michel Jarre]], and the band [[Air (band)|Air]].<ref name=\"Indus2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/david-guetta-and-all-three-major-labels-are-among-industry-giants-pushing-for-copyright-reform/|title=David Guetta and all three major labels are among industry giants pushing for copyright reform {{!}} TIO|work=theindustryobserver.com.au|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721114621/https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/david-guetta-and-all-three-major-labels-are-among-industry-giants-pushing-for-copyright-reform/|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Other supporters in 2018 include musicians [[Paul McCartney]] and [[James Blunt]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paul-mccartney-james-blunt-back-new-european-copyright-law-1124974|title=Paul McCartney, James Blunt Back New European Copyright Law|date=4 July 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=4 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704152646/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paul-mccartney-james-blunt-back-new-european-copyright-law-1124974|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> author [[Philip Pullman]] (as head of the [[Society of Authors]]),<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20161205-Submission-to-IPO-on-DSM-directive-dec-2016.pdf|title=The Society of Authors' Response to the Intellectual Property Office's Calls for Views on the European Commission's Draft Legislation to Modernise the European Copyright Framework|publisher=[[Society of Authors]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704034530/http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20161205-Submission-to-IPO-on-DSM-directive-dec-2016.pdf|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"theverge 11sett 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/11/17845394/eu-copyright-directive-reform-date-vote-article-11-13|title=This is what at stake with the EU\u2019s latest copyright reform|last=Vincent|first=James|date=11 September 2018|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911182621/https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/11/17845394/eu-copyright-directive-reform-date-vote-article-11-13|archive-date=11 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Independent Music Companies Association]],<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://impalamusic.org/content/copyright-say-no-scaremongering-and-yes-creators-getting-paid|title=Copyright: say NO to scaremongering and YES to creators getting paid|publisher=[[Independent Music Companies Association]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704010146/http://impalamusic.org/content/copyright-say-no-scaremongering-and-yes-creators-getting-paid|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref> and German publisher [[Axel Springer SE|Axel Springer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/tensions-heighten-ahead-crunch-eu-copyright-reform-vote|title=Tensions heighten ahead of crunch EU copyright reform vote|website=www.theparliamentmagazine.eu|language=en|access-date=3 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701164908/https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/tensions-heighten-ahead-crunch-eu-copyright-reform-vote|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPublishing trade bodies similarly claim that a \"bad-faith\" \"misleading campaign\", is being carried out. They specifically name Wikipedia and [[Google]] as orchestrators,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"mythbuster\">{{cite web|url=https://www.publishersright.eu/mythbuster|title=MYTHBUSTER|website=publishersright.eu|publisher=[[European Magazine Media Association]] and others|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705003900/https://www.publishersright.eu/mythbuster|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukmusic.org/news/uk-music-chief-slams-google-as-corporate-vultures-as-figures-show-googles-3|title=UK Music chief slams Google as \"corporate vultures\" as figures show Google's \u20ac31m EU lobbying bid|publisher=[[UK Music]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704153622/https://www.ukmusic.org/news/uk-music-chief-slams-google-as-corporate-vultures-as-figures-show-googles-3|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"enpa\">{{cite web|url=http://enpa.eu/news/enpa-reacts-wikipedia-hostile-campaign-against-copyright|title=ENPA reacts to Wikipedia hostile campaign against Copyright|date=3 July 2018|publisher=[[European Newspaper Publishers' Association]]|access-date=5 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705034245/http://enpa.eu/news/enpa-reacts-wikipedia-hostile-campaign-against-copyright|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/07/05/eu_copyright_vote/|title=European Parliament balks at copyright law reform vote|date=5 July 2018|work=The Register|access-date=4 September 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905065215/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/07/05/eu_copyright_vote/|archive-date=5 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> claiming that Wikipedia and other platforms engaged in \"{{Sic|inacceptable}} misleading campaigns [...] to influence MEPs\" and pointing out that Google spent {{\u20ac|4.5&nbsp;million}} lobbying in Europe during 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/transparencyregister/public/consultation/displaylobbyist.do?id=03181945560-59|title=Transparency Register: Google|website=[[Lobby register#European Union|EU Transparency Register]]|access-date=4 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704182929/http://ec.europa.eu/transparencyregister/public/consultation/displaylobbyist.do?id=03181945560-59|archive-date=4 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> is among the sponsors of the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], another leading opponent,<ref name=\"Reg2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/06/20/eu_copyright_reform_article_11_13/|title=JURI's out, Euro copyright votes in: Whoa, did the EU just 'break the internet'?|date=20 June 2018|work=[[The Register]]|access-date=4 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140231/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/06/20/eu_copyright_reform_article_11_13/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>{{better source|date=July 2018}} and was seen asking its partners to lobby against the reform.<ref name=\":5\" /> These estimates have been called \"flawed\" and that how much Google has spent on lobbying on this issue is not possible to determine.<ref name=Corp2019/> These estimates were also released by the music industry as a press release just before the JURI voted.<ref name=Corp2019/>\n\nThe publishers argue that licensed content providers such as [[Spotify]] and [[Netflix]] are also negatively affected by the current copyright regime, which they say benefits user-driven platforms such as [[YouTube]] (owned by the parent company of Google) and [[Facebook]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://makeinternetfair.eu/en/node/18|title=About the transfer of value / value gap|date=31 January 2018|website=makeinternetfair.eu|publisher=[[European Grouping of Societies of Authors and Composers]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703151826/http://makeinternetfair.eu/en/node/18|archive-date=3 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref> They claim reports of [[spambot]]s flooding MEPs with so many anti-copyright emails that they can no longer carry out their work.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":9\" />\n\nWhile some publishers support the proposal, European Innovative Media Publishers, a publishing industry lobbying organisation, was founded in 2015 specifically to oppose Article 11.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://mediapublishers.eu/2017/12/27/small-publishers-take-neighbouring-right-out-of-eu-copyright-reform/|title=Our Op-ed as published in EurActiv: Small publishers: Take 'neighbouring right' out of EU copyright reform|website=mediapublishers.eu|accessdate=14 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614121753/http://mediapublishers.eu/2017/12/27/small-publishers-take-neighbouring-right-out-of-eu-copyright-reform/|archive-date=14 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Newspapers ===\nSome newspapers in support of the directive pejoratively label some of those opposed as \"the largest, richest corporate entities in the world\". In an editorial, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' stated that \"YouTube controls 60{{Nbsp}}per{{Nbsp}}cent of all streaming audio business, but pays only 11{{Nbsp}}per{{Nbsp}}cent of the revenues that artists receive\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/20a8d1e0-810a-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=The case for reforming the rules of copyright|date=6 July 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709010124/https://www.ft.com/content/20a8d1e0-810a-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref> Others newspapers focus on Article 11, arguing that the reform is a battle between European media pluralism and monopolistic foreign Internet giants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.humanite.fr/medias-defendre-le-pluralisme-en-europe-contre-les-geants-du-net-657096|title=M\u00e9dias. D\u00e9fendre le pluralisme en Europe contre les g\u00e9ants du Net\u2009!|date=20 June 2018|work=L'Humanit\u00e9|access-date=6 July 2018|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707005820/https://www.humanite.fr/medias-defendre-le-pluralisme-en-europe-contre-les-geants-du-net-657096|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liberation.fr/france/2018/06/18/l-europe-doit-defendre-les-medias-contre-la-loi-des-gafa_1660125|title=L\u2019Europe doit d\u00e9fendre les m\u00e9dias contre la&nbsp;loi des&nbsp;Gafa|work=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|access-date=6 July 2018|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707005938/http://www.liberation.fr/france/2018/06/18/l-europe-doit-defendre-les-medias-contre-la-loi-des-gafa_1660125|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A variety of mainstream newspapers have reported that some Internet platforms are lobbying against the bill to support their financial interests.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|title=YouTube and Facebook escape billions in copyright payouts after EU vote|last=Sweney|first=Mark|last2=Rankin|first2=Jennifer|date=5 July 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=5 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724094528/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=MEPs reject EU copyright reforms in victory for internet giants|last=Khan|first=Mehreen|date=5 July 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234046/https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=5 July 2018}}<br />{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-searches-for-way-round-eu-copyright-dmrjrgpx2|title=Google searches for way round EU copyright|last=Duke|first=Simon|date=1 July 2018|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=6 July 2018|language=en|issn=0956-1382|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707005833/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-searches-for-way-round-eu-copyright-dmrjrgpx2|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=live}}<br />{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-companies-win-reprieve-as-eu-parliament-delays-copyright-law-1530787465|title=Tech Companies Win Reprieve as EU Parliament Delays Copyright Law|last=Schechner|first=Sam|date=5 July 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=6 July 2018|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707005845/https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-companies-win-reprieve-as-eu-parliament-delays-copyright-law-1530787465|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=live}}<br />{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-07-06/tech-giants-win-against-media-companies-in-eu-copyright-battle|title=Tech Giants Are Stronger Than Paul McCartney|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=6 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917202029/https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-07-06/tech-giants-win-against-media-companies-in-eu-copyright-battle|archive-date=17 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA group of nine{{Nbsp}}major European press publishers including [[Agence France-Presse]], the [[Press Association]], and the [[European Alliance of News Agencies]] issued a letter supporting the proposal, describing it as \"key for the media industry, the consumer\u2019s future access to news, and ultimately a healthy democracy\". In the letter, they cite existing state support for struggling news media and argue that it should instead be provided by the \"internet giants\" which have been \"siphoning off\" advertising revenue.<ref name=\"9agencies\">{{cite web|url=https://images.derstandard.at/2017/12/14/brief.pdf|title=Letter by 9 news agencies|date=14 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208030217/https://images.derstandard.at/2017/12/14/brief.pdf|archive-date=8 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCritical accounts of the proposal were published in the summer of 2018 by major newspapers in Austria,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://derstandard.at/2000081976547/Heftige-Kritik-an-EU-Plaenen-Sterben-Internet-Memes-in-Europa|title=EU-Pl\u00e4ne f\u00fcr Uploadfilter k\u00f6nnten Todessto\u00df f\u00fcr Memes bedeuten \u2013 derStandard.at|website=DER STANDARD|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005254/https://derstandard.at/2000081976547/Heftige-Kritik-an-EU-Plaenen-Sterben-Internet-Memes-in-Europa|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> France,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/secteur/high-tech/2018/06/08/32001-20180608ARTFIG00290-un-projet-de-loi-europeen-pourrait-menacer-les-memes-sur-internet.php|title=Un projet de loi europ\u00e9en pourrait menacer les m\u00e8mes sur Internet|date=8 June 2018|newspaper=FIGARO|accessdate=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621185316/http://www.lefigaro.fr/secteur/high-tech/2018/06/08/32001-20180608ARTFIG00290-un-projet-de-loi-europeen-pourrait-menacer-les-memes-sur-internet.php|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Germany,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/upload-filter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-schroedingers-internet-a-1213496.html|title=Upload-Filter: Liebe Leserin, lieber Leser,|last=Beuth|first=Patrick|date=18 June 2018|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621231958/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/upload-filter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-schroedingers-internet-a-1213496.html|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/newsticker/dpa_nt/infoline_nt/netzwelt/article177859184/EU-Ausschuss-stimmt-fuer-Leistungsschutz-und-Uploadfilter.html|title=EU-Ausschuss stimmt f\u00fcr Leistungsschutz und Uploadfilter|last=WELT|date=20 June 2018|work=DIE WELT|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316142552/https://www.welt.de/newsticker/dpa_nt/infoline_nt/netzwelt/article177859184/EU-Ausschuss-stimmt-fuer-Leistungsschutz-und-Uploadfilter.html|archive-date=16 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/eu-s-attempt-at-internet-copyright-reform-is-a-ridiculous-own-goal-1.3538030|title=EU's attempt at internet copyright reform is a ridiculous own goal|work=The Irish Times|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621160023/https://www.irishtimes.com/business/eu-s-attempt-at-internet-copyright-reform-is-a-ridiculous-own-goal-1.3538030|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2018/06/20/economia/ombre-pi-che-luci-della-riforma-europea-del-copyright-ZqzmbTAGxPIxUJga2Ac1rJ/pagina.html|title=Ombre (pi\u00f9 che luci) della riforma europea del copyright|work=La Stampa|access-date=22 June 2018|language=it-IT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620193520/http://www.lastampa.it/2018/06/20/economia/ombre-pi-che-luci-della-riforma-europea-del-copyright-ZqzmbTAGxPIxUJga2Ac1rJ/pagina.html|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/mondo/2018-06-20/europa-stretta-copyright-arriva-tassa-link-e-meme-rischio-171942.shtml?uuid=AE6SSf9E|title=Europa, stretta sul copyright: arriva la tassa sui link (e meme a rischio)|work=Il Sole 24 ORE|access-date=22 June 2018|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623201332/http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/mondo/2018-06-20/europa-stretta-copyright-arriva-tassa-link-e-meme-rischio-171942.shtml?uuid=AE6SSf9E|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Poland,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tokfm.pl/Tokfm/7,130517,23572195,cenzura-internetu-i-podatek-od-linkowania-nowa-dyrektywa.html|title=B\u0119dzie cenzura internetu? Ekspertka: To mo\u017ce uderzy\u0107 nawet w przegl\u0105dy prasy i portale typu Wykop|work=tokfm|access-date=22 June 2018|language=pl-PL|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005148/http://www.tokfm.pl/Tokfm/7,130517,23572195,cenzura-internetu-i-podatek-od-linkowania-nowa-dyrektywa.html|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Spain,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/03/24/inenglish/1490355715_551697.html|title=Editorial {{!}} A digital agreement|last=Pa\u00eds|first=El|date=24 March 2017|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=22 June 2018|issn=1134-6582|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005012/https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/03/24/inenglish/1490355715_551697.html|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Slovakia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tech.sme.sk/c/20849608/bruselska-smernica-moze-uskodit-otvorenemu-a-slobodnemu-internetu.html|title=Bruselsk\u00e1 smernica m\u00f4\u017ee u\u0161kodi\u0165 otvoren\u00e9mu a slobodn\u00e9mu internetu|last=a.s.|first=Petit Press|work=tech.sme.sk|access-date=22 June 2018|language=sk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005316/https://tech.sme.sk/c/20849608/bruselska-smernica-moze-uskodit-otvorenemu-a-slobodnemu-internetu.html|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Content creators===\nThe [[International Federation of Journalists]], a union, complained about late amendments which made remuneration of journalists dependent on \"contractual arrangements\" and \"laws on ownership\". While describing the proposals as \"an achievement for authors overall\" and \"good news for the industry and for authors in some sectors\", they described the amendments as \"bad for journalism and bad for Europe\" and called on the EU to \"decide wisely and reject any discriminatory provisions\".<ref name=\"IFJ2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ifj.org/media-centre/news/detail/category/authors-rights/article/new-copyright-directive-makes-a-mockery-of-journalists-authors-rights.html|title=New copyright directive makes a mockery of journalists' authors' rights|date=14 February 2019|website=[[International Federation of Journalists]]|access-date=14 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214220017/https://www.ifj.org/media-centre/news/detail/category/authors-rights/article/new-copyright-directive-makes-a-mockery-of-journalists-authors-rights.html|archive-date=14 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA representative from a company that makes content filters states that their wide introduction as while result from article 13 will likely hurt new music artists by limiting their ability to share what they create.<ref name=Fort2019Mar21/>\n\n===Prominent individuals===\nIndividuals who have publicly opposed the law include comedian [[Stephen Fry]]; author [[Neil Gaiman]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/pro/paul-mccartney-joins-celeb-lobbying-european-parliament-over-copyright-reform-vote/|title=Paul McCartney joins crowded fight over online rules|date=4 July 2018|publisher=[[Politico]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234208/https://www.politico.eu/pro/paul-mccartney-joins-celeb-lobbying-european-parliament-over-copyright-reform-vote/|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref> [[Tim Berners-Lee]], creator of the [[World Wide Web]]; and [[Vint Cerf]], co-inventor of the [[Internet protocol suite]].<ref name=\"BBC2018\" />\n\n=== Case law ===\nIn 2012, the [[European Court of Justice]] ruled that existing EU law \"must be interpreted as precluding a national court from issuing an injunction against a hosting service provider which requires it to install a system for filtering...with a view to preventing works from being made available to the public in breach of copyright\", arguing that such an injunction \"could potentially undermine freedom of information, since that system might not distinguish adequately between unlawful content and lawful content, with the result that its introduction could lead to the blocking of lawful communications\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://curia.europa.eu/juris/document/document.jsf?text=&docid=119512doclang=EN&cid=2283803|title=Belgische Vereniging van Auteurs, Componisten en Uitgevers CVBA (SABAM) v Netlog NV|date=16 February 2012|website=[[CURIA]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121204018/http://curia.europa.eu/juris/document/document.jsf?text=&docid=119512doclang=EN&cid=2283803|archive-date=21 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights ===\nThe [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] raised concerns that the proposal was incompatible with the 1966 [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]]. In a public letter, special rapporteur, [[David Kaye (law professor)|David Kaye]], argued that the proposal's reluctance to pin down precise obligations on content hosts created \"significant legal uncertainty\" inconsistent with the covenant's requirement that any restrictions on freedom of expression be \"provided by law\". He concluded that this could lead to \"pressure on content sharing providers to err on the side of caution\". Kaye also criticised the lack of \"prior judicial review\" inherent in the system, and the similarly extrajudicial nature of its appeals process.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Issues/Opinion/Legislation/OL-OTH-41-2018.pdf|title=European Union draft directive on copyright in the digital single market|author=Kaye|first=David|date=13 June 2018|publisher=[[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|UNHCHR]]|id=OL OTH 41/2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615004339/https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Issues/Opinion/Legislation/OL-OTH-41-2018.pdf|archive-date=15 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He acknowledges that while copyright law needs to be modernised in Europe it should not be done in a way that harms freedom of expression and that the current recommendations within article 13 are not needed.<ref name=Fort2019Mar21/>\n\nThe letter also raised concerns regarding the lack of protection for non-profit groups,<ref name=\"auto8\"/> although such groups had been excluded from the proposal's provisions prior to its publication.<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" />\n\n==Controversy==\n\n=== Articles 11 and 13 (15 and 17 as passed) ===\nArticles 11 and 13 of the draft Directive, prior to Trilogue negotiations and since moved to Articles 15 and 17 in the final, passed version, have drawn a great deal of attention and opposition. Article 11, referred to as the \"[[link tax]]\", generated concerns that less information and fewer resources would be available through search engines.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/05/business/eu-parliament-copyright.html | title = Tech Giants Win a Battle Over Copyright Rules in Europe | first = Adam | last = Satariano | date = 5 July 2018 | accessdate = 15 February 2019 | work = [[The New York Times]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190215220053/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/05/business/eu-parliament-copyright.html | archive-date = 15 February 2019 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In their explanatory memorandum for Article 11, the Council describes existing rights enforcement for the online use of press publications as \"complex and inefficient.\" They also draw particular attention to the use of news articles by \"news aggregators or media-monitoring services\" for commercial purposes, and the problems that would face press publishers in licensing their work to such services.<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" /> After the European Commission analysed the implementation of similar laws in Germany and Spain, they found that newspapers actually benefited financially from the increased exposure to their online articles.<ref name=\"ECstudy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.asktheeu.org/en/request/4776/response/15356/attach/6/Doc1.pdf|title=Online News Aggregation and Neighbouring Rights for News Publishers|id=Ref. Ares(2017)6256585|year=2017|author=[[European Commission]] contractor|access-date=10 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305092801/https://www.asktheeu.org/en/request/4776/response/15356/attach/6/Doc1.pdf|archive-date=5 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"EPstudy\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/11/google-news-spain-to-close-in-response-to-tax-on-story-links|title=Google News Spain to close in response to story links 'tax'|last=Rushe|first=Dominic|date=11 December 2014|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=5 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721111326/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/11/google-news-spain-to-close-in-response-to-tax-on-story-links|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TechCrunch2018\">{{cite news |title=European MEPs vote to reopen copyright debate over \u2018censorship\u2019 controversy |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/07/05/european-meps-vote-to-reopen-copyright-debate-over-censorship-controversy/ |accessdate=5 July 2018 |work=TechCrunch |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705110341/https://techcrunch.com/2018/07/05/european-meps-vote-to-reopen-copyright-debate-over-censorship-controversy/ |archive-date=5 July 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nGermany (with the [[ancillary copyright for press publishers]] law) and Spain tested a link tax: it was considered a \"complete disaster\" which cost them millions of euros.<ref name=\"Fortune-1\" /> Google shut down [[Google News]] in Spain<ref name=\"Fortune-1\" /> and stopped using linked snippets of German articles completely.<ref name=\"Fortune-2\">[http://fortune.com/2018/06/26/google-eu-copyright-directive/ \"Google Is Being Criticized Over Its Copyright Stance In Europe. But the Company Is Right\"], ''Fortune'', 26 June 2018</ref> Experts predicted that such a link tax would lead to the Internet in Europe being more dominated by large media corporations, since it would be too time-consuming and costly for small online media companies to reach their own separate legal agreements to allow a link or quotes. As a result, they felt, many small media companies in Europe would eventually be forced to shut down due to a lack of online exposure and revenue.<ref name=\"Fortune-1\">[http://fortune.com/2016/03/24/eu-ancillary-copyright/ \"EU Lawmakers Are Still Considering This Failed Copyright Idea\"], ''Fortune'', 24 March 2016</ref>\n\nArticle 13, colloquially called the \"upload filter\" provision, has faced widespread criticism over the possibility that it could have a \"[[chilling effect]]\" on online expression, as it would force most web services to stop users uploading copyrighted content without authorization, or else the service would risk being held liable for infringements of its guidelines.<ref name=\"Fortune-3\">[http://fortune.com/2019/02/14/eu-copyright-directive-trilogue-deal/ \"Tech Industry and Activists Still Hope to Sink New EU Copyright Rules\"], ''Fortune'', 14 February 2019</ref> And although the article requires only \"best efforts\" from providers, larger companies would need to use expensive content-matching technology similar to [[YouTube]]'s [[Content ID (algorithm)|Content ID]] system, which cost Google about $100 million to develop.<ref name=\"Fortune-4\">[http://fortune.com/2019/03/26/eu-copyright-directive-google-news/ \"Google Once Cited EU's Copyright Reforms as a Business Risk. Now They're a Reality\"], ''Fortune'', 26 March 2019</ref><ref name=\"BBC2018Meme\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44546620|title='Disastrous' copyright bill vote approved|date=20 June 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180625111719/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44546620|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.axel-voss-europa.de/2018/06/18/stellungnahme-zur-reform-des-urheberrechts/|title=Europ\u00e4isches Urheberrecht|last=Voss|first=Axel|date=18 June 2018|website=www.axel-voss-europa.de|language=de-DE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234103/https://www.axel-voss-europa.de/2018/06/18/stellungnahme-zur-reform-des-urheberrechts/|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref> Others are concerned that due to the cost of filtering, only major U.S. technology firms would have sufficient resources to develop them, and that outsourcing the task by EU companies would then have privacy and data protection implications.<ref name=\"Rom20182\">{{cite journal|last1=Romero-Moreno|first1=Felipe|date=29 May 2018|title='Notice and staydown' and social media: amending Article 13 of the Proposed Directive on Copyright|journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology|pages=1\u201324|doi=10.1080/13600869.2018.1475906|hdl=2299/20431|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/eu/2018/06/19/the-eus-disastrous-copyright-reform-explained/|title=The EU's disastrous Copyright Reform, explained by its lovers and haters|last=Maack|first=M\u00e1r M\u00e1sson|date=19 June 2018|work=The Next Web|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180620124321/https://thenextweb.com/eu/2018/06/19/the-eus-disastrous-copyright-reform-explained/|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Rom2020\">{{cite journal |last=Romero-Moreno |first=Felipe |date=17 March 2020 |title='Upload filters' and human rights: implementing Article 17 of the Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market |journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology |pages=1\u201331 |doi-access=free |doi=10.1080/13600869.2020.1733760|issn=1360-0869 |hdl-access=free |hdl=2299/20431}}</ref>\n\nThe controversy over Article 13 has led Internet pioneers including [[Tim Berners-Lee]], [[Vint Cerf]], [[Jimmy Wales]], and [[Mitch Kapor]] to warn that \"Article 13 takes an unprecedented step towards the transformation of the Internet from an open platform for sharing and innovation, into a tool for the automated surveillance and control of its users.\"<ref name=\"EFF-letter\">[https://www.eff.org/files/2018/06/12/article13letter.pdf \"Article 13 of the EU Copyright Directive Threatens the Internet\"], letter to the President of the European Parliament, 12 June 2018</ref> [[Diego Naranjo]], senior policy adviser at the advocacy group [[European Digital Rights]], similarly warned that Article 13 \"sets a dangerous precedent for Internet filters and automated censorship mechanisms\u2014in the EU and across the globe.\"<ref name=\"Newstalk\">[https://www.newstalk.com/news/eu-controversial-copyright-841506 \"European Parliament approves controversial new copyright directive\"], ''Newstalk'', 26 March 2019</ref> The organisation said that \"online content filtering could be the end of the internet as we know it.\"<ref name=\"Newstalk\" />\n\nThe media lawyers Christian Solmecke and Anne-Christine Herr reported in their analysis of the negotiated compromise that it inherits the duty to use an upload filter because no other technique exists to fulfil the requirements of the law. They point out alternative solutions to extract enhanced license fees from an online provider without restricting the rights of private users by filtering all uploads\u2014i.e., by according [[private copying levy]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Christian Solmecke und Anne-Christine Herr |url=https://www.wbs-law.de/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Analyse-Artikel-13-Version-1.2-WILDE-BEUGER-SOLMECKE-Rechtsanw\u00e4lte.pdf|title=Rechtliche Analyse der Pro- und Contra Argumente zu Artikel 13 der geplanten EU Urheberrechtsnovelle|date=2019-03-19|accessdate=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nCritics have also noted the issue of [[False positives and false negatives|false positives]] within such systems, and their inability to account for copyright limitations such as [[fair dealing]] and [[parody]] (leading, they state, to a \"[[Internet meme|meme]] ban\").<ref name=\"CNET2018June22\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/article-13-europes-hotly-debated-eu-copyright-law-explained/|title=Everything you need to know about Europe's new meme-ending war|date=22 June 2018|accessdate=1 July 2018|website=CNET|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180624104448/https://www.cnet.com/news/article-13-europes-hotly-debated-eu-copyright-law-explained/|archive-date=24 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Supporters and third parties pointed out that YouTube has used Content ID for a decade and yet remains a successful host for content of all kinds.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://torrentfreak.com/censorship-machines-are-destroying-the-internet-as-we-speak-180624/|title=Censorship Machines are 'Destroying The Internet' As We Speak?|date=24 June 2018|work=TorrentFreak|access-date=23 July 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724032123/https://torrentfreak.com/censorship-machines-are-destroying-the-internet-as-we-speak-180624/|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the system still suffers from false positives, [[copyright trolls]], and scammers leveraging YouTube's handling of copyright claims under the U.S. [[Online Copyright Infringement Liability Limitation Act]] (OCILLA)\u2014a component of the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]] (DMCA)\u2014as a form of [[extortion]], by placing false copyright claims on a user's content until they pay a ransom (aiming to have the account taken down unless they pay), or [[doxxing]] by means of the requirement to include personal contact information when performing a counterclaim under this law.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wodinsky |first1=Shoshana |title=YouTube\u2019s copyright strikes have become a tool for extortion |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/11/18220032/youtube-copystrike-blackmail-three-strikes-copyright-violation |accessdate=20 February 2019 |work=The Verge |date=11 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220003031/https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/11/18220032/youtube-copystrike-blackmail-three-strikes-copyright-violation |archive-date=20 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe CEO of YouTube, [[Susan Wojcicki]], warned that the legislation \"poses a threat to both your livelihood and your ability to share your voice with the world\", and that under Article 13, the site may \u2014 even on content it does have a license to host \u2014 be required to clear every possible copyright associated with a video or be prevented from streaming it within the EU, and do the same at scale for every piece of video uploaded by users.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-warns-unintended-consequences-article-13-1202500444/|title=YouTube CEO Susan Wojcicki Warns Against \"Unintended Consequences\" Of EU's Article 13|last=Chmielewski|first=Dawn C.|last2=Chmielewski|first2=Dawn C.|date=12 November 2018|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043337/https://deadline.com/2018/11/youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-warns-unintended-consequences-article-13-1202500444/|archive-date=6 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The CEO of [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]], [[Emmett Shear]], has also criticised Article 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/video/2019/03/27/twitch-ceo-article-13/|title=Twitch CEO: Article 13 'Wrong Compromise' On Copyright Reform|last=Baran|first=Jonathan|date=2019-03-27|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\nAfter its passing, Pirate Party MEP [[Julia Reda]] pointed out that Article 13 may violate the Canada/EU [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA), which states that its parties must provide \"limitations or exceptions\" on the liability of intermediary communications service providers in regards to copyright infringement, and that they must not be \"conditioned on the service provider monitoring its service, or affirmatively seeking facts indicating infringing activity.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190412/07120341988/could-article-13s-upload-filters-be-thrown-out-because-eu-canada-trade-deal-ceta.shtml|title=Could Article 13's Upload Filters Be Thrown Out Because Of The EU-Canada Trade Deal CETA?|last=Moody|first=Moody|date=17 April 2019|website=Techdirt|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Public protests ===\n[[File:Protesto contra a reforma europeia do direito de autor, em especial os artigos 11 e 13, em Lisboa, Julho de 2018.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Public protests against article 11 and 13 in Lisbon in July 2018.]]\n[[File:Spontante Kundgebung in Hamburg gegen EU-Urheberrechtsvorhaben 3.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Protests in Hamburg on 6 March 2019 against the EU Copyright Directive]]\n\nA [[Change.org]] petition has gathered more than 5 million signatures {{As of|2019|March|21|lc=y|df=|since=}} which oppose the directive, of which roughly 1.3 million are from Germany.<ref name=Paper2019>{{cite news|url=http://paperjam.lu/news/le-choc-des-titans|title=Le choc des titans|date=31 January 2019|work=Paperjam News|language=fr|access-date=13 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213130908/http://paperjam.lu/news/le-choc-des-titans|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/wirtschaft/urherberrechtsreform-unterschriften-101.html |title=4,7 Millionen Unterschriften gegen Upload-Filter |website=[[Tagesschau (Germany)|Tagesschau]] |language=de |date=18 February 2019 |access-date=18 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218205526/https://www.tagesschau.de/wirtschaft/urherberrechtsreform-unterschriften-101.html |archive-date=18 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=Fort2019Mar21/> As of February 2019, it has gathered the most signatures in European history.<ref name=EFF2019Feb>{{cite web |last1=Doctorow |first1=Cory |title=The Worst Possible Version of the EU Copyright Directive Has Sparked a German Uprising |url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/02/worst-possible-version-eu-copyright-directive-has-sparked-german-uprising |website=Electronic Frontier Foundation |accessdate=24 February 2019 |language=en |date=18 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223233833/https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/02/worst-possible-version-eu-copyright-directive-has-sparked-german-uprising |archive-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nA number of public protests have been held in opposition to the proposed directive, mainly concerning Article 11 and 13. European wide protests on 23 March 2019 saw tens to hundreds of thousands of people marching.<ref name=\"Simon2019\">{{cite news |last1=Berlin |first1=Simon Hurtz |title=Dieser Protest k\u00f6nnte Artikel 13 stoppen |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/digital/upload-filter-urheberrecht-demo-berlin-1.4380487 |accessdate=23 March 2019 |work=sueddeutsche.de |date=2019 |language=de}}</ref> One estimate put the number at 40,000 people in Munich and 15,000 in Berlin.<ref name=\"ProtestsMar23\">{{cite news |last1=Welle (www.dw.com) |first1=Deutsche |title=EU copyright bill: Protests across Europe highlight rifts over reform plans {{!}} DW {{!}} 23 March 2019 |url=https://www.dw.com/en/eu-copyright-bill-protests-across-europe-highlight-rifts-over-reform-plans/a-48037133 |accessdate=23 March 2019 |work=DW.COM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323224602/https://www.dw.com/en/eu-copyright-bill-protests-across-europe-highlight-rifts-over-reform-plans/a-48037133 |archive-date=23 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Another estimate indicated 30,000 people in Berlin and more than 100,000 in Germany overall.<ref name=Simon2019/> A 16 February 2019 protest organised by German YouTube stars in [[Cologne]] attracted a significant crowd despite having only been announced two days earlier. German news media gave reports of attendance, with one report describing \"several hundred participants\", another \"over 1000\", and a third \"1500\" based on police reports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tag24.de/nachrichten/youtube-artikel-13-urheberrecht-zensur-demo-protest-in-koeln-975131|title=Was ist Artikel 13? Warum deutsche YouTube-Stars heute in K\u00f6ln auf die Barrikaden gehen|publisher=[[:de:TAG24|TAG24 NEWS]]|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220064211/https://www.tag24.de/nachrichten/youtube-artikel-13-urheberrecht-zensur-demo-protest-in-koeln-975131|archive-date=20 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=19 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Wir-sind-die-Bots-ueber-1000-demonstrieren-gegen-Artikel-13-4311105.html|title=\"Wir sind die Bots\" \u2013 \u00fcber 1000 demonstrieren gegen Artikel 13|date=16 February 2019|website=[[Heise Online]]|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217162603/https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Wir-sind-die-Bots-ueber-1000-demonstrieren-gegen-Artikel-13-4311105.html|archive-date=17 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Bla2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/diginomics/tausende-menschen-demonstrieren-gegen-urheberrechtsreform-16045816.html|title=\"Ich bin kein Bot\": Tausende Menschen protestieren gegen Urheberrechtsreform|last1=Blazekovic|first1=Jessica von|work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]|date=17 February 2019|accessdate=20 February 2019|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220103450/https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/diginomics/tausende-menschen-demonstrieren-gegen-urheberrechtsreform-16045816.html|archive-date=20 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A second protest in Cologne on 23 February 2019 had a reported attendance of more than 3000.<ref name=Hei2019>{{cite web |url=https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Dieser-Bot-geht-waehlen-3000-demonstrieren-in-Koeln-gegen-Urheberrechtsreform-4316858.html |title=\"Dieser Bot geht w\u00e4hlen\" \u2013 3000 demonstrieren in K\u00f6ln gegen Urheberrechtsreform |website=[[Heise Online]] |date=23 February 2019 |access-date=23 February 2019 |last=Kleinz |first=Torsten |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224062536/https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Dieser-Bot-geht-waehlen-3000-demonstrieren-in-Koeln-gegen-Urheberrechtsreform-4316858.html |archive-date=24 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Demonstrators attributed problems of the bill to Axel Voss and the CDU party.<ref name=Hei2019/> A protest in Berlin on 2 March attracted roughly 3,500.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.zdf.de/nachrichten/heute/tausende-menschen-demonstrieren-gegen-uploadfilter-100.html |title=Demo gegen Urheberrechtsreform - Tausende wehren sich gegen Artikel 13 |date=2 March 2019 |access-date=2 March 2019 |work=[[ZDF]] |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303124652/https://www.zdf.de/nachrichten/heute/tausende-menschen-demonstrieren-gegen-uploadfilter-100.html |archive-date=3 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The protests are being organised by a grassroots movement and are raising funds by [[Gofundme]].<ref name=Hei2019/>\n\nAfter the [[European People's Party]] tried to move the vote on the directive ahead to circumvent the planned protests on 23 March 2019,<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1102951601663369217|user=Senficon|title=Here is written proof that @EPPGroup tried to move the vote on #copyright & #Article13 ahead to next week. Apparently they're denying it now, so either your public outcry impressed them, or they figured out that the translations won't be ready in time. #SaveYourInternet [Repost]|author=Julia Reda|date=5 March 2019|author-link=Julia Reda|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Beuth |first1=Ein Kommentar Patrick |title=EU-Urheberrechtsreform: Der Zorn der \u00dcbergangenen |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/posse-um-urheberrechtsreform-die-evp-hat-sich-die-wut-der-buerger-verdient-a-1256412.html |accessdate=8 March 2019 |work=Spiegel Online |date=5 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308001125/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/posse-um-urheberrechtsreform-die-evp-hat-sich-die-wut-der-buerger-verdient-a-1256412.html |archive-date=8 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> demonstrations were organised at short notice in ten German cities, including Berlin, between 5 and 9 March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://savetheinternet.info/demos |title=Demos |website=Savetheinternet.info |access-date=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306042952/https://savetheinternet.info/demos |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Following public protests, the European People's Party claimed that they did not try to move the vote forwards despite evidence to the contrary.<ref>{{cite web |title=UPDATED! How do you pass the most unpopular measure in European history? With the most undemocratic dirty trick in EU history: stop the #Article13 vote from being moved ahead of day of protest! |url=https://boingboing.net/2019/03/04/march-23-march.html |website=Boing Boing |accessdate=8 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305144704/https://boingboing.net/2019/03/04/march-23-march.html |archive-date=5 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=Tech2019Mar5>{{cite web |title=Supporters Of Article 13 Briefly Tried To Move Parliament Vote Up Before Scheduled Protests; Now Deny Plan That They Clearly Had |url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190304/15233741731/supporters-article-13-briefly-tried-to-move-parliament-vote-up-before-scheduled-protests-now-deny-plan-that-they-clearly-had.shtml |website=Techdirt. |accessdate=8 March 2019 |date=5 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308224100/https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190304/15233741731/supporters-article-13-briefly-tried-to-move-parliament-vote-up-before-scheduled-protests-now-deny-plan-that-they-clearly-had.shtml |archive-date=8 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Additionally, the request to move the vote forwards may not have been withdrawn as of 5 March 2019.<ref name=Tech2019Mar5/>\n\nSmaller prior EU-wide events occurred in August 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://juliareda.eu/2018/08/saveyourinternet-action-day/|title=People are taking to the streets on August 26th to #SaveYourInternet \u2013 join in!|last=Reda|first=Julia|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021334/https://juliareda.eu/2018/08/saveyourinternet-action-day/|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref> and January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stopacta2.org/stopacta2-events/|title=#stopACTA2 events|date=24 August 2018|website=stop ACTA2 - Save Your Internet|language=en-US|access-date=15 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115182153/https://www.stopacta2.org/stopacta2-events/|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Organisers did not release their own figures, but supporters of the proposals based on photos from the August events estimated that there had been at most 800 participants across the continent, with an average of 30 per location.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webschauder.de/astroturf-instead-of-grass-roots-when-clicktivism-meets-hard-reality/|title=Astroturf instead of grass roots: When clicktivism meets hard reality|website=WebSchauder|language=de-DE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218081933/http://webschauder.de/astroturf-instead-of-grass-roots-when-clicktivism-meets-hard-reality/|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral European websites, including the European versions of [[Wikipedia]], [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]], and [[Reddit]], disabled some or many of the features on their websites on 21 March 2019 as a means to protest and raise awareness of the pending vote and encourage users to contact their appropriate national body to affect the vote. This was similar to action taken on 18 January 2012 by numerous websites to [[Protests against SOPA and PIPA|protest similar laws proposed in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/21/18275462/eu-copyright-directive-protest-wikipedia-twitch-pornhub-final-vote | title = European Wikipedias have been turned off for the day to protest dangerous copyright laws | first = James | last = Vincent | date = 21 March 2019 | accessdate = 21 March 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190321125952/https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/21/18275462/eu-copyright-directive-protest-wikipedia-twitch-pornhub-final-vote | archive-date = 21 March 2019 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Lobbying ===\nThe [[European Parliament]] claimed that \"MEPs have rarely or even never been subject to a similar degree of lobbying\", and that there have been prior \"lobbying campaigns predicting catastrophic outcomes, which have never come true\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20190111IPR23225/questions-and-answers-on-issues-about-the-digital-copyright-directive|title=Questions and Answers on issues about the digital copyright directive|date=1 November 2019|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021421/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20190111IPR23225/questions-and-answers-on-issues-about-the-digital-copyright-directive|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' reported that \"Google is helping to fund a website that encourages people to spam politicians and newspapers with automated messages backing its policy goals\".<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-funds-activist-site-that-pushes-its-views-rg2g5cr6t|title=Google funds website that spams for its causes|last=Media&nbsp;Correspondent|first=Matthew Moore|date=6 August 2018|work=The Times|access-date=10 August 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810214845/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-funds-activist-site-that-pushes-its-views-rg2g5cr6t|archive-date=10 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> MEP [[Sven Schulze]] stated that he believed Google to be behind the email campaign because many of the emails came from [[Gmail]] addresses.<ref name=Bla2019/>\n\nLobbying in favour of the proposed directive was directed toward the EU itself and was much less visible to the public. The large media groups and publishers have had much greater contact between their [[lobbyists]] and MEPs than the technology industry.<ref name=Corp2019/> Stunts pulled by those lobbying in favour include sending MEPs pamphlets with condoms attached with the phrase \u201cWe love tech giants, we love protection too\u201d.<ref name=\"Corp2019\" />\n\nThe [[EU Commission]], in a since withdrawn [[blog post]], stated that those who opposed the directive were a \"mob\".<ref name=Ind2019>{{cite news |title=EU takes down strange, 'offensive' blog post attacking internet campaigners |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/eu-copyright-rules-blog-post-commission-article-11-13-latest-a8786256.html |accessdate=24 February 2019 |work=The Independent |date=19 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224183452/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/eu-copyright-rules-blog-post-commission-article-11-13-latest-a8786256.html |archive-date=24 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/streit-ueber-artikel-13-wer-braucht-schon-argumente-a-1255608.html |title=Streit \u00fcber Artikel 13: Wer braucht schon Argumente? |newspaper=[[Spiegel Online]] |last=Beuth |first=Patrick |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228184545/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/streit-ueber-artikel-13-wer-braucht-schon-argumente-a-1255608.html |archive-date=28 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The [[Commissioners]] technically responsible for such posts, [[Mariya Gabriel]] and [[Andrus Ansip]], both deny authorizing its publication.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schmihing |first1=Carina |title=Youtuber: Wie sich PietSmiet, RobBubble und Co. gegen Artikel 13 wehren |url=https://www.nw.de/blogs/games_und_netzwelt/22385030_Youtuber-Wie-sich-PietSmiet-RobBubble-und-Co.-gegen-Artikel-13-wehren.html |website=Games & Netzwelt |accessdate=24 February 2019 |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224062438/https://www.nw.de/blogs/games_und_netzwelt/22385030_Youtuber-Wie-sich-PietSmiet-RobBubble-und-Co.-gegen-Artikel-13-wehren.html |archive-date=24 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The European Commission has also apologized for its publication.<ref name=Ind2019/> [[Jean-Claude Juncker]], the head of the [[EU Commission]] declined after a direct request to answer who authorized its publication.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Masnick |first1=Mike |title=EU Commission Refuses To Explain Why It Published Medium Article Mocking The Public's Concerns Over Article 13 |url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190321/16154741848/eu-commission-refuses-to-explain-why-it-published-medium-article-mocking-publics-concerns-over-article-13.shtml |website=Techdirt. |accessdate=23 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322230758/https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190321/16154741848/eu-commission-refuses-to-explain-why-it-published-medium-article-mocking-publics-concerns-over-article-13.shtml |archive-date=22 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nSome commentators stated years of intense lobbying served to \"crowd out other voices and successfully distort the public debate\", and that \"toxic\" discussions were harming \"healthy dialogue\".<ref name=\"Corp2019\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/copyright-platforms-eu-google-winners-and-losers-of-europes-copyright-reform/|title=Winners and losers of Europe's copyright reform|last=Kayali|first=Laura|date=14 February 2019|website=POLITICO|access-date=17 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021415/https://www.politico.eu/article/copyright-platforms-eu-google-winners-and-losers-of-europes-copyright-reform/|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Those in support of the directive, however, carried out negotiations without public oversight.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Doctorow |first1=Cory |title=That German-French Deal to \"Rescue\" the EU Copyright Directive? Everyone Hates It. EVERYONE. |url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/02/german-french-deal-rescue-eu-copyright-directive-everyone-hates-it-everyone |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=Electronic Frontier Foundation |date=7 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320092740/https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/02/german-french-deal-rescue-eu-copyright-directive-everyone-hates-it-everyone |archive-date=20 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> And when the general public became involved in discussing the directive online the EU commission referred to them as a \"mob\".<ref>{{cite news |title=EU takes down strange, 'offensive' blog post attacking internet campaigners |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/eu-copyright-rules-blog-post-commission-article-11-13-latest-a8786256.html |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=The Independent |date=19 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316142612/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/eu-copyright-rules-blog-post-commission-article-11-13-latest-a8786256.html |archive-date=16 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n=== Voting issues ===\nBefore the vote on the directive, a vote was held on whether to consider amendments, which would have allowed the possibility of separating Articles 11 and 13 into separate votes. The proposal fell short by 5 votes. It was reported after the fact that 13 MEPs had requested that their votes be changed, since they voted incorrectly due to alleged confusion over the order of voting. The revised results added 10 votes in favour of amendments. However, these corrections are strictly for parliamentary records only, and do not change the result of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/mar/27/mep-errors-mean-european-copyright-law-may-not-have-passed|title=MEPs accidentally vote wrong way on copyright law|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=2019-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/button-pushing-errors-affected-copyright-reform-vote-record-shows/|title=Button-pushing errors affected copyright reform vote, record shows|last=Vinocur|first=Nicholas|date=2019-03-27|website=Politico.eu|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190326/15193241877/enough-meps-say-they-mistakenly-voted-articles-11-13-that-vote-should-have-flipped-eu-parliament-says-too-bad.shtml|title=Enough MEPs Say They Mistakenly Voted For Articles 11 & 13 That The Vote Should Have Flipped; EU Parliament Says Too Bad|first=Mike|last=Masnick|website=Techdirt|date=26 March 2019|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Bomb threat ===\nAccording to German media reports, an online bomb threat was posted against Axel Voss' office in [[Bonn]] claiming that a bomb had been placed at the office, and it would be detonated should the EU Parliament vote to back the proposed copyright reforms. The message had originally been posted on an obscure Finnish Linux Forum, before being brought to wider attention on [[Reddit]]. It has since been removed while an investigation by regional police was initiated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/copyright-mep-in-bomb-threat-scare/|title=Copyright MEP in bomb threat scare|first=Samuel|last=Stolton|date=19 March 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom position ===\nOn 31 January 2020, the United Kingdom left the European Union. The [[transition period]] is scheduled to expire on 31 December 2020. The UK Government has therefore declared that, since the date for EU member states to transpose the directive into national law is in 2021, the UK will not be implementing the copyright directive in full.  Government minister [[Chris Skidmore]] stated that \n{{quote|\"The deadline for implementing the EU Copyright Directive is 7 June 2021. The United Kingdom will leave the European Union on 31 January 2020 and the Implementation Period will end on 31 December 2020. The Government has committed not to extend the Implementation Period. Therefore, the United Kingdom will not be required to implement the Directive, and the Government has no plans to do so. Any future changes to the UK copyright framework will be considered as part of the usual domestic policy process.\"<ref name =Bird />}} \nUK Culture Minister [[Nigel Adams]] said that, despite the Government supporting many of the overall aims of the directive, the UK\u2019s 'imminent departure from the EU means we are not required to implement the Copyright Directive in full'.<ref name =Bird>{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=7cbde598-9ca2-421b-8bc3-eee4a836bb1e | title = UK Government \u201chas no plans\u201d to implement the Copyright Directive |publisher= Bird & Bird LLP | author =William Wortley| date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Legal challenge ==\nOn 24 May 2019, [[Poland]] filed an action for annulment of the Directive with the [[Court of Justice of the European Union]].<ref name=\":19\"/> [[Foreign minister|Deputy Foreign Minister]] of Poland Konrad Szymanski said the directive \"may result in adopting regulations that are analogous to preventive censorship, which is forbidden not only in the [[Constitution of Poland|Polish constitution]] but also in the EU treaties\" on [[public broadcaster]] [[TVP Info]].<ref name=\":19\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-copyright-poland-idUSKCN1SU0T9|title=Poland files complaint with EU's top court over copyright rule change|date=2019-05-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-05-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Impact on media ==\nIn November 2019, [[News Media Alliance]] published an analysis of traffic received by eight Spanish websites whose news articles had been redistributed by Google News until it ceased operations in 2014 in response to a similar regulation introduced by Spanish lawmakers. Alliance data covering the period from 2014-2019 has demonstrated that publishers have not only continued the same amount of unique views with or without Google News, but also the amount of traffic has increased in some cases, especially the most valuable direct traffic as compared to less profitable referral traffic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsmediaalliance.org/google-news-shutdown-in-spain-not-as-bad-as-google-would-have-you-believe/|title=Google News Shutdown in Spain Was Not as Bad as Google Would Have You Believe|last=Munter|first=Johannes|date=2019-11-14|website=News Media Alliance|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Copyright law of the European Union]]\n* [[Copyright Directive (disambiguation)]] (lists the EU directives on copyright)\n* [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]] of 1998 (\"updates but does not replace the 11 directives which together comprise the EU\u2019s copyright legislation.\")\n* [[Electronic Commerce Directive 2000|Electronic Commerce Directive]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last=Romero-Moreno |first=Felipe |date=29 May 2018 |title='Notice and staydown' and social media: amending Article 13 of the Proposed Directive on Copyright |journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology |pages=1\u201324 |doi-access=free |doi=10.1080/13600869.2018.1475906 |issn=1360-0869 |hdl-access=free |hdl=2299/20431}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Romero-Moreno |first=Felipe |date=17 March 2020 |title='Upload filters' and human rights: implementing Article 17 of the Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market |journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology |pages=1\u201331 |doi-access=free |doi=10.1080/13600869.2020.1733760|issn=1360-0869 |hdl-access=free |hdl=2299/20431}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{cite web |title=Final text of the Directive as submitted to the Parliament on 26 March 2019|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf |accessdate=26 March 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://fixcopyright.wikimedia.org/?title=Fix_copyright&uselang=en|title=Wikimedia Public Policy: It's time for an update. Tell the European Parliament to fix copyright.|access-date=11 Sep 2018|language=en|quotation=On 12 September, the European Parliament will vote on changes to a copyright law that will dictate how we communicate in the digital age}} (translated in 24 languages)\n* [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/oeil/popups/ficheprocedure.do?lang=&reference=2016/0280(COD) Procedure file]\n*{{URL|http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf|The text of the European Council proposal as of 3 March 2019}}\n*{{URL|http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35373/st09134-en18.pdf|The text of the European Council proposal as of 25 May 2018}}\n*{{URL|1=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=REPORT&mode=XML&reference=A8-2018-0245&language=EN|2=The text of European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs's proposed negotiating position}}\n*{{URL|https://edri.org/copyright-reform-document-pool/|Copyright reform document pool}}\n*{{URL|https://petiport.secure.europarl.europa.eu/petitions/en/petition/content/0424%252F2018/html/Petition-No-0424%252F2018-by-P.-Z.-%2528Polish%2529-on-deleting-Article-11-and-Article-13-from-the-draft-Directive-on-Copyright-in-the-Digital-Single-Market | Petition against Artikel 11 and 13}} on the Petitions Web Portal of the [[European Parliament Committee on Petitions]]\n\n{{Intellectual property laws of the European Union}}\n{{Portal bar|European Union|Law|Technology|Internet|Politics}}\n\n[[Category:Copyright legislation]]\n[[Category:European Single Market| ]]\n[[Category:Economy of the European Union]]\n[[Category:European Union telecommunications policy]]\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n[[Category:Copyright law of the European Union]]\n[[Category:European Union directives]]\n[[Category:2019 controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 2019 Directive|the 2001 Directive|Information Society Directive}}\n{{short description|2019 EU copyright reform directive}}\n{{use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox EU legislation\n| number              = 2019/790\n| type                = directive\n| EEA                 = yes\n| title               = Directive (EU) 2019/790 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 17 April 2019 on copyright and related rights in the Digital Single Market and amending Directives 96/9/EC and 2001/29/EC\n| Parties             = \n| madeby              = \n| madeunder           = Articles 53(1), 62 and 114\n| OJrefurl            = \n| OJref               = [https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=OJ:L:2019:130:TOC L 130, 17 May 2019]\n| EEATreaty           = \n| EEADec              = \n| made                = {{dts|17 April 2019}}\n| commenced           = {{dts|6 June 2019}}\n| implementation      = within 2 years after coming into force\n| EPVote={{Composition bar|348|622|hex=#00FF00}}\n| application         = \n| CommProp            = \n| ESCOpin             = \n| CROpin              = \n| ParlOpin            = \n| Reports             = \n| replaces            = \n| amends              = [[Database Directive]] (Directive 96/9)<br>[[Information Society Directive]] (Directive 2001/29/EC)\n| amendedby           = \n| replacedby          = \n| status              = in force (implementation pending)\n}}\nThe '''Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market''', formally the '''Directive (EU) 2019/790 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 17 April 2019 on copyright and related rights in the Digital Single Market and amending Directives 96/9/EC and 2001/29/EC''' is a [[European Union]] (EU) [[Directive (European Union)|directive]] which has been adopted and came into force on 7 June 2019. It is intended to ensure \"a well-functioning marketplace for copyright\".<ref name=\"EC2016\">{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A52016PC0593|title=Proposal for a Directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on copyright in the Digital Single Market|author=[[European Commission]]|date=14 September 2016|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623032844/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A52016PC0593|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It extends existing [[copyright law of the European Union|European Union copyright law]] and is a component of the EU's [[Digital Single Market]] project.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/eu-copyright-legislation |title=The EU copyright legislation |author=European Commission |access-date=4 July 2018 |date=28 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705032942/https://ec.europa.eu/digital-single-market/en/eu-copyright-legislation |archive-date=5 July 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The [[European Council]] (EC) describes their key goals with the Directive as protecting press publications; reducing the \"value gap\" between the profits made by Internet platforms and by content creators; encouraging collaboration between these two groups, and creating [[copyright exceptions]] for [[text and data mining|text- and data-mining]].<ref name=\"EUJune252\">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|title=Copyright rules for the digital environment: Council agrees its position \u2013 Consilium|publisher=Europa (web portal)|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613171238/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|archive-date=13 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe directive was introduced by the [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] on 20 June 2018, and a revised proposal was approved by the parliament on 12 September 2018. The final version, which resulted from negotiations during [[formal trilogue meeting]]s, was presented to the parliament on 13 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU reaches provisional deal on online copyright reform |url=http://afp.omni.se/eu-reaches-provisional-deal-on-online-copyright-reform/a/Eo11J3 |website=afp.omni.se |accessdate=14 February 2019 |language=sv |date=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214233336/http://afp.omni.se/eu-reaches-provisional-deal-on-online-copyright-reform/a/Eo11J3 |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The measure was approved by on 26 March 2019<ref name=\"wired-13pass\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/eu-article-13-passed-meme-war|title=The EU has passed Article 13, but Europe's meme war is far from over|last=Volpicelli|first=Gian|access-date=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912151840/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/eu-article-13-passed-meme-war|archive-date=12 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"verge finalvote mar19\">{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/26/18280726/europe-copyright-directive | title=  Europe\u2019s controversial overhaul of online copyright receives final approval | first =James | last =Vincent | date = 26 March 2019 | accessdate = 26 March 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-47708144|title=EU backs controversial copyright law|last=Kleinman|first=Zoe|date=2019-03-26|work=BBC|access-date=2019-03-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the directive was approved by the [[Council of the European Union]] on 15 April 2019.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/15/article-13-eu-council-backs-copyright-law-that-could-hit-youtube-fb.html|title=Article 13: EU Council backs copyright law that could hit YouTube, FB|last=Browne|first=Ryan|date=2019-04-15|website=CNBC|access-date=2019-04-15}}</ref> Member states have two years to pass appropriate legislation to meet the Directive's requirements.<ref name=\"internationalinsider.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://internationalinsider.org/2019/10/15/digital-single-market-copyright-directive-eu-to-start-dialogue-with-stakeholder/|title=Digital Single Market Copyright Directive: EU to start dialogue with stakeholder|date=2019-10-15|website=International Insider|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\nCopyright guarantees that writers, composers, musicians, filmmakers and other creators are acknowledged, compensated and protected for their work.<ref name=\"internationalinsider.org\"/>\n\nThe directive has generally been supported by newspapers, publishers, and media groups but opposed by major tech companies and some Internet users, as well as human rights advocates. Two of the Directive's articles have drawn significant discussion. Draft Article 11 (Article 15 of the directive), known as the \"link tax\", gives newspapers more direct control and re-use of their product, which may impact some Internet services like [[news aggregator]]s. Draft Article 13 (Article 17 of the directive) tasks service providers that host [[user-generated content]] to employ \"effective and proportionate\" measures to prevent users from violating copyright. Tech companies expressed concern that this would necessitate the need for upload filters at their current scales. A broad concern with the Directive is on the use of [[fair dealing]] through the directive, and that it could quell freedom of speech.\n\n== History ==\n===Background===\nThe European Union's (EU) first attempt to unify copyrights in light of digital technologies was adopted in 2001 as the [[Information Society Directive|Information Society Directive 2001/29/EC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-01-528_en.htm|title=Commission welcomes adoption of the Directive on copyright in the information society by the Council|author=[[European Commission]]|date=4 July 2018|access-date=4 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705062644/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-01-528_en.htm|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The Directive's major objectives were to harmonise EU legislation with international law (as set by the 1996 [[World Intellectual Property Organization]] treaties), to strengthen intellectual property protection, to reduce conflicts in copyright laws between member states, and to assure adequate remuneration to content producers.<ref name=\"CESP 2015\">{{cite report | url = https://www.ceps.eu/system/files/SR120_0.pdf | title = The Implementation, Application and Effects of the EU Directive on Copyright in the Information Society | authors = Andrea Renda, Felice Simonelli, Giuseppe Mazziotti, Alberto Bolognini and Giacomo Luchetta | publisher = [[Centre for European Policy Studies]] | date = November 2015 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180913223259/https://www.ceps.eu/system/files/SR120_0.pdf | archivedate = 13 September 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> While some parts of the 2001 Directive were effective, other parts of the directive were not satisfactory for the current digital market long after its implementation. In 2012, the [[European Commission]] (EC) announced that they would be reviewing the 2001 Directive and having stakeholder discussions in light of several issues raised with failed copyright proposals from those in the [[European Commissioner for Internal Market and Services]] position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/battle-on-eu-copyright-law-re-opened-by-commission/|title=Battle on EU copyright law re-opened by Commission|date=5 December 2012|work=POLITICO|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005238/https://www.politico.eu/article/battle-on-eu-copyright-law-re-opened-by-commission/|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The EC took public comments from December 2013 through March 2014, and published its first report on the state of the EU copyright law in July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/internal_market/consultations/2013/copyright-rules/docs/contributions/consultation-report_en.pdf|title=Report on the responses to the Public Consultation on the Review of the EU Copyright Rules|last=Directorate General Internal Market and Services Directorate D \u2013 Intellectual property D1|date=July 2014|url-status=live|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005034/http://ec.europa.eu/internal_market/consultations/2013/copyright-rules/docs/contributions/consultation-report_en.pdf|archive-date=23 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] was elected to the [[President of the European Commission|presidency of the European Commission]] and took office in November 2014.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-27679170 | title = Profile: EU's Jean-Claude Juncker | date = 15 July 2014 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = BBC | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181101003046/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-27679170 | archive-date = 1 November 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In his campaign position, Juncker saw the potential to \"improve\" the EU's financial status by harmonising the various digital marketplaces among member nations to create job opportunities and drive a knowledge-based society. Juncker appointed Estonian politician, [[Andrus Ansip]], as Vice-President for the Digital Single Market within the EC that year, tasked with working with [[G\u00fcnther Oettinger]], [[European Commissioner for Digital Economy and Society]], and other sections within the EC to come up with the necessary legislative steps that would be required to implement a Digital Single Market.<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-523_en.htm | title = Questions and Answers: The Juncker Commission | date = 10 September 2014 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = [[European Commission]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180827115040/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-523_en.htm | archive-date = 27 August 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Initial plans for the legislative steps and their potential impact were announced by the EC in May 2015. Ansip stated that by the implementation of a Digital Single Market, they could increase the European [[gross domestic product]] by as much as {{\u20ac|415{{nbsp}}billion|link=yes}} per year.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/may/06/eu-unveils-plans-digital-single-market-online-firms | title = EU unveils plans to set up digital single market for online firms | first = Ian | last = Traynor | date = 6 May 2015 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | work = [[The Guardian]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180704093514/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/may/06/eu-unveils-plans-digital-single-market-online-firms | archive-date = 4 July 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?qid=1447773803386&uri=CELEX:52015DC0192|title=Communication from the Commission to the European Parliament, the Council, the European Economic and Social Committee and the Committee of the Regions \u2013 A Digital Single Market Strategy for Europe|date=6 May 2015|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|series=COM/2015/0192|url-status=live|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623004904/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?qid=1447773803386&uri=CELEX:52015DC0192|archive-date=23 June 2018}}</ref> The [[European Parliament]], following up on a report on the state of European Copyright from a [[member of the European Parliament]] (MEP), [[Julia Reda]], that identified several inadequacies of the 2001 Information Society Directive, affirmed support for the EC's goal of a Digital Single Market as well as supporting an initiative with the EP for similar copyright reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&reference=P8-TA-2015-0273&language=EN&ring=A8-2015-0209|title=European Parliament resolution of 9 July 2015 on the implementation of Directive 2001/29/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 22 May 2001 on the harmonisation of certain aspects of copyright and related rights in the information society (2014/2256(INI))|date=9 July 2015|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142725/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&reference=P8-TA-2015-0273&language=EN&ring=A8-2015-0209|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The EC subsequently began working on establishing the legal framework by the end of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=COM:2015:626:FIN|title=Communication from the Commission to the European Parliament, the Council, the European Economic and Social Committee and the Committee of the Regions \u2013 Towards a modern, more European copyright framework|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|series=COM/2015/0626|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623032857/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=COM:2015:626:FIN}}</ref>\n\n===Legislative process===\n[[File:Vote on the new Copyright regulation (46754387104).jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Approval of the measure by the European Parliament in [[Strasbourg]], 26 March 2019]]\n\nThe directive fell within the [[ordinary legislative procedure]], and thus was to be approved by both the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union. While the European Parliament had to pass the Directive with a simple majority, in the Council a [[qualified majority]] was needed: at least 55% of the countries, representing over 65% of the population.\n\nThe first draft of the proposed Directive from the EC was issued on 14 September 2016,<ref>{{cite report | url = https://ec.europa.eu/transparency/regdoc/rep/1/2016/EN/1-2016-593-EN-F1-1.PDF | title = Proposal for a Directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on Copyright in the Digital Single Market | date = 14 September 2016 | accessdate = 13 September 2018 | publisher = [[European Commission]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180822171925/http://ec.europa.eu/transparency/regdoc/rep/1/2016/EN/1-2016-593-EN-F1-1.PDF | archivedate = 22 August 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Following revisions, the [[Council of the European Union]]'s [[Committee of Permanent Representatives]] (COREPER) approved of the EC's legislative directives on 25 May 2018 and prepared to bring the matter to vote in the EP,<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35373/st09134-en18.pdf|title=Proposal for a directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market|date=25 May 2018|page=26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609084910/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35373/st09134-en18.pdf|archive-date=9 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> to reach a final text, without the support of Germany, Finland, the Netherlands, Slovenia, Belgium, or Hungary.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=22 June 2018|title=EU Council agrees Copyright Directive position|url=https://www.create.ac.uk/eu-council-agrees-copyright-directive-position/|newspaper=CREATe|date=29 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623004703/https://www.create.ac.uk/eu-council-agrees-copyright-directive-position/|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] finalised their amendments to the directive on 20 June 2018 and put them toward the parliament for negotiation.<ref name=\"EUJune25\">{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|title=Copyright rules for the digital environment: Council agrees its position|date=25 May 2018|publisher=[[European Council]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613171238/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/copyright-rules-for-the-digital-environment-council-agrees-its-position/|archive-date=13 June 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]] voted on 5 July 2018 not to proceed to the negotiation stage, but instead to reopen the directive for debate in September 2018.<ref name=\"theguardianeuvote\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|title=YouTube and Facebook escape billions in copyright payouts after EU vote|last=Sweney|first=Mark|last2=Rankin|first2=Jennifer|date=5 July 2018|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|access-date=5 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724094528/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"rejectjuly-5-2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=MEPs reject EU copyright reforms in victory for internet giants|last=Khan|first=Mehreen|date=5 July 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234046/https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref> There were 318 votes to re-open the debate, 278 to proceed, and 31 abstentions.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44712475|title=EU's controversial copyright plan rejected|date=5 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705230728/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44712475|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/eu-parlament-zu-urheberrecht-umstrittene-reform-ueberraschend-ausgebremst-a-1216741.html |title=EU-Parlament bremst Urheberrechtsreform aus |access-date=6 July 2018 |date=5 July 2018 |last=B\u00f6hm |first=Markus |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706071756/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/eu-parlament-zu-urheberrecht-umstrittene-reform-ueberraschend-ausgebremst-a-1216741.html |archive-date=6 July 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 September 2018, an updated position of the parliament was approved with the final vote being 438{{Nbsp}}in favour and 226{{Nbsp}}against,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/12/17849868/eu-internet-copyright-reform-article-11-13-approved|title=EU approves controversial Copyright Directive, including internet 'link tax' and 'upload filter'|date=12 September 2018|last=Vincent|first=James|website=The Verge|accessdate=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912113116/https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/12/17849868/eu-internet-copyright-reform-article-11-13-approved|archive-date=12 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> meaning that [[Formal trilogue meeting|trilogue negotiations]] can start between the [[European Commission]], the [[Council of the European Union]] and the [[European Parliament]], with an expected conclusion in early 2019. Should the three groups agree to the final language, then the directive will be sent to governments of the twenty-eight{{Nbsp}}member states to be passed as laws within those countries, with each country formalising certain processes as necessary to meet their existing laws.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/09/european-parliament-approves-copyright-bill-slammed-by-digital-rights-groups/ | title = What's in the sweeping copyright bill just passed by the European Parliament | first = Timothy | last = Lee | date = 12 September 2018 | accessdate = 12 September 2018 | work = [[Ars Technica]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180912163937/https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/09/european-parliament-approves-copyright-bill-slammed-by-digital-rights-groups/ | archive-date = 12 September 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nInitial trilogue meetings overseen by Romania were scheduled to start on 21 January 2019, however, on 19 January 2019, Romania cancelled these meetings following the rejection of Romania's proposed compromise text by eleven countries: Germany, Belgium, the Netherlands, Finland, Slovenia, Italy, [[Poland]], Sweden, Croatia, Luxembourg and Portugal. With the exclusion of Portugal and Croatia, the other nine countries rejected the compromised text for Articles 11 and/or 13 stating that the measures did not do enough to do to protect their citizens' copyright protections. Romania had the opportunity to revise their text to gain a majority vote, delaying the vote.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.engadget.com/2019/01/19/eu-copyright-directive-rejected-at-council/ | title = EU copyright laws face uncertain fate after 11 countries reject proposal | first = Jon | last = Fingas | date = 19 January 2019 | accessdate = 19 January 2019 | work = [[Engadget]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190120074753/https://www.engadget.com/2019/01/19/eu-copyright-directive-rejected-at-council/ | archive-date = 20 January 2019 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe trilogue negotiations were completed on 13 February 2019, the final text still retaining the controversial Articles 11 and 13.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20190226IPR28811/copyright-meps-back-provisional-agreement | title = Copyright: MEPs back provisional agreement | website = europarl.europa.eu | date = 26 February 2019 | access-date = 26 February 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190227060644/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20190226IPR28811/copyright-meps-back-provisional-agreement | archive-date = 27 February 2019 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> At this point, the text was reviewed by the [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]], and then presented to the full European Parliament for a vote. The vote in Parliament was held on 26 March 2019, with the Directive passing by a vote of 348 MPs to 274<ref>[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//NONSGML+PV+20190326+RES-VOT+DOC+PDF+V0//EN&language=EN voting results] on page 8</ref> against.<ref name=\"wired-13pass\" /><ref name=\"verge finalvote mar19\"/><ref name=\":15\"/> After corrections of mistaken votes, the result was a vote of 338 MPs to 284.<ref name=\"VotesCorrections\">[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//NONSGML+PV+20190326+RES-RCV+DOC+PDF+V0//EN&language=EN voting results with corrections (end of page 53)] on page 52-53</ref> The main support for the directive came from the centre-right ([[European People's Party group|EPP]]). In terms of countries, most votes in favour came from France (62), Italy (39), Germany (38), Spain (34) and the UK (31), while the most votes against it came from Germany (49), Poland (33), UK (30), Italy (27) and the Netherlands (17).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.votewatch.eu/en/term8-copyright-in-the-digital-single-market-draft-legislative-resolution-provisional-agreement-amendment-.html#/##vote-tabs-list-1 |title=Copyright in the Digital Single Market |accessdate=30 Mar 2019 |publisher=Votewatch Europe}}</ref> While there had been an additional vote on an amendment to have a separate vote on the inclusion of the two controversial Articles (draft Articles 11 and 13, Directive Articles 15 and 17), the amendment narrowly failed to pass, with at least 13 MEPs stating they mistakenly voted the wrong way on this vote; if these had been voted as the MEP had intended, the amendment would have passed and required the additional vote.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/27/18283837/europe-copyright-directive-accidental-vote-meps-amendment | title = Ten European lawmakers say they voted against pivotal copyright amendment by accident | first = James | last = Vincent | date = 27 March 2019 | accessdate = 27 March 2019 | website = [[The Verge]] }}</ref>\n\n; Voting results in the European Parliament without corrections on 26 March 2019 by political groups<ref name=\"VotesCorrections\" />\n(<span style=\"background:green;color:#FFF\">In favour</span>/<span style=\"background:red;color:#FFF\">against</span> DSM copyright directive)\n{{Graph:Chart|width=900|height=200|xAxisTitle=Political group|yAxisTitle=number of EP members|type=stackedrect|x=EPP (153:28), S&D (99:54), ECR (23:42), ALDE (36:25), Greens-EFA (4:39), GUE-NGL (5:36), EFDD (6:28), ENF (15:14), Non-attached (7:8) |y1=153,99,23,36,4,5,6,15,7|y2=28,54,42,25,39,36,28,14,8|y3=36,34,10,7,9,11,7,8,7|y1Title=Votes in favour|y2Title=Votes against|y3Title=Abstention or not present|colors=green,red,gray|legend=Colours}}\n\n[[File:Copyright DSM Council Vote.svg|thumb|400px|Voting in the Council on 15 April. Besides voting against, [[Finland]], [[Italy]], [[Luxembourg]], the [[Netherlands]] and [[Poland]] have released a joint statement opposing the final draft of the directive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.permanentrepresentations.nl/documents/policy-notes/2019/02/20/joint-statement-regarding-the-copyright-directive|title=Joint statement on the Directive of the European Parliament and Council on copyright in the Digital Single Market - Policy document - The Netherlands at International Organisations|last=Zaken|first=Ministerie van Buitenlandse|date=2019-02-20|website=www.permanentrepresentations.nl|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref>|alt=]]\nThe Directive was approved by the [[Council of the European Union]] on 15 April 2019.<ref name=\":17\" /> 19 member states (representing 71% of the EU population in the countries that cast a vote) voted in favour of the Directive with six opposing and three abstaining.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nThe Directive will enter into force on 7 June 2019.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/25/18639963/poland-european-union-copyright-directive-filed-complaint-court-of-justice|title=Poland has filed a complaint against the European Union\u2019s copyright directive|last=Liptak|first=Andrew|date=2019-05-25|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> Member states will then have until 7 June 2021 to introduce laws within their own countries to support the Directive.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/mar/26/meps-approve-sweeping-changes-to-copyright-law-european-copyright-directive|title=MEPs approve sweeping changes to copyright law|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=2019-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":19\"/>\n\n== Content ==\nArticle numbers refer to the draft version of this copyright directive up through around 20 March 2019; the approved directive reorders several of the articles, such as draft Article 13 becoming the Directive's Article 17.<ref name=\"final directive\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf | title = DIRECTIVE (EU) 2019/... OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL on copyright and related rights in the Digital Single Market and amending Directives 96/9/EC and 2001/29/EC | date = 26 March 2019 | accessdate = 15 April 2019 | publisher = [[European Parliament]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Article 3 ===\n\nArticle 3 introduces a [[Limitations and exceptions to copyright|copyright exception]] for [[text and data mining]] (TDM) for the purposes of scientific research.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=9 June 2018|title=Copyright Reform: Help Us Ensure an Effective TDM Exception! \u2013 LIBER|url=https://libereurope.eu/blog/2017/09/25/copyright-reform-help-us-ensure-an-effective-tdm-exception/|newspaper=LIBER|date=25 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228164450/http://libereurope.eu/blog/2017/09/25/copyright-reform-help-us-ensure-an-effective-tdm-exception/|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The COREPER version has both a mandatory and an optional extension.<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\"/>\n\nDepending on whether it acknowledges the [[public domain]] status of facts and information, the TDM exception could increase or decrease restrictions compared to the status quo.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=12 June 2018|title=24 organisations urge Rapporteur Axel Voss MEP to strike a more ambitious deal on TDM \u2013 European Alliance for Research Excellence|url=http://eare.eu/24-organisations-urge-rapporteur-voss-reach-ambitious-deal-tdm/|newspaper=European Alliance for Research Excellence|date=8 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140050/http://eare.eu/24-organisations-urge-rapporteur-voss-reach-ambitious-deal-tdm/|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Article 5 ===\n\nArticle 5 introduces a mandatory exception for the use of copyrighted works as part of \"digital and cross-border teaching activities\". This article clarifies that educational establishments can make non-commercial use of copyrighted works for illustrative purposes.<ref name=\"final directive\"/>\n\nThere have been worries from the educational sector that the exception proposed in article 5 is too limiting. For example, the sector proposes to broaden the scope of \"educational establishments\" to include cultural heritage institutions. The most debated part of the article is 5(2), under which the exception would not be available if there are \"adequate licenses\" available in the market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://education.okfn.org/educators-ask-for-a-better-copyright/|title=Educators ask for a better copyright|date=16 January 2018|work=Open Education Working Group|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705150720/https://education.okfn.org/educators-ask-for-a-better-copyright/|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe COREPER version{{clarify|date=April 2019}} has changes to reflect the arguments of the education sector, but still includes the debated article 5(2).<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.csee-etuce.org/en/news/archive/2657-etuce-urges-the-european-parliament-to-vote-in-favour-of-an-open-broad-and-flexible-eu-copyright-education-exception| title = ETUCE urges the European Parliament to vote in favour of an open, broad and flexible EU copyright education exception | date  =4 July 2018 | accessdate = 15 April 2019 | publisher = European Trade Union Committee for Education }}</ref>\n\n=== Article 14 ===\nArticle 14 states that reproductions of works of visual art that are in the [[public domain]] cannot be subject to copyright or related rights, unless the reproduction is an original creative work.<ref name=\"finaltext\">{{cite web |title=Final text of the Directive as submitted to the Parliament on 26 March 2019|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf |accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Article 11|Article 15}}Draft Article 11 (Article 15 of the directive) ===\nDraft Article 11 (Article 15 of the directive) extends the 2001 Information Society Directive to grant publishers direct copyright over \"online use of their press publications by information society service providers\".<ref name=\"EUJune25\" /> Under current EU law, publishers instead rely on authors assigning copyright to them and must prove rights ownership for each individual work.<ref name=\"EPstudy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/thinktank/en/document.html?reference=IPOL_STU(2017)596810|title=Strengthening the Position of Press Publishers and Authors and Performers in the Copyright Directive \u2013 Think Tank|publisher=European Parliament|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143258/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/thinktank/en/document.html?reference=IPOL_STU(2017)596810|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The version of the directive voted on by the [[European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs]] contained explicit exemptions for the act of [[hyperlinking]] and \"legitimate private and non-commercial use of press publications by individual users\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://juliareda.eu/2018/06/article-11-13-vote/|title=What\u2019s at stake in the July 5 #SaveYourInternet vote: The text, explained|last=Reda|first=Julia|work=Julia Reda|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705194938/https://juliareda.eu/2018/06/article-11-13-vote/|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe proposal attaches several new conditions to the right, including expiry after one year and exemptions for either copying an \"insubstantial\" part of a work or for copying it in the course of academic or scientific research.<ref name=\"EUJune25\" /> It is derived from the [[ancillary copyright for press publishers]] which was introduced in Germany in 2013.<ref name=\"EPstudy\" /> Press publishing, \"whose purpose is to inform the general public and which are periodically or regularly updated\", is distinguished from [[academic publishing|academic]] and [[Scientific literature|scientific]] publishing (Recital 33).<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\"/>\n\nArticle 11 was moved to Article 15 in the final draft from the trilogue negotiations issued 26 March 2019 and approved by the Parliament and Council.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://fortune.com/2019/03/26/eu-copyright-directive-article-13-passed/ | title = EU Holds Online Platforms Liable for Users' Copyright Infringement | first = David | last = Meyer | date = 26 March 2019 | accessdate = 15 April 2019 | work = [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] }}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Article 13|Article 17}}Draft Article 13 (Directive Article 17)===\nDraft Article 13 of the draft replaces the \"[[Electronic Commerce Directive 2000|mere conduit]]\" exemption from copyright infringement from for-profit \"[[User-generated content|online content sharing service]] providers\" with a new, conditional exemption to liability. These conditions are an implementation of \"effective and proportionate measures\", as claimed by service providers, to \"prevent the availability of specific [unlicensed] works identified by rightsholders\", acting \"expeditiously\" to remove them, and demonstrating that \"best efforts\" have been made to prevent their future availability. The article also extends any licenses granted to content hosts to their users, as long as those users are not acting \"on a commercial basis\".<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" />\n\nThe article directs member states to consider the size of the provider, the amount of content uploaded, and the effectiveness of the measures imposed \"in light of technological developments\". It also mandates an appeals process,<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" /> and requires content hosts to share \"information on the use of content\" with the content's owner, the lack of which has been a point of contention in the past.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/03/technology/internet/03youtube.html|title=Royalty Dispute Stops Music Videos in Germany|last=O\u2019Brien|first=Kevin J.|work=New York Times|access-date=10 August 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811005734/https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/03/technology/internet/03youtube.html|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDraft Article 13's provisions target commercial web hosts which \"store and give the public access to a large number of works or other subject-matter uploaded by its users which [they] organise and promote for profit-making purposes\". The proposal makes explicit that this does not include private [[cloud storage]] services, non-profit encyclopedias (such as [[Wikipedia]]), nor non-profit educational or scientific repositories.<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" />\n\nDraft Article 13b requires websites which \"automatically reproduce or refer to significant amounts of copyright-protected visual works\" to \"conclude fair and balanced licensing agreements with any requesting {{Sic|rightholders}}\".<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nDraft Article 13 was named Article 17 in the final trilogue draft issued in February 2019 and approved by the European Parliament and Council.<ref name=\"verge finalvote mar19\"/>\n\n=== Draft Articles 14 through 16 (Directive articles 18 through 20)  ===\nAs a whole, draft articles 14-16 (Directive Articles 18-20) in the working version of the Directive, improve the bargaining position of authors and performers, even though it set out systems that were weaker than some existing ones in member states.<ref name=EPstudy/> Draft article 15 (Directive article 19) aims to allow authors to increase their remuneration in some cases where it is disproportionately low.<ref name=EPstudy/>\n\nAssociations of authors had proposed a \"rights reversion mechanism\" which would allow cancelling a [[copyright transfer agreement]] proven to be disadvantageous.<ref name=\"basca01\" >{{cite web|title=Music creators call for EU-wide rights reversion mechanism|url=https://basca.org.uk/2017/10/19/music-creators-call-eu-wide-rights-reversion-mechanism/|website=BASCA|accessdate=5 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142607/https://basca.org.uk/2017/10/19/music-creators-call-eu-wide-rights-reversion-mechanism/|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20170811-ALCS-and-SoA-Briefing-note-on-DSM-directive-and-Juri-amendments.pdf|title=Our Views on the European Commission's Draft Legislation to Modernise the European Copyright Framework and Proposed Amendments|date=August 2017|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141523/http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20170811-ALCS-and-SoA-Briefing-note-on-DSM-directive-and-Juri-amendments.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Other articles ===\nOther passages of the proposal attempt to clarify the legal status of [[orphan works]] and certain common activities by libraries.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=22 June 2018|title=European Parliament votes to improve access to digitised cultural heritage|url=https://pro.europeana.eu/post/european-parliament-votes-to-improve-access-to-digitsed-cultural-heritage|website=Europeana|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622100105/https://pro.europeana.eu/post/european-parliament-votes-to-improve-access-to-digitsed-cultural-heritage|archive-date=22 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the Trilogue negotiations, Article 12a proposed granting sports event organisers copyright over recordings of their events.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&language=EN&reference=P8-TA-2018-0337|title=Amendments adopted by the European Parliament on 12 September 2018 on the proposal for a directive of the European Parliament and of the Council on copyright in the Digital Single Market|date=12 September 2018|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111211840/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=TA&language=EN&reference=P8-TA-2018-0337|archive-date=11 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/3kenb8/the-eu-can-still-be-saved-from-its-internet-wrecking-copyright-plan | title = The EU Can Still Be Saved From Its Internet-Wrecking Copyright Plan | first = Karl | last =Bode |date= 12 September 2018 | accessdate = 15 April 2019 | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Motherboard]] }}</ref>  The March 2019 version only says, on the last page, that the commission in the future will assess the challenges of illegal online transmissions of sports broadcasts.<ref name=\"final directive\"/>\n\n== Positions ==\n\n=== Politicians ===\nAs of 21 March 2019, 100 MEPs have signed in support of the directive, while 126 have agreed to vote against it.<ref>{{cite web |title=MEPs pro Manifesto for an open and fair internet |url=https://www.manifesto4copyright.eu/MEPs |website=www.manifesto4copyright.eu |accessdate=21 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321104251/https://www.manifesto4copyright.eu/MEPs |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pledge 2019: Against Article 13 |url=https://pledge2019.eu/en |website=pledge2019.eu |accessdate=21 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320154614/https://pledge2019.eu/en |archive-date=20 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> On 20 March 2019 74 MEPs asked for Article 13 to be deleted from the directive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amendment 269 |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-269-270_EN.pdf |accessdate=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321110827/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-269-270_EN.pdf |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In the end, 348 voted for and 274 voted against.<ref>{{cite web |title=Copyright in the Digital Single Market: European Parliament Vote |url=https://juliareda.eu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/copyrightvote.pdf |accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, support in the European Parliament was led by the [[European People's Party group]] and the [[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats]], the parliament's two largest groups. Major national parties in support include Germany's ruling [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]] and their coalition partners the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]], the United Kingdom's ruling [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and opposition [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], and Poland's main opposition party, [[Civic Platform]].<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.votewatch.eu/en/term8-copyright-in-the-digital-single-market-draft-legislative-resolution-vote-commission-proposal-ordinar.html|title=Results of the 12th of September vote on Copyright in the Digital Single Market|website=VoteWatch|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124230/https://www.votewatch.eu/en/term8-copyright-in-the-digital-single-market-draft-legislative-resolution-vote-commission-proposal-ordinar.html|archive-date=9 December 2018|url-status=live|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/the-industry-is-totally-united-on-this-issue-uk-music-leads-copyright-delegation-to-brussels/072965|title='The industry is totally united on this issue': UK Music leads copyright delegation to Brussels|access-date=23 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724032222/http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/the-industry-is-totally-united-on-this-issue-uk-music-leads-copyright-delegation-to-brussels/072965|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe directive's [[rapporteur]], [[Axel Voss]], is German MEP and a member of the EPP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eppgroup.eu/news/Axel-Voss-appointed-new-Rapporteur-for-Copyright-Directive|title=Axel Voss appointed new Rapporteur for Copyright Directive|date=15 June 2017|work=eppgroup.eu|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705233740/http://www.eppgroup.eu/news/Axel-Voss-appointed-new-Rapporteur-for-Copyright-Directive|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Voss rejects critics' arguments against the directive, and in particular describes talk of censorship as \"unjustified, excessive, objectively wrong and dishonest\". He points out that content filtering technology has been in use on [[YouTube]] for a decade without having ever sparked an \"anti-censorship campaign\",<ref name=\":7\" /> and accuses \"big [internet] platforms\" of mounting a \"fake news campaign\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://multimedia.europarl.europa.eu/en/copyright-directive-statement-by-axel-voss-eppde-rapporteur-_I158298-V_v|title=Copyright directive: statement by Axel VOSS (EPP,DE), rapporteur|date=2 July 2018|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705232910/https://multimedia.europarl.europa.eu/en/copyright-directive-statement-by-axel-voss-eppde-rapporteur-_I158298-V_v|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Axel Voss's understanding of copyright was referred to as \"absolutely lacking\" in 2019 by Till Kreutzer, a copyright expert, after Voss stated that people are allowed to upload newspaper articles in full.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU-Urheberrechtsreform: Das \"absolute Unverst\u00e4ndnis\" des Axel Voss - Golem.de |url=https://www.golem.de/news/eu-urheberrechtsreform-das-absolute-unverstaendnis-des-axel-voss-1902-139511.html |website=www.golem.de |accessdate=24 February 2019 |language=de-DE |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223193120/https://www.golem.de/news/eu-urheberrechtsreform-das-absolute-unverstaendnis-des-axel-voss-1902-139511.html |archive-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]], a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|member of Parliament of the United Kingdom]] and the deputy leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], said, \"we have got to secure for the workers [...] the full fruits of their industry. Google are trying to prevent that from happening\".<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOpposition in the European Parliament is led by populist parties including Poland's ruling [[Law and Justice]] party, Italy's ruling [[Five Star Movement]]/[[Lega Nord]] coalition, and the [[UK Independence Party]]. Other opponents include a large number of smaller parties at either end of the political spectrum.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/10/italy-steps-defend-eu-internet-users-against-copyright-filters-who-will-be-next|title=Italy Steps Up To Defend EU Internet Users Against Copyright Filters \u2013 Who Will Be Next?|last=O'Brein|first=Danny|date=23 October 2018|work=[[Electronic Frontier Foundation]]|accessdate=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023194617/https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/10/italy-steps-defend-eu-internet-users-against-copyright-filters-who-will-be-next|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Notable among these is the [[Pirate Party Germany]], whose sole MEP [[Julia Reda]] has been an outspoken opponent of the proposal.<ref name=\"PM2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/meps-rally-against-planned-eu-copyright-reform|title=MEPs rally against planned EU copyright reform|website=theparliamentmagazine.eu|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701164917/https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/meps-rally-against-planned-eu-copyright-reform|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She describes the efforts behind the law as large media companies trying to force \"platforms and search engines to use their snippets and to pay for them\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://copyrightblog.kluweriplaw.com/2018/06/18/julia-reda-discusses-current-proposal-directive-copyright-digital-single-market/|title=Julia Reda discusses the current Proposal for a Directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market \u2013 Kluwer Copyright Blog|date=18 June 2018|website=Kluwer Copyright Blog|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701164956/http://copyrightblog.kluweriplaw.com/2018/06/18/julia-reda-discusses-current-proposal-directive-copyright-digital-single-market/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> UKIP leader and MEP [[Gerard Batten]] said that the proposal may \"destroy the capacity for free speech on the internet and social media\".<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukip.org/national-ukip-news-item.php?id=18|title=UKIP opposes the EU's Copyright Directive in the Single Digital Market|date=3 July 2018|website=[[UK Independence Party]]|access-date=29 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129142031/https://www.ukip.org/national-ukip-news-item.php?id=18|archive-date=29 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Batten further noted that an international agreement, and not an EU directive, was needed to protect \"the legitimate rights of creators, authors and innovators\", whilst not stifling \"free speech and information dissemination\".<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nIt has been rumoured that during the [[European Council]]'s private vote to approve its negotiating position in March 2018 the ambassadors of Germany, Finland, the Netherlands, Slovenia, Belgium and Hungary either abstained from voting or voted against the proposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LauKaya/status/1000022947401224192|title=The #copyright directive was approved today...|last=Kayali|first=Laura|date=25 May 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219035846/https://twitter.com/LauKaya/status/1000022947401224192|archive-date=19 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref> However, MEPs of each of those countries' governing parties went on to largely or wholly support the directive in parliament.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nGerman politician [[Kevin K\u00fchnert]], federal chairperson of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]]'s [[Young Socialists in the SPD|youth organisation]], has voiced opposition to Article 13, claiming that it violates the coalition agreement between the SPD and the [[CDU/CSU]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/uploadfilter-kevin-kuehnert-fordert-abstimmung-auf-spd-parteikonvent-a-1254592.html |title=Kevin K\u00fchnert fordert Abstimmung auf SPD-Parteikonvent |work=[[Spiegel Online]] |language=de |date=22 February 2019 |access-date=22 February 2019 |last1=Hickmann |first1=Christoph |last2=Medick |first2=Veit |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222165055/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/uploadfilter-kevin-kuehnert-fordert-abstimmung-auf-spd-parteikonvent-a-1254592.html |archive-date=22 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Petra Sitte, vice-chair of the democratic socialist party [[The Left (Germany)|The Left]], also stated that the effective endorsement of upload filters violates the coalition agreement, calling this copyright directive a \"compromise between the interests of different large corporations\" (\"''Kompromiss zwischen den Interessen verschiedener Gro\u00dfkonzerne''\") and \"a grave threat to freedom of expression\" (\"''eine ernsthafte Gefahr f\u00fcr die Meinungsfreiheit''\").<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.linksfraktion.de/themen/nachrichten/detail/uploadfilter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-ewiges-deja-vu/ |title=Uploadfilter und Leistungsschutzrecht: Ewiges D\u00e9j\u00e0-Vu |last=Sitte |first=Petra |date=15 February 2019 |access-date=22 February 2019 |website=Die Linke. im Bundestag |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223074345/https://www.linksfraktion.de/themen/nachrichten/detail/uploadfilter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-ewiges-deja-vu/ |archive-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe day before the Parliament vote, the ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]'' reported that Germany may have caved in to support the Directive at the last minute in exchange for France's approval of the controversial [[Nord Stream|Nord Stream 2]] project, a [[natural gas]] pipeline from Russia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.faz.net/faz-edition/wirtschaft/2019-03-26/f30a5870c08cc1e1b4524c1be19d1faf/ |title=Altmaier opfert Start-ups im Urheberrecht |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |language=de |date=2019-03-25 |access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> MEP [[Tiemo W\u00f6lken]], a member of the SDP and opponent of the Directive, claimed that this had been rumoured before the report was published.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=woelken |number=1110278446515699712 |date=2019-03-25 |title=Was bisher in #Br\u00fcssel & #Berlin nur gemunkelt wurde, l\u00e4sst sich offensichtlich nun so belegen, dass es ver\u00f6ffentlicht wird. Es gab einen Deal auf h\u00f6chster Ebene zwischen Deutschland & Frankreich. #Uploadfilter gegen #Gas. Ein Grund mehr morgen mit #Nein zu stimmen! #Artikel13 |last=W\u00f6lken |first=Tiemo |authorlink=Tiemo W\u00f6lken}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-governmental organisations ===\n[[File:Blackout of wikipedia.de by Wikimedia Deutschland - March 2019.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Blackout of [[German Wikipedia]] - 21 March 2019]]\n[[File:Italian Wikipedia blocked.png|thumb|upright=1.4|The banner block on [[Italian Wikipedia]]. Other blocked Wikipedias had similar messages.]]\n[[File:English Wikipedia EU copyright banner.png|thumb|upright=1.4|The banner on the English Wikipedia seen from a German IP address]]\nIn 2017, [[Human Rights Watch]] and [[Reporters Without Borders]] were among the signatories of an open letter opposing Article 13.<ref>{{cite news |last=Locklear |first=Mallory |title=Digital rights groups speak out against EU plan to scan online content |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/17/digital-rights-groups-against-eu-scan-online-content/ |work=[[Engadget]] |date=17 October 2017 |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220063020/https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/17/digital-rights-groups-against-eu-scan-online-content/ |archive-date=20 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> 145{{Nbsp}}organisations from the areas of human and digital rights, media freedom, publishing, libraries, educational institutions, software developers, and [[Internet service provider]]s signed a letter opposing the proposed legislation on 26 April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leistungsschutzrecht.info/sites/default/files/assets/dokumente/aktuelles/openletter-axelvoss-deletearticle11-english.pdf|title=Letter by 145 civil society organisations|url-status=live|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141128/http://leistungsschutzrecht.info/sites/default/files/assets/dokumente/aktuelles/openletter-axelvoss-deletearticle11-english.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> Some of those opposed include the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], [[Creative Commons]], [[European Digital Rights]],<ref name=\"Index2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indexoncensorship.org/2018/04/digital-single-market-nightmare/|title=Directive on copyright in the Digital Single Market 'destined to become a nightmare'|date=26 April 2018|website=Index on Censorship|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140215/https://www.indexoncensorship.org/2018/04/digital-single-market-nightmare/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Max Planck Society]],<ref name=\"CNET2018June22\" /> [[GitHub]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boingboing.net/2018/09/11/developers-developers-develope-3.html|title=What developers need to do to save the internet from the EU's looming copyright disaster|last=Doctorow|first=Cory|authorlink=Cory Doctorow|date=11 September 2018|website=[[Boing Boing]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911113555/https://boingboing.net/2018/09/11/developers-developers-develope-3.html|archive-date=11 September 2018|url-status=live|access-date=11 September 2018}}</ref> various [[Wikimedia]] chapters,<ref name=\"Index2018\" /> and the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] (the parent organisation of [[Wikipedia]]).<ref name=\"WikimediaFoundation\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2018/06/29/eu-copyright-proposal-will-hurt-web-wikipedia/|title=How the EU copyright proposal will hurt the web and Wikipedia|last=Hershenov|first=Eileen|date=29 June 2018|website=wikimedia.org|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|access-date=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701194303/https://blog.wikimedia.org/2018/06/29/eu-copyright-proposal-will-hurt-web-wikipedia/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Italian Wikipedia]],<ref name=\"ItalyWikipedia\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44696302|title=Italy Wikipedia shuts down in protest at EU copyright law|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=3 July 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=29 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729060650/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44696302|archive-date=29 July 2018|url-status=live|publisher=BBC|department=World News (Europe)}}</ref><ref name=\"PagesShutDown\">{{Cite news|url=https://siliconangle.com/blog/2018/07/04/italian-spanish-polish-wikipedia-pages-shut-down-ahead-controversial-copyright-law/|title=Italian, Spanish and Polish Wikipedia pages shut down ahead of controversial copyright law|last=Farrell|first=James|date=4 July 2018|work=[[Silicon Angle]]|access-date=29 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729062249/https://siliconangle.com/blog/2018/07/04/italian-spanish-polish-wikipedia-pages-shut-down-ahead-controversial-copyright-law/|archive-date=29 July 2018|url-status=live|publisher=Silicon Angle Media|department=Blog}}</ref><ref name=\"PolishWikipedia\">{{Cite news|url=https://polandinenglish.info/37945453/polish-wikipedia-shuts-down-in-protest-at-eu-copyright-law|title=Polish Wikipedia shuts down in protest at EU copyright law|author=pg/st<!--No other author information availble.-->|date=4 July 2018|work=Poland in English|access-date=29 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729061112/https://polandinenglish.info/37945453/polish-wikipedia-shuts-down-in-protest-at-eu-copyright-law|archive-date=29 July 2018|url-status=live|publisher=[[Telewizja Polska]]}}</ref> later followed by others including the [[Spanish Wikipedia|Spanish]],<ref name=\"PagesShutDown\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/tecnologia/redes/abci-wikipedia-espanol-cierra-forma-temporal-protesta-propuesta-copyright-201807041109_noticia.html|title=Wikipedia en espa\u00f1ol cierra de forma temporal en protesta por la propuesta de copyright de la UE|work=abc|access-date=4 July 2018|language=es-ES|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704153031/https://www.abc.es/tecnologia/redes/abci-wikipedia-espanol-cierra-forma-temporal-protesta-propuesta-copyright-201807041109_noticia.html|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Estonian Wikipedia|Estonian]], [[Latvian Wikipedia|Latvian]], [[Polish Wikipedia|Polish]],<ref name=\"PagesShutDown\" /><ref name=\"PolishWikipedia\" /> [[French Wikipedia|French]], and [[Portuguese Wikipedia|Portuguese]] editions,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tehnika.postimees.ee/4513784/eesti-vikipeedia-pani-protesti-margiks-oma-lehekulje-kinni|title=Eesti Vikipeedia pani protesti m\u00e4rgiks oma lehek\u00fclje kinni|work=Tehnika|access-date=4 July 2018|language=et|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704084323/https://tehnika.postimees.ee/4513784/eesti-vikipeedia-pani-protesti-margiks-oma-lehekulje-kinni|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \"blacked-out\" its pages for readers on 3\u20135 July 2018, while the English Wikipedia added a banner asking readers in Europe to contact their representatives in the European Parliament.<ref name=\"ItalyWikipedia\" /> The Wikimedia Foundation reiterated its concerns in February 2019.<ref name=\"WikimediaFoundation19\">{{cite web |url=https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/02/07/problems-remain-with-the-eus-copyright-reform/ |title=Problems remain with the EU's copyright reform |last1=Dimitrov |first1=Dimitar |last2=Davenport |first2=Allison |website=[[Wikimedia Foundation]] |date=7 February 2019 |accessdate=21 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222041936/https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/02/07/problems-remain-with-the-eus-copyright-reform/ |archive-date=22 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"WikimediaFoundation19b\">{{cite web |url=https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/02/28/we-do-not-support-the-eu-copyright-directive-in-its-current-form-heres-why-you-shouldnt-either/ |title=We do not support the EU Copyright Directive in its current form. Here's why you shouldn't either |website=[[Wikimedia Foundation]] |last=Davenport |first=Allison |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=2 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306044327/https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/02/28/we-do-not-support-the-eu-copyright-directive-in-its-current-form-heres-why-you-shouldnt-either/ |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Four editions of Wikipedia\u2014German, Danish, Czech and Slovak\u2014were blacked-out for 24 hours on 21 March 2019 to further protest the directive.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why Wikipedia will go offline for 24 hours in Germany |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/03/14/wikipedia-go-offline-hours-germany-protest-against-eu-bill-that-could-harm-freedom-speech/ |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=14 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319215240/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/03/14/wikipedia-go-offline-hours-germany-protest-against-eu-bill-that-could-harm-freedom-speech/ |archive-date=19 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Prepare for the shutdown of Slovak Wikipedia |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/22079741/slovak-wikipedia-to-shut-down-eu-copyright-directive.html |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=spectator.sme.sk |date=20 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321073123/https://spectator.sme.sk/c/22079741/slovak-wikipedia-to-shut-down-eu-copyright-directive.html |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=Fort2019Mar21>{{cite news |title=Why Four Versions of Wikipedia Have Deliberately Gone Dark |url=http://fortune.com/2019/03/21/wikipedia-dark-eu-copyright-protest/ |accessdate=22 March 2019 |work=Fortune |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322122633/http://fortune.com/2019/03/21/wikipedia-dark-eu-copyright-protest/ |archive-date=22 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Wikipedia co-founder [[Jimmy Wales]] raised concerns regarding the costs and effectiveness of upload filters and possible negative effects upon [[free speech]] online.<ref name=\"BBC2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44482381|title=Protests over Brussels copyright reform|date=15 June 2018|work=[[BBC News Online|BBC News]]|accessdate=19 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316142603/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44482381|archive-date=16 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://copybuzz.com/copyright/50-human-rights-media-freedom-ngos-ask-eu-delete-censorship-filter-stop-madness/|title=Over 50 Human Rights & Media Freedom NGOs ask EU to Delete Censorship Filter & to Stop \u00a9 Madness \u2013 Copybuzz|website=copybuzz.com|language=en-US|access-date=8 July 2018|date=16 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709010042/http://copybuzz.com/copyright/50-human-rights-media-freedom-ngos-ask-eu-delete-censorship-filter-stop-madness/|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Technology companies ===\n[[Google]] (which operates the [[Google News]] aggregation site which would be affected) has opposed the directive since its first inception in 2016, when they argued that the proposals would \"turn the internet into a place where everything uploaded to the web must be cleared by lawyers\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.google/outreach-initiatives/public-policy/european-copyright-theres-better-way/|title=European copyright: there's a better way|date=14 September 2016|work=Google|access-date=10 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709132940/https://blog.google/outreach-initiatives/public-policy/european-copyright-theres-better-way/|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Kent Walker, Senior Vice President for Global Affairs and Chief Legal Officer at Google, \"Companies that act reasonably in helping rights holders identify and control the use of their content shouldn\u2019t be held liable for anything a user uploads, any more than a telephone company should be liable for the content of conversations.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blog.google/around-the-globe/google-europe/now-time-fix-eu-copyright-directive/|title=Now is the time to fix the EU copyright directive|last=|first=|date=Feb 7, 2019|website=Google Official Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2018 the company encouraged news publishers in its [[Digital News Initiative]] to lobby MEPs on the proposals, members of the initiative are eligible for grants to support digital journalism from a \u20ac150m fund.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a8031d7a-78a0-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=Google criticised for push against EU copyright reform|date=26 June 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705004439/https://www.ft.com/content/a8031d7a-78a0-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref> YouTube's [[chief executive officer]], [[Susan Wojcicki]], urged content creators on the platform to take action to oppose the legislation, as it \"poses a threat to both [their] livelihood and [their] ability to share [their] voice with the world\", and stressing that their [[Content ID (algorithm)|Content ID]] system was intended to help assure fair management and payments for copyright holders already without government intervention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/22/youtube-susan-wojcicki-creators-protest-eu-article-13-copyright-law.html|title=YouTube CEO urges YouTube creators to protest European copyright law|last=D'onfo|first=Julianne|date=22 October 2018|work=[[CNBC]]|accessdate=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022215957/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/22/youtube-susan-wojcicki-creators-protest-eu-article-13-copyright-law.html|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Wojcicki later wrote that any company implementing the necessary protocols to meet the directive would have a significant financial burden, and for a company the scale of YouTube, \"the potential liabilities could be so large that no company could take on such a financial risk\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/12/18087250/youtube-ceo-copyright-directive-article-13-european-union|title=YouTube CEO calls EU's proposed copyright regulation financially impossible|last=Alexander|first=Julie|date=12 November 2018|work=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=12 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112170240/https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/12/18087250/youtube-ceo-copyright-directive-article-13-european-union|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Facebook]] is also opposed, arguing that the proposal \"could have serious, unintended consequences for an open and creative internet\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/european-parliament-votes-against-publishers-right-copyright-law-changes-as-facebook-warns-of-unintended-consequences/|title=European Parliament votes against 'publisher's right' copyright law changes as Facebook warns of 'unintended consequences'|date=5 July 2018|magazine=Press Gazette|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711025503/https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/european-parliament-votes-against-publishers-right-copyright-law-changes-as-facebook-warns-of-unintended-consequences/|archive-date=11 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Computer and Communications Industry Association]], a trade association that represents Google and other large technology companies, is a principal funder of the [[Copyright for Creativity]] organisation, a coalition that led the \"Save Your Internet\" campaign opposing the directive.<ref name=\"Corp2019\">{{cite web |title=Copyright Directive: how competing big business lobbies drowned out critical voices |url=https://corporateeurope.org/power-lobbies/2018/12/copyright-directive-how-competing-big-business-lobbies-drowned-out-critical |website=Corporate Europe Observatory |accessdate=16 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216153252/https://corporateeurope.org/power-lobbies/2018/12/copyright-directive-how-competing-big-business-lobbies-drowned-out-critical |archive-date=16 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Reddit]] in November 2018 referred their European users to a website called \"Don't Wreck the Net\".<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=https://redditblog.com/2018/11/28/the-eu-copyright-directive-what-redditors-in-europe-need-to-know/|title=The EU Copyright Directive: What Redditors in Europe need to know|website=Reddit|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207083308/https://redditblog.com/2018/11/28/the-eu-copyright-directive-what-redditors-in-europe-need-to-know/|archive-date=7 December 2018|url-status=live|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Academics ===\nMore than 200 academics have criticised the directive, emphasising concerns about the effectiveness of Article 11's impact on the readership of online publication and of Article 13's obligations on service providers that will \"benefit big players\".<ref name=\"Create20180629\">{{cite web|url=https://www.create.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Academic_Statement_Copyright_Directive_29_06_2018.pdf|title=Copyright Reform: Open Letter from European Research Centres|date=29 June 2018|work=CREATe|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629155041/https://www.create.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Academic_Statement_Copyright_Directive_29_06_2018.pdf|archive-date=29 June 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ivir.nl/academics-against-press-publishers-right/|title=Letter by 169 academics|url-status=live|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180705001936/https://www.ivir.nl/academics-against-press-publishers-right/|archive-date=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://peepbeep.files.wordpress.com/2016/10/30-september-2016-openlettercommission-w-s1.pdf|title=Open letter by 40 scholars to the European Commission|date=30 October 2016|url-status=live|access-date=9 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141206/https://peepbeep.files.wordpress.com/2016/10/30-september-2016-openlettercommission-w-s1.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> [[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition|SPARC Europe]] called for the removal of Article 11, arguing that it would \"make the last two decades of news less accessible to researchers and the public, leading to a distortion of the public's knowledge and memory of past events\", and if extended to academic publishing, would \"in effect ask readers to pay publishers for access to works for which authors, institutions or research funders had already paid publishers to make freely accessible to all under '[[open access]]' terms\".<ref name=\"Create20180629\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sparceurope.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/CopyrightReformBrief.pdf|title=\"Copyright in the Digital Single Market\" briefing|publisher=SPARC Europe|url-status=live|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622220830/https://sparceurope.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/CopyrightReformBrief.pdf|archive-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> Twenty-five research centres common on concerns that the financial benefits from the proposed directive will occur to large rightsholders rather than creators, with creators simple being used as \"frontmen/women\".<ref name=\"Create20180629\" />\n\nThe proposal is generally supported by academic publishers including the [[International Association of Scientific, Technical, and Medical Publishers]].<ref name=\"Nature2018\">{{cite journal|last1=Schiermeier|first1=Quirin|date=5 April 2018|title=EU copyright reforms draw fire from scientists|journal=Nature|volume=556|issue=7699|pages=14\u201315|doi=10.1038/d41586-018-03837-7|pmid=29620761}}</ref> This group has nevertheless criticised the proposal for excluding scientific publishers from the provisions of Article 11, describing the exclusion as \"unwarranted and potentially discriminatory\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stm-assoc.org/2016_09_14_News_Release_STM_response_to_Directive_on_Copyright_in_the_Single_Digital_Market.pdf|title=STM response to Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market|date=14 September 2016|publisher=[[International Association of Scientific, Technical, and Medical Publishers|STM]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410174902/https://www.stm-assoc.org/2016_09_14_News_Release_STM_response_to_Directive_on_Copyright_in_the_Single_Digital_Market.pdf|archive-date=10 April 2018|url-status=live|access-date=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Eurodoc|European Council for Doctoral Candidates and Junior Researchers]] opposes the proposal on the grounds that Article 13's exemption for non-commercial groups does not cover all scientific repositories, and cites the [[Horizon 2020]] project as an example of commercial work in the sector. They also generally agree with the claims of other opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurodoc.net/eurodoc-open-letter-copyright-directive.pdf|title=Eurodoc Open Letter to European Parliament on Copyright Directive|date=2 July 2018|website=[[Eurodoc]]|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702233401/http://eurodoc.net/eurodoc-open-letter-copyright-directive.pdf|archive-date=2 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition]], an [[open access]] advocacy group, opposes the proposal in principle.<ref name=\"Nature2018\" />\n\n=== Publishers ===\nA campaign organised by the [[European Grouping of Societies of Authors and Composers]] collected over 32,000{{Nbsp}}signatures in 2018 from creators including [[David Guetta]], [[Ennio Morricone]], [[Jean-Michel Jarre]], and the band [[Air (band)|Air]].<ref name=\"Indus2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/david-guetta-and-all-three-major-labels-are-among-industry-giants-pushing-for-copyright-reform/|title=David Guetta and all three major labels are among industry giants pushing for copyright reform {{!}} TIO|work=theindustryobserver.com.au|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721114621/https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/david-guetta-and-all-three-major-labels-are-among-industry-giants-pushing-for-copyright-reform/|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Other supporters in 2018 include musicians [[Paul McCartney]] and [[James Blunt]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paul-mccartney-james-blunt-back-new-european-copyright-law-1124974|title=Paul McCartney, James Blunt Back New European Copyright Law|date=4 July 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=4 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704152646/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paul-mccartney-james-blunt-back-new-european-copyright-law-1124974|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> author [[Philip Pullman]] (as head of the [[Society of Authors]]),<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20161205-Submission-to-IPO-on-DSM-directive-dec-2016.pdf|title=The Society of Authors' Response to the Intellectual Property Office's Calls for Views on the European Commission's Draft Legislation to Modernise the European Copyright Framework|publisher=[[Society of Authors]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704034530/http://www.societyofauthors.org/SOA/MediaLibrary/SOAWebsite/Submissions/20161205-Submission-to-IPO-on-DSM-directive-dec-2016.pdf|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"theverge 11sett 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/11/17845394/eu-copyright-directive-reform-date-vote-article-11-13|title=This is what at stake with the EU\u2019s latest copyright reform|last=Vincent|first=James|date=11 September 2018|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911182621/https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/11/17845394/eu-copyright-directive-reform-date-vote-article-11-13|archive-date=11 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Independent Music Companies Association]],<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://impalamusic.org/content/copyright-say-no-scaremongering-and-yes-creators-getting-paid|title=Copyright: say NO to scaremongering and YES to creators getting paid|publisher=[[Independent Music Companies Association]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704010146/http://impalamusic.org/content/copyright-say-no-scaremongering-and-yes-creators-getting-paid|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref> and German publisher [[Axel Springer SE|Axel Springer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/tensions-heighten-ahead-crunch-eu-copyright-reform-vote|title=Tensions heighten ahead of crunch EU copyright reform vote|website=www.theparliamentmagazine.eu|language=en|access-date=3 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701164908/https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/tensions-heighten-ahead-crunch-eu-copyright-reform-vote|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPublishing trade bodies similarly claim that a \"bad-faith\" \"misleading campaign\", is being carried out. They specifically name Wikipedia and [[Google]] as orchestrators,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"mythbuster\">{{cite web|url=https://www.publishersright.eu/mythbuster|title=MYTHBUSTER|website=publishersright.eu|publisher=[[European Magazine Media Association]] and others|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705003900/https://www.publishersright.eu/mythbuster|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukmusic.org/news/uk-music-chief-slams-google-as-corporate-vultures-as-figures-show-googles-3|title=UK Music chief slams Google as \"corporate vultures\" as figures show Google's \u20ac31m EU lobbying bid|publisher=[[UK Music]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704153622/https://www.ukmusic.org/news/uk-music-chief-slams-google-as-corporate-vultures-as-figures-show-googles-3|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"enpa\">{{cite web|url=http://enpa.eu/news/enpa-reacts-wikipedia-hostile-campaign-against-copyright|title=ENPA reacts to Wikipedia hostile campaign against Copyright|date=3 July 2018|publisher=[[European Newspaper Publishers' Association]]|access-date=5 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705034245/http://enpa.eu/news/enpa-reacts-wikipedia-hostile-campaign-against-copyright|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/07/05/eu_copyright_vote/|title=European Parliament balks at copyright law reform vote|date=5 July 2018|work=The Register|access-date=4 September 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905065215/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/07/05/eu_copyright_vote/|archive-date=5 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> claiming that Wikipedia and other platforms engaged in \"{{Sic|inacceptable}} misleading campaigns [...] to influence MEPs\" and pointing out that Google spent {{\u20ac|4.5&nbsp;million}} lobbying in Europe during 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/transparencyregister/public/consultation/displaylobbyist.do?id=03181945560-59|title=Transparency Register: Google|website=[[Lobby register#European Union|EU Transparency Register]]|access-date=4 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704182929/http://ec.europa.eu/transparencyregister/public/consultation/displaylobbyist.do?id=03181945560-59|archive-date=4 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> is among the sponsors of the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]], another leading opponent,<ref name=\"Reg2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/06/20/eu_copyright_reform_article_11_13/|title=JURI's out, Euro copyright votes in: Whoa, did the EU just 'break the internet'?|date=20 June 2018|work=[[The Register]]|access-date=4 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140231/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/06/20/eu_copyright_reform_article_11_13/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>{{better source|date=July 2018}} and was seen asking its partners to lobby against the reform.<ref name=\":5\" /> These estimates have been called \"flawed\" and that how much Google has spent on lobbying on this issue is not possible to determine.<ref name=Corp2019/> These estimates were also released by the music industry as a press release just before the JURI voted.<ref name=Corp2019/>\n\nThe publishers argue that licensed content providers such as [[Spotify]] and [[Netflix]] are also negatively affected by the current copyright regime, which they say benefits user-driven platforms such as [[YouTube]] (owned by the parent company of Google) and [[Facebook]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://makeinternetfair.eu/en/node/18|title=About the transfer of value / value gap|date=31 January 2018|website=makeinternetfair.eu|publisher=[[European Grouping of Societies of Authors and Composers]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703151826/http://makeinternetfair.eu/en/node/18|archive-date=3 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref> They claim reports of [[spambot]]s flooding MEPs with so many anti-copyright emails that they can no longer carry out their work.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":9\" />\n\nWhile some publishers support the proposal, European Innovative Media Publishers, a publishing industry lobbying organisation, was founded in 2015 specifically to oppose Article 11.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://mediapublishers.eu/2017/12/27/small-publishers-take-neighbouring-right-out-of-eu-copyright-reform/|title=Our Op-ed as published in EurActiv: Small publishers: Take 'neighbouring right' out of EU copyright reform|website=mediapublishers.eu|accessdate=14 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614121753/http://mediapublishers.eu/2017/12/27/small-publishers-take-neighbouring-right-out-of-eu-copyright-reform/|archive-date=14 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Newspapers ===\nSome newspapers in support of the directive pejoratively label some of those opposed as \"the largest, richest corporate entities in the world\". In an editorial, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' stated that \"YouTube controls 60{{Nbsp}}per{{Nbsp}}cent of all streaming audio business, but pays only 11{{Nbsp}}per{{Nbsp}}cent of the revenues that artists receive\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/20a8d1e0-810a-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=The case for reforming the rules of copyright|date=6 July 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709010124/https://www.ft.com/content/20a8d1e0-810a-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref> Others newspapers focus on Article 11, arguing that the reform is a battle between European media pluralism and monopolistic foreign Internet giants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.humanite.fr/medias-defendre-le-pluralisme-en-europe-contre-les-geants-du-net-657096|title=M\u00e9dias. D\u00e9fendre le pluralisme en Europe contre les g\u00e9ants du Net\u2009!|date=20 June 2018|work=L'Humanit\u00e9|access-date=6 July 2018|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707005820/https://www.humanite.fr/medias-defendre-le-pluralisme-en-europe-contre-les-geants-du-net-657096|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liberation.fr/france/2018/06/18/l-europe-doit-defendre-les-medias-contre-la-loi-des-gafa_1660125|title=L\u2019Europe doit d\u00e9fendre les m\u00e9dias contre la&nbsp;loi des&nbsp;Gafa|work=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|access-date=6 July 2018|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707005938/http://www.liberation.fr/france/2018/06/18/l-europe-doit-defendre-les-medias-contre-la-loi-des-gafa_1660125|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A variety of mainstream newspapers have reported that some Internet platforms are lobbying against the bill to support their financial interests.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|title=YouTube and Facebook escape billions in copyright payouts after EU vote|last=Sweney|first=Mark|last2=Rankin|first2=Jennifer|date=5 July 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=5 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724094528/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/jul/05/youtube-could-escape-billions-in-copyright-payouts-after-eu-vote|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|title=MEPs reject EU copyright reforms in victory for internet giants|last=Khan|first=Mehreen|date=5 July 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234046/https://www.ft.com/content/bc235d20-803d-11e8-bc55-50daf11b720d|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=5 July 2018}}<br />{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-searches-for-way-round-eu-copyright-dmrjrgpx2|title=Google searches for way round EU copyright|last=Duke|first=Simon|date=1 July 2018|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=6 July 2018|language=en|issn=0956-1382|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707005833/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-searches-for-way-round-eu-copyright-dmrjrgpx2|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=live}}<br />{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-companies-win-reprieve-as-eu-parliament-delays-copyright-law-1530787465|title=Tech Companies Win Reprieve as EU Parliament Delays Copyright Law|last=Schechner|first=Sam|date=5 July 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=6 July 2018|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707005845/https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-companies-win-reprieve-as-eu-parliament-delays-copyright-law-1530787465|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=live}}<br />{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-07-06/tech-giants-win-against-media-companies-in-eu-copyright-battle|title=Tech Giants Are Stronger Than Paul McCartney|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=6 July 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917202029/https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-07-06/tech-giants-win-against-media-companies-in-eu-copyright-battle|archive-date=17 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA group of nine{{Nbsp}}major European press publishers including [[Agence France-Presse]], the [[Press Association]], and the [[European Alliance of News Agencies]] issued a letter supporting the proposal, describing it as \"key for the media industry, the consumer\u2019s future access to news, and ultimately a healthy democracy\". In the letter, they cite existing state support for struggling news media and argue that it should instead be provided by the \"internet giants\" which have been \"siphoning off\" advertising revenue.<ref name=\"9agencies\">{{cite web|url=https://images.derstandard.at/2017/12/14/brief.pdf|title=Letter by 9 news agencies|date=14 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208030217/https://images.derstandard.at/2017/12/14/brief.pdf|archive-date=8 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCritical accounts of the proposal were published in the summer of 2018 by major newspapers in Austria,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://derstandard.at/2000081976547/Heftige-Kritik-an-EU-Plaenen-Sterben-Internet-Memes-in-Europa|title=EU-Pl\u00e4ne f\u00fcr Uploadfilter k\u00f6nnten Todessto\u00df f\u00fcr Memes bedeuten \u2013 derStandard.at|website=DER STANDARD|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005254/https://derstandard.at/2000081976547/Heftige-Kritik-an-EU-Plaenen-Sterben-Internet-Memes-in-Europa|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> France,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/secteur/high-tech/2018/06/08/32001-20180608ARTFIG00290-un-projet-de-loi-europeen-pourrait-menacer-les-memes-sur-internet.php|title=Un projet de loi europ\u00e9en pourrait menacer les m\u00e8mes sur Internet|date=8 June 2018|newspaper=FIGARO|accessdate=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621185316/http://www.lefigaro.fr/secteur/high-tech/2018/06/08/32001-20180608ARTFIG00290-un-projet-de-loi-europeen-pourrait-menacer-les-memes-sur-internet.php|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Germany,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/upload-filter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-schroedingers-internet-a-1213496.html|title=Upload-Filter: Liebe Leserin, lieber Leser,|last=Beuth|first=Patrick|date=18 June 2018|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621231958/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/upload-filter-und-leistungsschutzrecht-schroedingers-internet-a-1213496.html|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/newsticker/dpa_nt/infoline_nt/netzwelt/article177859184/EU-Ausschuss-stimmt-fuer-Leistungsschutz-und-Uploadfilter.html|title=EU-Ausschuss stimmt f\u00fcr Leistungsschutz und Uploadfilter|last=WELT|date=20 June 2018|work=DIE WELT|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316142552/https://www.welt.de/newsticker/dpa_nt/infoline_nt/netzwelt/article177859184/EU-Ausschuss-stimmt-fuer-Leistungsschutz-und-Uploadfilter.html|archive-date=16 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/eu-s-attempt-at-internet-copyright-reform-is-a-ridiculous-own-goal-1.3538030|title=EU's attempt at internet copyright reform is a ridiculous own goal|work=The Irish Times|access-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621160023/https://www.irishtimes.com/business/eu-s-attempt-at-internet-copyright-reform-is-a-ridiculous-own-goal-1.3538030|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2018/06/20/economia/ombre-pi-che-luci-della-riforma-europea-del-copyright-ZqzmbTAGxPIxUJga2Ac1rJ/pagina.html|title=Ombre (pi\u00f9 che luci) della riforma europea del copyright|work=La Stampa|access-date=22 June 2018|language=it-IT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620193520/http://www.lastampa.it/2018/06/20/economia/ombre-pi-che-luci-della-riforma-europea-del-copyright-ZqzmbTAGxPIxUJga2Ac1rJ/pagina.html|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/mondo/2018-06-20/europa-stretta-copyright-arriva-tassa-link-e-meme-rischio-171942.shtml?uuid=AE6SSf9E|title=Europa, stretta sul copyright: arriva la tassa sui link (e meme a rischio)|work=Il Sole 24 ORE|access-date=22 June 2018|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623201332/http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/mondo/2018-06-20/europa-stretta-copyright-arriva-tassa-link-e-meme-rischio-171942.shtml?uuid=AE6SSf9E|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Poland,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tokfm.pl/Tokfm/7,130517,23572195,cenzura-internetu-i-podatek-od-linkowania-nowa-dyrektywa.html|title=B\u0119dzie cenzura internetu? Ekspertka: To mo\u017ce uderzy\u0107 nawet w przegl\u0105dy prasy i portale typu Wykop|work=tokfm|access-date=22 June 2018|language=pl-PL|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005148/http://www.tokfm.pl/Tokfm/7,130517,23572195,cenzura-internetu-i-podatek-od-linkowania-nowa-dyrektywa.html|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Spain,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/03/24/inenglish/1490355715_551697.html|title=Editorial {{!}} A digital agreement|last=Pa\u00eds|first=El|date=24 March 2017|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=22 June 2018|issn=1134-6582|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005012/https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/03/24/inenglish/1490355715_551697.html|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Slovakia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tech.sme.sk/c/20849608/bruselska-smernica-moze-uskodit-otvorenemu-a-slobodnemu-internetu.html|title=Bruselsk\u00e1 smernica m\u00f4\u017ee u\u0161kodi\u0165 otvoren\u00e9mu a slobodn\u00e9mu internetu|last=a.s.|first=Petit Press|work=tech.sme.sk|access-date=22 June 2018|language=sk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623005316/https://tech.sme.sk/c/20849608/bruselska-smernica-moze-uskodit-otvorenemu-a-slobodnemu-internetu.html|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Content creators===\nThe [[International Federation of Journalists]], a union, complained about late amendments which made remuneration of journalists dependent on \"contractual arrangements\" and \"laws on ownership\". While describing the proposals as \"an achievement for authors overall\" and \"good news for the industry and for authors in some sectors\", they described the amendments as \"bad for journalism and bad for Europe\" and called on the EU to \"decide wisely and reject any discriminatory provisions\".<ref name=\"IFJ2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ifj.org/media-centre/news/detail/category/authors-rights/article/new-copyright-directive-makes-a-mockery-of-journalists-authors-rights.html|title=New copyright directive makes a mockery of journalists' authors' rights|date=14 February 2019|website=[[International Federation of Journalists]]|access-date=14 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214220017/https://www.ifj.org/media-centre/news/detail/category/authors-rights/article/new-copyright-directive-makes-a-mockery-of-journalists-authors-rights.html|archive-date=14 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA representative from a company that makes content filters states that their wide introduction as while result from article 13 will likely hurt new music artists by limiting their ability to share what they create.<ref name=Fort2019Mar21/>\n\n===Prominent individuals===\nIndividuals who have publicly opposed the law include comedian [[Stephen Fry]]; author [[Neil Gaiman]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/pro/paul-mccartney-joins-celeb-lobbying-european-parliament-over-copyright-reform-vote/|title=Paul McCartney joins crowded fight over online rules|date=4 July 2018|publisher=[[Politico]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234208/https://www.politico.eu/pro/paul-mccartney-joins-celeb-lobbying-european-parliament-over-copyright-reform-vote/|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref> [[Tim Berners-Lee]], creator of the [[World Wide Web]]; and [[Vint Cerf]], co-inventor of the [[Internet protocol suite]].<ref name=\"BBC2018\" />\n\n=== Case law ===\nIn 2012, the [[European Court of Justice]] ruled that existing EU law \"must be interpreted as precluding a national court from issuing an injunction against a hosting service provider which requires it to install a system for filtering...with a view to preventing works from being made available to the public in breach of copyright\", arguing that such an injunction \"could potentially undermine freedom of information, since that system might not distinguish adequately between unlawful content and lawful content, with the result that its introduction could lead to the blocking of lawful communications\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://curia.europa.eu/juris/document/document.jsf?text=&docid=119512doclang=EN&cid=2283803|title=Belgische Vereniging van Auteurs, Componisten en Uitgevers CVBA (SABAM) v Netlog NV|date=16 February 2012|website=[[CURIA]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121204018/http://curia.europa.eu/juris/document/document.jsf?text=&docid=119512doclang=EN&cid=2283803|archive-date=21 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights ===\nThe [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] raised concerns that the proposal was incompatible with the 1966 [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]]. In a public letter, special rapporteur, [[David Kaye (law professor)|David Kaye]], argued that the proposal's reluctance to pin down precise obligations on content hosts created \"significant legal uncertainty\" inconsistent with the covenant's requirement that any restrictions on freedom of expression be \"provided by law\". He concluded that this could lead to \"pressure on content sharing providers to err on the side of caution\". Kaye also criticised the lack of \"prior judicial review\" inherent in the system, and the similarly extrajudicial nature of its appeals process.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Issues/Opinion/Legislation/OL-OTH-41-2018.pdf|title=European Union draft directive on copyright in the digital single market|author=Kaye|first=David|date=13 June 2018|publisher=[[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|UNHCHR]]|id=OL OTH 41/2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615004339/https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Issues/Opinion/Legislation/OL-OTH-41-2018.pdf|archive-date=15 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He acknowledges that while copyright law needs to be modernised in Europe it should not be done in a way that harms freedom of expression and that the current recommendations within article 13 are not needed.<ref name=Fort2019Mar21/>\n\nThe letter also raised concerns regarding the lack of protection for non-profit groups,<ref name=\"auto8\"/> although such groups had been excluded from the proposal's provisions prior to its publication.<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" />\n\n==Controversy==\n\n=== Articles 11 and 13 (15 and 17 as passed) ===\nArticles 11 and 13 of the draft Directive, prior to Trilogue negotiations and since moved to Articles 15 and 17 in the final, passed version, have drawn a great deal of attention and opposition. Article 11, referred to as the \"[[link tax]]\", generated concerns that less information and fewer resources would be available through search engines.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/05/business/eu-parliament-copyright.html | title = Tech Giants Win a Battle Over Copyright Rules in Europe | first = Adam | last = Satariano | date = 5 July 2018 | accessdate = 15 February 2019 | work = [[The New York Times]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190215220053/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/05/business/eu-parliament-copyright.html | archive-date = 15 February 2019 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In their explanatory memorandum for Article 11, the Council describes existing rights enforcement for the online use of press publications as \"complex and inefficient.\" They also draw particular attention to the use of news articles by \"news aggregators or media-monitoring services\" for commercial purposes, and the problems that would face press publishers in licensing their work to such services.<ref name=\"consilium_europa01\" /> After the European Commission analysed the implementation of similar laws in Germany and Spain, they found that newspapers actually benefited financially from the increased exposure to their online articles.<ref name=\"ECstudy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.asktheeu.org/en/request/4776/response/15356/attach/6/Doc1.pdf|title=Online News Aggregation and Neighbouring Rights for News Publishers|id=Ref. Ares(2017)6256585|year=2017|author=[[European Commission]] contractor|access-date=10 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305092801/https://www.asktheeu.org/en/request/4776/response/15356/attach/6/Doc1.pdf|archive-date=5 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"EPstudy\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/11/google-news-spain-to-close-in-response-to-tax-on-story-links|title=Google News Spain to close in response to story links 'tax'|last=Rushe|first=Dominic|date=11 December 2014|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=5 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721111326/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/11/google-news-spain-to-close-in-response-to-tax-on-story-links|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TechCrunch2018\">{{cite news |title=European MEPs vote to reopen copyright debate over \u2018censorship\u2019 controversy |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/07/05/european-meps-vote-to-reopen-copyright-debate-over-censorship-controversy/ |accessdate=5 July 2018 |work=TechCrunch |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705110341/https://techcrunch.com/2018/07/05/european-meps-vote-to-reopen-copyright-debate-over-censorship-controversy/ |archive-date=5 July 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nGermany (with the [[ancillary copyright for press publishers]] law) and Spain tested a link tax: it was considered a \"complete disaster\" which cost them millions of euros.<ref name=\"Fortune-1\" /> Google shut down [[Google News]] in Spain<ref name=\"Fortune-1\" /> and stopped using linked snippets of German articles completely.<ref name=\"Fortune-2\">[http://fortune.com/2018/06/26/google-eu-copyright-directive/ \"Google Is Being Criticized Over Its Copyright Stance In Europe. But the Company Is Right\"], ''Fortune'', 26 June 2018</ref> Experts predicted that such a link tax would lead to the Internet in Europe being more dominated by large media corporations, since it would be too time-consuming and costly for small online media companies to reach their own separate legal agreements to allow a link or quotes. As a result, they felt, many small media companies in Europe would eventually be forced to shut down due to a lack of online exposure and revenue.<ref name=\"Fortune-1\">[http://fortune.com/2016/03/24/eu-ancillary-copyright/ \"EU Lawmakers Are Still Considering This Failed Copyright Idea\"], ''Fortune'', 24 March 2016</ref>\n\nArticle 13, colloquially called the \"upload filter\" provision, has faced widespread criticism over the possibility that it could have a \"[[chilling effect]]\" on online expression, as it would force most web services to stop users uploading copyrighted content without authorization, or else the service would risk being held liable for infringements of its guidelines.<ref name=\"Fortune-3\">[http://fortune.com/2019/02/14/eu-copyright-directive-trilogue-deal/ \"Tech Industry and Activists Still Hope to Sink New EU Copyright Rules\"], ''Fortune'', 14 February 2019</ref> And although the article requires only \"best efforts\" from providers, larger companies would need to use expensive content-matching technology similar to [[YouTube]]'s [[Content ID (algorithm)|Content ID]] system, which cost Google about $100 million to develop.<ref name=\"Fortune-4\">[http://fortune.com/2019/03/26/eu-copyright-directive-google-news/ \"Google Once Cited EU's Copyright Reforms as a Business Risk. Now They're a Reality\"], ''Fortune'', 26 March 2019</ref><ref name=\"BBC2018Meme\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44546620|title='Disastrous' copyright bill vote approved|date=20 June 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180625111719/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44546620|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.axel-voss-europa.de/2018/06/18/stellungnahme-zur-reform-des-urheberrechts/|title=Europ\u00e4isches Urheberrecht|last=Voss|first=Axel|date=18 June 2018|website=www.axel-voss-europa.de|language=de-DE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234103/https://www.axel-voss-europa.de/2018/06/18/stellungnahme-zur-reform-des-urheberrechts/|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref> Others are concerned that due to the cost of filtering, only major U.S. technology firms would have sufficient resources to develop them, and that outsourcing the task by EU companies would then have privacy and data protection implications.<ref name=\"Rom20182\">{{cite journal|last1=Romero-Moreno|first1=Felipe|date=29 May 2018|title='Notice and staydown' and social media: amending Article 13 of the Proposed Directive on Copyright|journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology|pages=1\u201324|doi=10.1080/13600869.2018.1475906|hdl=2299/20431|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/eu/2018/06/19/the-eus-disastrous-copyright-reform-explained/|title=The EU's disastrous Copyright Reform, explained by its lovers and haters|last=Maack|first=M\u00e1r M\u00e1sson|date=19 June 2018|work=The Next Web|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180620124321/https://thenextweb.com/eu/2018/06/19/the-eus-disastrous-copyright-reform-explained/|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Rom2020\">{{cite journal |last=Romero-Moreno |first=Felipe |date=17 March 2020 |title='Upload filters' and human rights: implementing Article 17 of the Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market |journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology |pages=1\u201331 |doi-access=free |doi=10.1080/13600869.2020.1733760|issn=1360-0869 |hdl-access=free |hdl=2299/20431}}</ref>\n\nThe controversy over Article 13 has led Internet pioneers including [[Tim Berners-Lee]], [[Vint Cerf]], [[Jimmy Wales]], and [[Mitch Kapor]] to warn that \"Article 13 takes an unprecedented step towards the transformation of the Internet from an open platform for sharing and innovation, into a tool for the automated surveillance and control of its users.\"<ref name=\"EFF-letter\">[https://www.eff.org/files/2018/06/12/article13letter.pdf \"Article 13 of the EU Copyright Directive Threatens the Internet\"], letter to the President of the European Parliament, 12 June 2018</ref> [[Diego Naranjo]], senior policy adviser at the advocacy group [[European Digital Rights]], similarly warned that Article 13 \"sets a dangerous precedent for Internet filters and automated censorship mechanisms\u2014in the EU and across the globe.\"<ref name=\"Newstalk\">[https://www.newstalk.com/news/eu-controversial-copyright-841506 \"European Parliament approves controversial new copyright directive\"], ''Newstalk'', 26 March 2019</ref> The organisation said that \"online content filtering could be the end of the internet as we know it.\"<ref name=\"Newstalk\" />\n\nThe media lawyers Christian Solmecke and Anne-Christine Herr reported in their analysis of the negotiated compromise that it inherits the duty to use an upload filter because no other technique exists to fulfil the requirements of the law. They point out alternative solutions to extract enhanced license fees from an online provider without restricting the rights of private users by filtering all uploads\u2014i.e., by according [[private copying levy]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Christian Solmecke und Anne-Christine Herr |url=https://www.wbs-law.de/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Analyse-Artikel-13-Version-1.2-WILDE-BEUGER-SOLMECKE-Rechtsanw\u00e4lte.pdf|title=Rechtliche Analyse der Pro- und Contra Argumente zu Artikel 13 der geplanten EU Urheberrechtsnovelle|date=2019-03-19|accessdate=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nCritics have also noted the issue of [[False positives and false negatives|false positives]] within such systems, and their inability to account for copyright limitations such as [[fair dealing]] and [[parody]] (leading, they state, to a \"[[Internet meme|meme]] ban\").<ref name=\"CNET2018June22\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/article-13-europes-hotly-debated-eu-copyright-law-explained/|title=Everything you need to know about Europe's new meme-ending war|date=22 June 2018|accessdate=1 July 2018|website=CNET|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180624104448/https://www.cnet.com/news/article-13-europes-hotly-debated-eu-copyright-law-explained/|archive-date=24 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Supporters and third parties pointed out that YouTube has used Content ID for a decade and yet remains a successful host for content of all kinds.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://torrentfreak.com/censorship-machines-are-destroying-the-internet-as-we-speak-180624/|title=Censorship Machines are 'Destroying The Internet' As We Speak?|date=24 June 2018|work=TorrentFreak|access-date=23 July 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724032123/https://torrentfreak.com/censorship-machines-are-destroying-the-internet-as-we-speak-180624/|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the system still suffers from false positives, [[copyright trolls]], and scammers leveraging YouTube's handling of copyright claims under the U.S. [[Online Copyright Infringement Liability Limitation Act]] (OCILLA)\u2014a component of the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]] (DMCA)\u2014as a form of [[extortion]], by placing false copyright claims on a user's content until they pay a ransom (aiming to have the account taken down unless they pay), or [[doxxing]] by means of the requirement to include personal contact information when performing a counterclaim under this law.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wodinsky |first1=Shoshana |title=YouTube\u2019s copyright strikes have become a tool for extortion |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/11/18220032/youtube-copystrike-blackmail-three-strikes-copyright-violation |accessdate=20 February 2019 |work=The Verge |date=11 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220003031/https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/11/18220032/youtube-copystrike-blackmail-three-strikes-copyright-violation |archive-date=20 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe CEO of YouTube, [[Susan Wojcicki]], warned that the legislation \"poses a threat to both your livelihood and your ability to share your voice with the world\", and that under Article 13, the site may \u2014 even on content it does have a license to host \u2014 be required to clear every possible copyright associated with a video or be prevented from streaming it within the EU, and do the same at scale for every piece of video uploaded by users.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-warns-unintended-consequences-article-13-1202500444/|title=YouTube CEO Susan Wojcicki Warns Against \"Unintended Consequences\" Of EU's Article 13|last=Chmielewski|first=Dawn C.|last2=Chmielewski|first2=Dawn C.|date=12 November 2018|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043337/https://deadline.com/2018/11/youtube-ceo-susan-wojcicki-warns-unintended-consequences-article-13-1202500444/|archive-date=6 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The CEO of [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]], [[Emmett Shear]], has also criticised Article 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/video/2019/03/27/twitch-ceo-article-13/|title=Twitch CEO: Article 13 'Wrong Compromise' On Copyright Reform|last=Baran|first=Jonathan|date=2019-03-27|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\nAfter its passing, Pirate Party MEP [[Julia Reda]] pointed out that Article 13 may violate the Canada/EU [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA), which states that its parties must provide \"limitations or exceptions\" on the liability of intermediary communications service providers in regards to copyright infringement, and that they must not be \"conditioned on the service provider monitoring its service, or affirmatively seeking facts indicating infringing activity.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190412/07120341988/could-article-13s-upload-filters-be-thrown-out-because-eu-canada-trade-deal-ceta.shtml|title=Could Article 13's Upload Filters Be Thrown Out Because Of The EU-Canada Trade Deal CETA?|last=Moody|first=Moody|date=17 April 2019|website=Techdirt|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Public protests ===\n[[File:Protesto contra a reforma europeia do direito de autor, em especial os artigos 11 e 13, em Lisboa, Julho de 2018.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Public protests against article 11 and 13 in Lisbon in July 2018.]]\n[[File:Spontante Kundgebung in Hamburg gegen EU-Urheberrechtsvorhaben 3.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Protests in Hamburg on 6 March 2019 against the EU Copyright Directive]]\n\nA [[Change.org]] petition has gathered more than 5 million signatures {{As of|2019|March|21|lc=y|df=|since=}} which oppose the directive, of which roughly 1.3 million are from Germany.<ref name=Paper2019>{{cite news|url=http://paperjam.lu/news/le-choc-des-titans|title=Le choc des titans|date=31 January 2019|work=Paperjam News|language=fr|access-date=13 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213130908/http://paperjam.lu/news/le-choc-des-titans|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/wirtschaft/urherberrechtsreform-unterschriften-101.html |title=4,7 Millionen Unterschriften gegen Upload-Filter |website=[[Tagesschau (Germany)|Tagesschau]] |language=de |date=18 February 2019 |access-date=18 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218205526/https://www.tagesschau.de/wirtschaft/urherberrechtsreform-unterschriften-101.html |archive-date=18 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=Fort2019Mar21/> As of February 2019, it has gathered the most signatures in European history.<ref name=EFF2019Feb>{{cite web |last1=Doctorow |first1=Cory |title=The Worst Possible Version of the EU Copyright Directive Has Sparked a German Uprising |url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/02/worst-possible-version-eu-copyright-directive-has-sparked-german-uprising |website=Electronic Frontier Foundation |accessdate=24 February 2019 |language=en |date=18 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223233833/https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/02/worst-possible-version-eu-copyright-directive-has-sparked-german-uprising |archive-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nA number of public protests have been held in opposition to the proposed directive, mainly concerning Article 11 and 13. European wide protests on 23 March 2019 saw tens to hundreds of thousands of people marching.<ref name=\"Simon2019\">{{cite news |last1=Berlin |first1=Simon Hurtz |title=Dieser Protest k\u00f6nnte Artikel 13 stoppen |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/digital/upload-filter-urheberrecht-demo-berlin-1.4380487 |accessdate=23 March 2019 |work=sueddeutsche.de |date=2019 |language=de}}</ref> One estimate put the number at 40,000 people in Munich and 15,000 in Berlin.<ref name=\"ProtestsMar23\">{{cite news |last1=Welle (www.dw.com) |first1=Deutsche |title=EU copyright bill: Protests across Europe highlight rifts over reform plans {{!}} DW {{!}} 23 March 2019 |url=https://www.dw.com/en/eu-copyright-bill-protests-across-europe-highlight-rifts-over-reform-plans/a-48037133 |accessdate=23 March 2019 |work=DW.COM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323224602/https://www.dw.com/en/eu-copyright-bill-protests-across-europe-highlight-rifts-over-reform-plans/a-48037133 |archive-date=23 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Another estimate indicated 30,000 people in Berlin and more than 100,000 in Germany overall.<ref name=Simon2019/> A 16 February 2019 protest organised by German YouTube stars in [[Cologne]] attracted a significant crowd despite having only been announced two days earlier. German news media gave reports of attendance, with one report describing \"several hundred participants\", another \"over 1000\", and a third \"1500\" based on police reports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tag24.de/nachrichten/youtube-artikel-13-urheberrecht-zensur-demo-protest-in-koeln-975131|title=Was ist Artikel 13? Warum deutsche YouTube-Stars heute in K\u00f6ln auf die Barrikaden gehen|publisher=[[:de:TAG24|TAG24 NEWS]]|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220064211/https://www.tag24.de/nachrichten/youtube-artikel-13-urheberrecht-zensur-demo-protest-in-koeln-975131|archive-date=20 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=19 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Wir-sind-die-Bots-ueber-1000-demonstrieren-gegen-Artikel-13-4311105.html|title=\"Wir sind die Bots\" \u2013 \u00fcber 1000 demonstrieren gegen Artikel 13|date=16 February 2019|website=[[Heise Online]]|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217162603/https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Wir-sind-die-Bots-ueber-1000-demonstrieren-gegen-Artikel-13-4311105.html|archive-date=17 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Bla2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/diginomics/tausende-menschen-demonstrieren-gegen-urheberrechtsreform-16045816.html|title=\"Ich bin kein Bot\": Tausende Menschen protestieren gegen Urheberrechtsreform|last1=Blazekovic|first1=Jessica von|work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]|date=17 February 2019|accessdate=20 February 2019|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220103450/https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/diginomics/tausende-menschen-demonstrieren-gegen-urheberrechtsreform-16045816.html|archive-date=20 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A second protest in Cologne on 23 February 2019 had a reported attendance of more than 3000.<ref name=Hei2019>{{cite web |url=https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Dieser-Bot-geht-waehlen-3000-demonstrieren-in-Koeln-gegen-Urheberrechtsreform-4316858.html |title=\"Dieser Bot geht w\u00e4hlen\" \u2013 3000 demonstrieren in K\u00f6ln gegen Urheberrechtsreform |website=[[Heise Online]] |date=23 February 2019 |access-date=23 February 2019 |last=Kleinz |first=Torsten |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224062536/https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Dieser-Bot-geht-waehlen-3000-demonstrieren-in-Koeln-gegen-Urheberrechtsreform-4316858.html |archive-date=24 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Demonstrators attributed problems of the bill to Axel Voss and the CDU party.<ref name=Hei2019/> A protest in Berlin on 2 March attracted roughly 3,500.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.zdf.de/nachrichten/heute/tausende-menschen-demonstrieren-gegen-uploadfilter-100.html |title=Demo gegen Urheberrechtsreform - Tausende wehren sich gegen Artikel 13 |date=2 March 2019 |access-date=2 March 2019 |work=[[ZDF]] |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303124652/https://www.zdf.de/nachrichten/heute/tausende-menschen-demonstrieren-gegen-uploadfilter-100.html |archive-date=3 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The protests are being organised by a grassroots movement and are raising funds by [[Gofundme]].<ref name=Hei2019/>\n\nAfter the [[European People's Party]] tried to move the vote on the directive ahead to circumvent the planned protests on 23 March 2019,<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1102951601663369217|user=Senficon|title=Here is written proof that @EPPGroup tried to move the vote on #copyright & #Article13 ahead to next week. Apparently they're denying it now, so either your public outcry impressed them, or they figured out that the translations won't be ready in time. #SaveYourInternet [Repost]|author=Julia Reda|date=5 March 2019|author-link=Julia Reda|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Beuth |first1=Ein Kommentar Patrick |title=EU-Urheberrechtsreform: Der Zorn der \u00dcbergangenen |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/posse-um-urheberrechtsreform-die-evp-hat-sich-die-wut-der-buerger-verdient-a-1256412.html |accessdate=8 March 2019 |work=Spiegel Online |date=5 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308001125/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/posse-um-urheberrechtsreform-die-evp-hat-sich-die-wut-der-buerger-verdient-a-1256412.html |archive-date=8 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> demonstrations were organised at short notice in ten German cities, including Berlin, between 5 and 9 March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://savetheinternet.info/demos |title=Demos |website=Savetheinternet.info |access-date=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306042952/https://savetheinternet.info/demos |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Following public protests, the European People's Party claimed that they did not try to move the vote forwards despite evidence to the contrary.<ref>{{cite web |title=UPDATED! How do you pass the most unpopular measure in European history? With the most undemocratic dirty trick in EU history: stop the #Article13 vote from being moved ahead of day of protest! |url=https://boingboing.net/2019/03/04/march-23-march.html |website=Boing Boing |accessdate=8 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305144704/https://boingboing.net/2019/03/04/march-23-march.html |archive-date=5 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=Tech2019Mar5>{{cite web |title=Supporters Of Article 13 Briefly Tried To Move Parliament Vote Up Before Scheduled Protests; Now Deny Plan That They Clearly Had |url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190304/15233741731/supporters-article-13-briefly-tried-to-move-parliament-vote-up-before-scheduled-protests-now-deny-plan-that-they-clearly-had.shtml |website=Techdirt. |accessdate=8 March 2019 |date=5 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308224100/https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190304/15233741731/supporters-article-13-briefly-tried-to-move-parliament-vote-up-before-scheduled-protests-now-deny-plan-that-they-clearly-had.shtml |archive-date=8 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Additionally, the request to move the vote forwards may not have been withdrawn as of 5 March 2019.<ref name=Tech2019Mar5/>\n\nSmaller prior EU-wide events occurred in August 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://juliareda.eu/2018/08/saveyourinternet-action-day/|title=People are taking to the streets on August 26th to #SaveYourInternet \u2013 join in!|last=Reda|first=Julia|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021334/https://juliareda.eu/2018/08/saveyourinternet-action-day/|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref> and January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stopacta2.org/stopacta2-events/|title=#stopACTA2 events|date=24 August 2018|website=stop ACTA2 - Save Your Internet|language=en-US|access-date=15 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115182153/https://www.stopacta2.org/stopacta2-events/|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Organisers did not release their own figures, but supporters of the proposals based on photos from the August events estimated that there had been at most 800 participants across the continent, with an average of 30 per location.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webschauder.de/astroturf-instead-of-grass-roots-when-clicktivism-meets-hard-reality/|title=Astroturf instead of grass roots: When clicktivism meets hard reality|website=WebSchauder|language=de-DE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218081933/http://webschauder.de/astroturf-instead-of-grass-roots-when-clicktivism-meets-hard-reality/|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral European websites, including the European versions of [[Wikipedia]], [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]], and [[Reddit]], disabled some or many of the features on their websites on 21 March 2019 as a means to protest and raise awareness of the pending vote and encourage users to contact their appropriate national body to affect the vote. This was similar to action taken on 18 January 2012 by numerous websites to [[Protests against SOPA and PIPA|protest similar laws proposed in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/21/18275462/eu-copyright-directive-protest-wikipedia-twitch-pornhub-final-vote | title = European Wikipedias have been turned off for the day to protest dangerous copyright laws | first = James | last = Vincent | date = 21 March 2019 | accessdate = 21 March 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190321125952/https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/21/18275462/eu-copyright-directive-protest-wikipedia-twitch-pornhub-final-vote | archive-date = 21 March 2019 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Lobbying ===\nThe [[European Parliament]] claimed that \"MEPs have rarely or even never been subject to a similar degree of lobbying\", and that there have been prior \"lobbying campaigns predicting catastrophic outcomes, which have never come true\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20190111IPR23225/questions-and-answers-on-issues-about-the-digital-copyright-directive|title=Questions and Answers on issues about the digital copyright directive|date=1 November 2019|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021421/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20190111IPR23225/questions-and-answers-on-issues-about-the-digital-copyright-directive|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' reported that \"Google is helping to fund a website that encourages people to spam politicians and newspapers with automated messages backing its policy goals\".<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-funds-activist-site-that-pushes-its-views-rg2g5cr6t|title=Google funds website that spams for its causes|last=Media&nbsp;Correspondent|first=Matthew Moore|date=6 August 2018|work=The Times|access-date=10 August 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810214845/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/google-funds-activist-site-that-pushes-its-views-rg2g5cr6t|archive-date=10 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> MEP [[Sven Schulze]] stated that he believed Google to be behind the email campaign because many of the emails came from [[Gmail]] addresses.<ref name=Bla2019/>\n\nLobbying in favour of the proposed directive was directed toward the EU itself and was much less visible to the public. The large media groups and publishers have had much greater contact between their [[lobbyists]] and MEPs than the technology industry.<ref name=Corp2019/> Stunts pulled by those lobbying in favour include sending MEPs pamphlets with condoms attached with the phrase \u201cWe love tech giants, we love protection too\u201d.<ref name=\"Corp2019\" />\n\nThe [[EU Commission]], in a since withdrawn [[blog post]], stated that those who opposed the directive were a \"mob\".<ref name=Ind2019>{{cite news |title=EU takes down strange, 'offensive' blog post attacking internet campaigners |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/eu-copyright-rules-blog-post-commission-article-11-13-latest-a8786256.html |accessdate=24 February 2019 |work=The Independent |date=19 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224183452/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/eu-copyright-rules-blog-post-commission-article-11-13-latest-a8786256.html |archive-date=24 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/streit-ueber-artikel-13-wer-braucht-schon-argumente-a-1255608.html |title=Streit \u00fcber Artikel 13: Wer braucht schon Argumente? |newspaper=[[Spiegel Online]] |last=Beuth |first=Patrick |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228184545/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/streit-ueber-artikel-13-wer-braucht-schon-argumente-a-1255608.html |archive-date=28 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The [[Commissioners]] technically responsible for such posts, [[Mariya Gabriel]] and [[Andrus Ansip]], both deny authorizing its publication.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schmihing |first1=Carina |title=Youtuber: Wie sich PietSmiet, RobBubble und Co. gegen Artikel 13 wehren |url=https://www.nw.de/blogs/games_und_netzwelt/22385030_Youtuber-Wie-sich-PietSmiet-RobBubble-und-Co.-gegen-Artikel-13-wehren.html |website=Games & Netzwelt |accessdate=24 February 2019 |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224062438/https://www.nw.de/blogs/games_und_netzwelt/22385030_Youtuber-Wie-sich-PietSmiet-RobBubble-und-Co.-gegen-Artikel-13-wehren.html |archive-date=24 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The European Commission has also apologized for its publication.<ref name=Ind2019/> [[Jean-Claude Juncker]], the head of the [[EU Commission]] declined after a direct request to answer who authorized its publication.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Masnick |first1=Mike |title=EU Commission Refuses To Explain Why It Published Medium Article Mocking The Public's Concerns Over Article 13 |url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190321/16154741848/eu-commission-refuses-to-explain-why-it-published-medium-article-mocking-publics-concerns-over-article-13.shtml |website=Techdirt. |accessdate=23 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322230758/https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190321/16154741848/eu-commission-refuses-to-explain-why-it-published-medium-article-mocking-publics-concerns-over-article-13.shtml |archive-date=22 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nSome commentators stated years of intense lobbying served to \"crowd out other voices and successfully distort the public debate\", and that \"toxic\" discussions were harming \"healthy dialogue\".<ref name=\"Corp2019\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/copyright-platforms-eu-google-winners-and-losers-of-europes-copyright-reform/|title=Winners and losers of Europe's copyright reform|last=Kayali|first=Laura|date=14 February 2019|website=POLITICO|access-date=17 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021415/https://www.politico.eu/article/copyright-platforms-eu-google-winners-and-losers-of-europes-copyright-reform/|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Those in support of the directive, however, carried out negotiations without public oversight.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Doctorow |first1=Cory |title=That German-French Deal to \"Rescue\" the EU Copyright Directive? Everyone Hates It. EVERYONE. |url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/02/german-french-deal-rescue-eu-copyright-directive-everyone-hates-it-everyone |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=Electronic Frontier Foundation |date=7 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320092740/https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/02/german-french-deal-rescue-eu-copyright-directive-everyone-hates-it-everyone |archive-date=20 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> And when the general public became involved in discussing the directive online the EU commission referred to them as a \"mob\".<ref>{{cite news |title=EU takes down strange, 'offensive' blog post attacking internet campaigners |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/eu-copyright-rules-blog-post-commission-article-11-13-latest-a8786256.html |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=The Independent |date=19 February 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316142612/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/eu-copyright-rules-blog-post-commission-article-11-13-latest-a8786256.html |archive-date=16 March 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n=== Voting issues ===\nBefore the vote on the directive, a vote was held on whether to consider amendments, which would have allowed the possibility of separating Articles 11 and 13 into separate votes. The proposal fell short by 5 votes. It was reported after the fact that 13 MEPs had requested that their votes be changed, since they voted incorrectly due to alleged confusion over the order of voting. The revised results added 10 votes in favour of amendments. However, these corrections are strictly for parliamentary records only, and do not change the result of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/mar/27/mep-errors-mean-european-copyright-law-may-not-have-passed|title=MEPs accidentally vote wrong way on copyright law|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=2019-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/button-pushing-errors-affected-copyright-reform-vote-record-shows/|title=Button-pushing errors affected copyright reform vote, record shows|last=Vinocur|first=Nicholas|date=2019-03-27|website=Politico.eu|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190326/15193241877/enough-meps-say-they-mistakenly-voted-articles-11-13-that-vote-should-have-flipped-eu-parliament-says-too-bad.shtml|title=Enough MEPs Say They Mistakenly Voted For Articles 11 & 13 That The Vote Should Have Flipped; EU Parliament Says Too Bad|first=Mike|last=Masnick|website=Techdirt|date=26 March 2019|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Bomb threat ===\nAccording to German media reports, an online bomb threat was posted against Axel Voss' office in [[Bonn]] claiming that a bomb had been placed at the office, and it would be detonated should the EU Parliament vote to back the proposed copyright reforms. The message had originally been posted on an obscure Finnish Linux Forum, before being brought to wider attention on [[Reddit]]. It has since been removed while an investigation by regional police was initiated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/digital/news/copyright-mep-in-bomb-threat-scare/|title=Copyright MEP in bomb threat scare|first=Samuel|last=Stolton|date=19 March 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom position ===\nOn 31 January 2020, the United Kingdom left the European Union. The [[transition period]] is scheduled to expire on 31 December 2020. The UK Government has therefore declared that, since the date for EU member states to transpose the directive into national law is in 2021, the UK will not be implementing the copyright directive in full.  Government minister [[Chris Skidmore]] stated that \n{{quote|\"The deadline for implementing the EU Copyright Directive is 7 June 2021. The United Kingdom will leave the European Union on 31 January 2020 and the Implementation Period will end on 31 December 2020. The Government has committed not to extend the Implementation Period. Therefore, the United Kingdom will not be required to implement the Directive, and the Government has no plans to do so. Any future changes to the UK copyright framework will be considered as part of the usual domestic policy process.\"<ref name =Bird />}} \nUK Culture Minister [[Nigel Adams]] said that, despite the Government supporting many of the overall aims of the directive, the UK\u2019s 'imminent departure from the EU means we are not required to implement the Copyright Directive in full'.<ref name =Bird>{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=7cbde598-9ca2-421b-8bc3-eee4a836bb1e | title = UK Government \u201chas no plans\u201d to implement the Copyright Directive |publisher= Bird & Bird LLP | author =William Wortley| date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Legal challenge ==\nOn 24 May 2019, [[Poland]] filed an action for annulment of the Directive with the [[Court of Justice of the European Union]].<ref name=\":19\"/> [[Foreign minister|Deputy Foreign Minister]] of Poland Konrad Szymanski said the directive \"may result in adopting regulations that are analogous to preventive censorship, which is forbidden not only in the [[Constitution of Poland|Polish constitution]] but also in the EU treaties\" on [[public broadcaster]] [[TVP Info]].<ref name=\":19\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-copyright-poland-idUSKCN1SU0T9|title=Poland files complaint with EU's top court over copyright rule change|date=2019-05-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-05-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Impact on media ==\nIn November 2019, [[News Media Alliance]] published an analysis of traffic received by eight Spanish websites whose news articles had been redistributed by Google News until it ceased operations in 2014 in response to a similar regulation introduced by Spanish lawmakers. Alliance data covering the period from 2014-2019 has demonstrated that publishers have not only continued the same amount of unique views with or without Google News, but also the amount of traffic has increased in some cases, especially the most valuable direct traffic as compared to less profitable referral traffic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsmediaalliance.org/google-news-shutdown-in-spain-not-as-bad-as-google-would-have-you-believe/|title=Google News Shutdown in Spain Was Not as Bad as Google Would Have You Believe|last=Munter|first=Johannes|date=2019-11-14|website=News Media Alliance|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Copyright law of the European Union]]\n* [[Copyright Directive (disambiguation)]] (lists the EU directives on copyright)\n* [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]] of 1998 (\"updates but does not replace the 11 directives which together comprise the EU\u2019s copyright legislation.\")\n* [[Electronic Commerce Directive 2000|Electronic Commerce Directive]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last=Romero-Moreno |first=Felipe |date=29 May 2018 |title='Notice and staydown' and social media: amending Article 13 of the Proposed Directive on Copyright |journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology |pages=1\u201324 |doi-access=free |doi=10.1080/13600869.2018.1475906 |issn=1360-0869 |hdl-access=free |hdl=2299/20431}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Romero-Moreno |first=Felipe |date=17 March 2020 |title='Upload filters' and human rights: implementing Article 17 of the Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market |journal=International Review of Law, Computers & Technology |pages=1\u201331 |doi-access=free |doi=10.1080/13600869.2020.1733760|issn=1360-0869 |hdl-access=free |hdl=2299/20431}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{cite web |title=Final text of the Directive as submitted to the Parliament on 26 March 2019|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf |accessdate=26 March 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://fixcopyright.wikimedia.org/?title=Fix_copyright&uselang=en|title=Wikimedia Public Policy: It's time for an update. Tell the European Parliament to fix copyright.|access-date=11 Sep 2018|language=en|quotation=On 12 September, the European Parliament will vote on changes to a copyright law that will dictate how we communicate in the digital age}} (translated in 24 languages)\n* [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/oeil/popups/ficheprocedure.do?lang=&reference=2016/0280(COD) Procedure file]\n*{{URL|http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf|The text of the European Council proposal as of 3 March 2019}}\n*{{URL|http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35373/st09134-en18.pdf|The text of the European Council proposal as of 25 May 2018}}\n*{{URL|1=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?type=REPORT&mode=XML&reference=A8-2018-0245&language=EN|2=The text of European Parliament Committee on Legal Affairs's proposed negotiating position}}\n*{{URL|https://edri.org/copyright-reform-document-pool/|Copyright reform document pool}}\n*{{URL|https://petiport.secure.europarl.europa.eu/petitions/en/petition/content/0424%252F2018/html/Petition-No-0424%252F2018-by-P.-Z.-%2528Polish%2529-on-deleting-Article-11-and-Article-13-from-the-draft-Directive-on-Copyright-in-the-Digital-Single-Market | Petition against Artikel 11 and 13}} on the Petitions Web Portal of the [[European Parliament Committee on Petitions]]\n\n{{Intellectual property laws of the European Union}}\n{{Portal bar|European Union|Law|Technology|Internet|Politics}}\n\n[[Category:Copyright legislation]]\n[[Category:European Single Market| ]]\n[[Category:Economy of the European Union]]\n[[Category:European Union telecommunications policy]]\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n[[Category:Copyright law of the European Union]]\n[[Category:European Union directives]]\n[[Category:2019 controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Brainulator9", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:cite fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Directive_on_Copyright_in_the_Digital_Single_Market"}
